{"title_page": "Jennifer Mnookin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox academic|name=Jennifer L. Mnookin|image=|occupation=Dean, UCLA School of Law|period=2015 - Present\n\nUCLA Law faculty, 2005 - Present\n\nUniversity of Virginia School of Law faculty, 1998 - 2005|education=J.D., Yale Law School\n\nPh.D., Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n\nA.B., Harvard University|discipline=Evidence, Science an Technology}}\n\n'''Jennifer L. Mnookin''' is the Dean of [[UCLA School of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/jennifer-l-mnookin/|title=Biography Page|website=law.ucla.edu|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She is also the David G. Price and Dallas P. Price Professor of Law and the founding co-director of UCLA Law's Program on Understanding Law, Science and Evidence (PULSE@UCLA Law).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.ucla.edu/centers/interdisciplinary-studies/pulse/about/#!|title=About the Program on Understanding Law, Science, and Evidence|website=www.law.ucla.edu|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She is an expert on evidence law, and has co-authored books, written articles and published op-eds on the subjects of expert and scientific evidence. On June 4, 2015, Mnookin was named the ninth dean in the history of UCLA School of Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/jennifer-mnookin-named-new-dean-of-ucla-school-of-law|title=Jennifer Mnookin named new dean of UCLA School of Law|last=Hampton|first=Phil|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> On April 23, 2020, she was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amacad.org/2020-member-announcement |title=New 2020 Members Announced |publisher=American Academy of Arts & Sciences |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nMnookin was born in 1967 in Cambridge, Massachusetts, and is the daughter of [[Robert Mnookin]], the Samuel Williston Professor of Law at [[Harvard Law School]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert H. Mnookin|url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/faculty/directory/10592/Mnookin|publisher=Harvard Law School|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>  and Dale Mnookin. She grew up in Berkeley and Palo Alto, California, and attended [[Harvard College]], where she earned her A.B. in 1988 and was an editor for [[The Harvard Crimson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congratulations, Crimson Class of '88, And Good Luck|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1988/6/9/congratulations-crimson-class-of-88-and/|publisher=The Harvard Crimson|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> She received her J.D. from [[Yale Law School]] in 1995 and holds a Ph.D. in the History and Sociology of Science and Technology from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"uclabio\">{{cite web|title=Biography Page|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/jennifer-l-mnookin/|website=law.ucla.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nMnookin joined the faculty of the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] in 1998. In 2002-03 she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard Law School.]] She joined the faculty of UCLA School of Law in 2005. Mnookin served as Vice Dean for Faculty and Research (2007\u201309) and as Vice Dean for External Appointments and Intellectual Life (2012\u201313) before being named dean.\n\nHer scholarship focuses on the interconnections between evidence, science and technology, and legal and cultural ideas about proof and persuasion. She has written on topics ranging from the history of photographic evidence to the complexities of the [[Confrontation Clause]] of the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] with respect to expert evidence. She is a co-author of ''The New Wigmore, A Treatise on Evidence: Expert Evidence,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lrus.wolterskluwer.com/store/product/the-new-wigmore-a-treatise-on-evidence-expert-evidence-second-edition/|title=The New Wigmore: A Treatise on Evidence - Expert Evidence, Second Edition {{!}} Wolters Kluwer Legal & Regulatory|website=Wolters Kluwer Legal & Regulatory|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> and ''Modern Scientific Evidence: The Law and Science of Expert Testimony''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legalsolutions.thomsonreuters.com/law-products/Treatises/Modern-Scientific-Evidence-The-Law-and-Science-of-Expert-Testimony-2017-2018-ed/p/105057698|title=Modern Scientific Evidence: The Law and... {{!}} Legal Solutions|last=Reuters|first=Thomson|website=legalsolutions.thomsonreuters.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> Much of her work has focused on the problems of forensic science evidence, especially pattern identification evidence like latent fingerprint identification.<ref name=\"uclabio\"/> She has frequently commented to the press on forensic science and evidence issues<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real CSI|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/criminal-justice/real-csi/transcript-18/|publisher=Public Broadcasting System|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=The Achilles' Heel of Fingerprints|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A64711-2004May28.html|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=The 'West Memphis Three' and combating cognitive biases|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/23/opinion/la-oe-mnookin-west-memphis-three-rele20110823|publisher=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=Clueless 'science'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/19/opinion/oe-mnookin19|publisher=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Russell |first=Sue |title=Bias and the Big Fingerprint Dust-Up |url=https://psmag.com/news/bias-and-the-big-fingerprint-dust-up-3629 |publisher=Pacific Standard |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202124711/https://psmag.com/news/bias-and-the-big-fingerprint-dust-up-3629 |archivedate=February 2, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Steinhauer|first=Jennifer|title=\u2018Grim Sleeper\u2019 Arrest Fans Debate on DNA Use|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09sleeper.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=mnookin&st=cse|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Liptak|first=Adam|title=In U.S., Expert Witnesses Are Partisan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/12/us/12experts.html?pagewanted=print|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/a-wake-up-call-on-the-junk-science-infesting-our-courtrooms/2016/09/19/85b6eb22-7e90-11e6-8d13-d7c704ef9fd9_story.html|title=A wake-up call on the junk science infesting our courtrooms|last=Edwards|first=Harry T.|date=2016-09-20|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-24|last2=Mnookin|first2=Jennifer L.|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> and has occasionally consulted or served as an expert witness on the scientific foundation of fingerprint evidence.<ref>{{cite web|title=United States of America v. Raynard Council|url=http://www.swgfast.org/Resources/110507_JudgeSpencerOpinion.pdf|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer scholarship on [[forensic science]] was cited extensively by the [[National Academy of Sciences]]' 2009 report.<ref>{{cite web|title=Strengthening Forensic Science in the United States|url=http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12589|publisher=The National Academies Press|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> She is a former member of the National Academy of Science's Committee on Science, Technology and the Law<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sites.nationalacademies.org/PGA/stl/PGA_049554|title=COMMITTEE MEMBERS|last=PGA|website=sites.nationalacademies.org|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> and is on the advisory board of the [[Electronic Privacy Information Center.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epic.org/epic/advisory_board.html|title=EPIC - EPIC Advisory Board|last=Center|first=Electronic Privacy Information|website=epic.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She was the primary investigator for a National Institute of Justice project that sought to develop objective metrics for measuring the difficulty of fingerprint comparisons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/two-ucla-professors-awarded-national-153642|title=UCLA professors awarded major federal grant to study error rates in fingerprint evidence|last=Gavel|first=Lauri|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> Her work on the Confrontation Clause was cited and discussed by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] in ''Williams v. Illinois'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams v. Illinois|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=14525729923225817611&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> In 2016, she co-chaired an advisory group to the President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology, which issued a report on the reliability of forensic science used in the courtroom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/PCAST/pcast_forensic_science_report_final.pdf|title=Report to the President: Forensic Science in Criminal Courts}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/q-a-with-jennifer-mnookin:-raising-the-bar-for-scientific-evidence-in-court|title=Q&A with Jennifer Mnookin: Raising the bar for scientific evidence in court|last=Kisliuk|first=Bill|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as a law school administrator, Mnookin is a former member of the steering committee of the [[Association of American Law Schools]]' Dean's Forum. Mnookin was named a member of the American Law Institute, a leading organization dedicated to improving and modernizing the law, in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ali.org/members/member/369001/|title=Members {{!}} American Law Institute|last=Institute|first=The American Law|website=American Law Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nMnookin is married to Joshua Foa Dienstag,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/29/style/weddings-jennifer-mnookin-joshua-dienstag.html|title=WEDDINGS; Jennifer Mnookin, Joshua Dienstag|date=1994-05-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> a professor of political science and law at UCLA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/joshua-foa-dienstag/|title=Joshua Foa Dienstag|publisher=UCLA Department of Political Science|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417125421/http://www.polisci.ucla.edu/people/faculty-pages/joshua-foa-dienstag|archivedate=April 17, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> They have two children, Sophia and Isaac.<ref>https://www.uclalawreview.org/reflections-on-law-teaching-2/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mnookin, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American legal writers]]\n[[Category:Legal educators]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox academic|name=Jennifer L. Mnookin|image=|occupation=Dean, UCLA School of Law|period=2015 - Present\n\nUCLA Law faculty, 2005 - Present\n\nUniversity of Virginia School of Law faculty, 1998 - 2005|education=J.D., Yale Law School\n\nPh.D., Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n\nA.B., Harvard University|discipline=Evidence, Science an Technology}}\n\n'''Jennifer L. Mnookin''' is the Dean of [[UCLA School of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/jennifer-l-mnookin/|title=Biography Page|website=law.ucla.edu|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She is also the David G. Price and Dallas P. Price Professor of Law and the founding co-director of UCLA Law's Program on Understanding Law, Science and Evidence (PULSE@UCLA Law).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.ucla.edu/centers/interdisciplinary-studies/pulse/about/#!|title=About the Program on Understanding Law, Science, and Evidence|website=www.law.ucla.edu|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She is an expert on evidence law, and has co-authored books, written articles and published op-eds on the subjects of expert and scientific evidence. On June 4, 2015, Mnookin was named the ninth dean in the history of UCLA School of Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/jennifer-mnookin-named-new-dean-of-ucla-school-of-law|title=Jennifer Mnookin named new dean of UCLA School of Law|last=Hampton|first=Phil|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> On April 23, 2020, she was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://https://www.amacad.org/2020-member-announcement</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nMnookin was born in 1967 in Cambridge, Massachusetts, and is the daughter of [[Robert Mnookin]], the Samuel Williston Professor of Law at [[Harvard Law School]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert H. Mnookin|url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/faculty/directory/10592/Mnookin|publisher=Harvard Law School|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>  and Dale Mnookin. She grew up in Berkeley and Palo Alto, California, and attended [[Harvard College]], where she earned her A.B. in 1988 and was an editor for [[The Harvard Crimson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congratulations, Crimson Class of '88, And Good Luck|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1988/6/9/congratulations-crimson-class-of-88-and/|publisher=The Harvard Crimson|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> She received her J.D. from [[Yale Law School]] in 1995 and holds a Ph.D. in the History and Sociology of Science and Technology from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"uclabio\">{{cite web|title=Biography Page|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/jennifer-l-mnookin/|website=law.ucla.edu}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nMnookin joined the faculty of the [[University of Virginia School of Law]] in 1998. In 2002-03 she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard Law School.]] She joined the faculty of UCLA School of Law in 2005. Mnookin served as Vice Dean for Faculty and Research (2007-09) and as Vice Dean for External Appointments and Intellectual Life (2012-13) before being named dean.\n\nHer scholarship focuses on the interconnections between evidence, science and technology, and legal and cultural ideas about proof and persuasion. She has written on topics ranging from the history of photographic evidence to the complexities of the [[Confrontation Clause]] of the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] with respect to expert evidence. She is a co-author of ''The New Wigmore, A Treatise on Evidence: Expert Evidence,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lrus.wolterskluwer.com/store/product/the-new-wigmore-a-treatise-on-evidence-expert-evidence-second-edition/|title=The New Wigmore: A Treatise on Evidence - Expert Evidence, Second Edition {{!}} Wolters Kluwer Legal & Regulatory|website=Wolters Kluwer Legal & Regulatory|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> and ''Modern Scientific Evidence: The Law and Science of Expert Testimony''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legalsolutions.thomsonreuters.com/law-products/Treatises/Modern-Scientific-Evidence-The-Law-and-Science-of-Expert-Testimony-2017-2018-ed/p/105057698|title=Modern Scientific Evidence: The Law and... {{!}} Legal Solutions|last=Reuters|first=Thomson|website=legalsolutions.thomsonreuters.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> Much of her work has focused on the problems of forensic science evidence, especially pattern identification evidence like latent fingerprint identification.<ref name=\"uclabio\"/> She has frequently commented to the press on forensic science and evidence issues<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real CSI|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/criminal-justice/real-csi/transcript-18/|publisher=Public Broadcasting System|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=The Achilles' Heel of Fingerprints|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A64711-2004May28.html|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=The 'West Memphis Three' and combating cognitive biases|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/23/opinion/la-oe-mnookin-west-memphis-three-rele20110823|publisher=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mnookin|first=Jennifer|title=Clueless 'science'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/19/opinion/oe-mnookin19|publisher=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Russell |first=Sue |title=Bias and the Big Fingerprint Dust-Up |url=https://psmag.com/news/bias-and-the-big-fingerprint-dust-up-3629 |publisher=Pacific Standard |accessdate=January 24, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202124711/https://psmag.com/news/bias-and-the-big-fingerprint-dust-up-3629 |archivedate=February 2, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Steinhauer|first=Jennifer|title=\u2018Grim Sleeper\u2019 Arrest Fans Debate on DNA Use|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09sleeper.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=mnookin&st=cse|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Liptak|first=Adam|title=In U.S., Expert Witnesses Are Partisan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/12/us/12experts.html?pagewanted=print|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/a-wake-up-call-on-the-junk-science-infesting-our-courtrooms/2016/09/19/85b6eb22-7e90-11e6-8d13-d7c704ef9fd9_story.html|title=A wake-up call on the junk science infesting our courtrooms|last=Edwards|first=Harry T.|date=2016-09-20|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-24|last2=Mnookin|first2=Jennifer L.|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>and has occasionally consulted or served as an expert witness on the scientific foundation of fingerprint evidence.<ref>{{cite web|title=United States of America v. Raynard Council|url=http://www.swgfast.org/Resources/110507_JudgeSpencerOpinion.pdf|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer scholarship on [[forensic science]] was cited extensively by the [[National Academy of Sciences]]' 2009 report.<ref>{{cite web|title=Strengthening Forensic Science in the United States|url=http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12589|publisher=The National Academies Press|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> She is a former member of the National Academy of Science's Committee on Science, Technology and the Law<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sites.nationalacademies.org/PGA/stl/PGA_049554|title=COMMITTEE MEMBERS|last=PGA|website=sites.nationalacademies.org|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> and is on the advisory board of the [[Electronic Privacy Information Center.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epic.org/epic/advisory_board.html|title=EPIC - EPIC Advisory Board|last=Center|first=Electronic Privacy Information|website=epic.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> She was the primary investigator for a National Institute of Justice project that sought to develop objective metrics for measuring the difficulty of fingerprint comparisons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/two-ucla-professors-awarded-national-153642|title=UCLA professors awarded major federal grant to study error rates in fingerprint evidence|last=Gavel|first=Lauri|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> Her work on the Confrontation Clause was cited and discussed by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] in ''Williams v. Illinois'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams v. Illinois|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=14525729923225817611&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> In 2016, she co-chaired an advisory group to the President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology, which issued a report on the reliability of forensic science used in the courtroom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/PCAST/pcast_forensic_science_report_final.pdf|title=Report to the President: Forensic Science in Criminal Courts}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/q-a-with-jennifer-mnookin:-raising-the-bar-for-scientific-evidence-in-court|title=Q&A with Jennifer Mnookin: Raising the bar for scientific evidence in court|last=Kisliuk|first=Bill|website=UCLA Newsroom|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as a law school administrator, Mnookin is a former member of the steering committee of the [[Association of American Law Schools]]' Dean's Forum. Mnookin was named a member of the American Law Institute, a leading organization dedicated to improving and modernizing the law, in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ali.org/members/member/369001/|title=Members {{!}} American Law Institute|last=Institute|first=The American Law|website=American Law Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nMnookin is married to Joshua Foa Dienstag,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/29/style/weddings-jennifer-mnookin-joshua-dienstag.html|title=WEDDINGS; Jennifer Mnookin, Joshua Dienstag|date=1994-05-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> a professor of political science and law at UCLA. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/joshua-foa-dienstag/|title=Joshua Foa Dienstag|publisher=UCLA Department of Political Science|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417125421/http://www.polisci.ucla.edu/people/faculty-pages/joshua-foa-dienstag|archivedate=April 17, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> They have two children, Sophia and Isaac.<ref>https://www.uclalawreview.org/reflections-on-law-teaching-2/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mnookin, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American legal writers]]\n[[Category:Legal educators]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennifer_Mnookin"}
{"title_page": "List of Stateside Puerto Ricans", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n<!--When adding names to the list, please include a reliable source that describes the person added as \"Puerto Rican\", \"Puerto Ricans in the United States\" or Stateside Puerto Ricans (or a source where the person describes themselves as such), in accordance with Wikipedia's [[No Original Research]] policies.-->\nThis is a list of '''[[Puerto Ricans in the United States]]''', including people born in the US of Puerto Rican descent and Puerto Ricans who live in the US. Since [[Puerto Rico]] is an unincorporated territory of the US, it is easier to migrate to the US from Puerto Rico than from anywhere else in Latin America. Currently, more than 5.5 million Puerto Ricans and their descendants live in the US, significantly more than the population of Puerto Rico itself. The following list contains notable members of the Puerto Rican community.\n{{Americans}}\n\n<!-- To be included in this list, the person must have a Wikipedia article showing they are Stateside Puerto Ricans in United States or must have references showing they are Stateside Puerto Ricans and are notable. \nPlease do not add yourself, non-notable people or fictional characters. Please add citations where appropriate --->\n{{Expand list|date=February 2012}}\n\n== Television show hosts ==\n[[File:La La Anthony by Robert Ector.jpg|thumb|160px|[[La La Anthony]]]]\n* [[La La (entertainer)|La La]]{{Snd}} actress, disc jockey, and television personality\n* [[Daisy Martinez]]{{Snd}} actress, model, chef, [[celebrity|television personality]] and [[author]]; host of [[PBS]] television series ''[[Daisy Cooks!]]''\n* [[John Melendez]]{{Snd}} television writer and former radio personality\n* [[Rogelio Mills]]{{Snd}} television personality; Puerto Rican/Black Hispanic American<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegodlynetwork.com/aboutfounder.html |title=About the Founder |work=The Godly Network |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Antonio S\u00e1nchez (Puerto Rican host)|Antonio S\u00e1nchez]]{{Snd}} radio and television personality, show host and producer\n\n== Business ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Samuel Ramirez.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.]]]] -->\n*[[Kimberly Casiano]]{{Snd}} President and [[Chief Operating Officer]] of [[Casiano Communications]]<ref name=\"PRcabinet\">{{cite web|accessdate=2007-06-10\n|url=http://centropr.org/lib-arc/faids/PDF%20File/OGPRUS%20Guide%20Oct%2018,%202006.pdf.\n|format=PDF\n|title=Finding Aid - The Records of the Offices of the Government of Puerto Rico in the United States, 1930-1993\n|publisher=Archives of the Puerto Rican Diaspora, Centro de Estudios Puertorrique\u00f1os, Hunter College}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n* [[Mar\u00eda Elena Holly]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican widow of rock and roll pioneer [[Buddy Holly]]; lives in Texas and New York<ref>[http://lubbockonline.com/stories/081508/loc_318846994.shtml Buddy and Maria Elena Holly married 50 years ago]</ref>\n* [[Ralph Mercado]]{{Snd}} promoter of Latin American music, including Latin jazz, Latin rock, merengue and salsa; established a network of businesses\n*[[Lisette Nieves]]{{Snd}} founder of Atrevete Latino Youth, Inc., an organization which focuses on the educational and leadership training of young [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]]s\n* [[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic to launch a successful investment banking firm\n* [[\u00c1ngel Ramos (industrialist)|Angel Ramos]]{{Snd}} founder of Telemundo, the second largest Spanish-language television network in the US\n* [[Xavier Romeu]]{{Snd}} Executive Director of [[Puerto Rico Industrial Development Company]]\n* [[Herb Scannell]]{{Snd}} President of BBC Worldwide America\n* [[Nina Tassler]]{{Snd}} television executive; President of CBS Entertainment since September 2004\n*[[Richard Velazquez]]{{Snd}} first Puerto Rican automotive designer for [[Porsche]]; first [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] [[Xbox]] product planner; co-founder and President of [[NSHMBA]] Seattle\n* [[Maria Vizcarrondo-De Soto]]{{Snd}} President and CEO of the United Way of Essex and West Hudson\n\n== Actors and actresses ==\n[[File:Yancey Arias 2010.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Yancey Arias]]]]\n[[File:Raquel Castro 2011.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Raquel Castro]]]]\n* [[Kirk Acevedo]]{{Snd}} actor, [[HBO]] series ''[[Oz (TV series)|Oz]]'', ''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]'', ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''\n* [[Daniella Alonso]]{{Snd}} actress\n* [[Trini Alvarado]]{{Snd}} actress, flamenco dancer, and flamenco singer\n* [[Philip Anthony-Rodriguez]]{{Snd}} actor and singer\n* [[Victor Argo]]{{Snd}} actor\n* [[Yancey Arias]]{{Snd}} American actor of Colombian and Puerto Rican descent \n* [[Rick Aviles]]{{Snd}} stand-up comedian and actor, ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]''\n* [[Jake T. Austin]]{{Snd}} actor, ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'' \n* [[Charlotte Ayanna]]{{Snd}} actress and former Miss Teen USA\n* [[Adrienne Bailon]]{{Snd}} singer and actress\n* [[Rosa Blasi]]{{Snd}} actress\n* [[Diego Boneta]]{{Snd}} American actor and singer; father is [[Mexican people|Mexican]], mother was born in the US, to a Puerto Rican father and [[Spanish people|Spanish]] mother<ref name=\"Univision\">{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.univision.com/cine/dvds/article/2011-02-08/diego-boneta-un-galan-mexicano|title=Diego Boneta, un gal\u00e1n mexicano en 'Mean Girls 2'|last=Garc\u00eda|first=Julio|date=8 February 2011|publisher=[[Univision]]|accessdate=22 April 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Calder\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} actor\n* [[Nydia Caro]]{{Snd}} actress and singer\n* [[David Castro (actor)|David Castro]]{{Snd}} actor\n* [[Raquel Castro]]{{Snd}} teen actress and singer\n* [[M\u00edriam Col\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} actress and founder and director of the Puerto Rican Traveling Theater in New York City\n* [[Liza Col\u00f3n-Zayas]]{{Snd}} actress and playwright\n* [[Kevin Corrigan]]{{Snd}} 