sports/article/Ron-Rivera-s-footprints-trace-to-Northern-6797204.php |website=SF Gate |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Chi Chi Rodriguez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican professional golfer\n* [[John Ruiz]]{{Snd}} former American professional boxer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latinosportslegends.com/Ruiz_John-bio.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624013553/http://latinosportslegends.com/Ruiz_John-bio.htm |archivedate=2011-06-24 }}\nBoxer, John Ruiz-Latino Legends in Sports</ref>\n* [[Daniel Santiago]]{{Snd}} professional American basketball player; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Lisa Marie Varon]]{{Snd}} American professional wrestler, bodybuilder and fitness competitor; of Puerto Rican and Turkish descent\n\n== Criminals ==\n* [[Salvador Agron|Salvador Agr\u00f3n]], aka \"The Capeman\" (1943\u20131986){{Snd}} Puerto Rican gang member who murdered two teenagers in a Hell's Kitchen park in 1959\n* [[Ariel Castro]]{{Snd}} former school bus driver who kidnapped, raped, and tortured three women in Cleveland, Ohio and held them captive for a decade\n* [[Raymond M\u00e1rquez]], aka \"Spanish Raymond\"{{Snd}} reputed American gangster; parents are from Puerto Rico<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/06/nyregion/longtime-numbers-king-of-new-york-goes-public-to-clear-his-name.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm New York Times; \"Longtime Numbers King of New York Goes Public to Clear His Name\" By SELWYN RAAB; Published: July 06, 1997]</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Padilla (prisoner)|Jos\u00e9 Padilla]], aka Abdullah al-Muhajir or Muhajir Abdullah{{Snd}} American convicted of aiding terrorists\n* [[Joshua Rosa]]{{Snd}} American convicted murderer in the state of Florida; parents are Puerto Rican\n\n== Diplomats ==\n[[File: Mari Carmen Aponte ambassador.jpg|thumb|150px|Mari Carmen Aponte]]\n* [[Mari Carmen Aponte]]{{Snd}} US Ambassador to [[El Salvador]]\n* [[Adrian A. Basora]]{{Snd}} American diplomat, and former US Ambassador to the [[Czech Republic]]\n* [[C\u00e9sar Benito Cabrera]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Mauritius]] and the [[Seychelles]]\n* [[Gabriel Guerra-Mondrag\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} US Ambassador to [[Chile]] 1994&ndash;1998\n* [[Luis Guinot]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Costa Rica]]\n* [[Hans Hertell]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to the [[Dominican Republic]]\n* [[Victor Marrero]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to the [[Organization of American States|OAS]]\n* [[Carmen Maria Martinez]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Zambia]]\n* [[Spencer Matthews King]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Guyana]]\n* [[Edward G. Miller, Jr.]] (1911\u20131968){{Snd}} lawyer; Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs 1949\u20131952<ref>\"Edward G. Miller Jr., 56, Dies' Acheson's Latin America Aide\", ''The New York Times'', 16 Apr. 1968.</ref>\n* [[Teodoro Moscoso]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Venezuela]] and head of [[Alliance for Progress]]\n* [[Horacio Rivero]]{{Snd}} Admiral (Ret.), former US Ambassador to [[Spain]]\n\n== Educators ==\n[[File:Joseph Acaba v2.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Joseph M. Acaba]]]]\n* [[Joseph M. Acaba|Joseph M. Acab\u00e1]]{{Snd}} educator, hydrogeologist, and NASA astronaut; American of Puerto Rican parent<ref name=\"Astronomy PR\">[http://astronomypr.com/articulos_acaba.html Astronomy PR] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506104134/http://www.astronomypr.com/articulos_acaba.html |date=2009-05-06 }}</ref>\n* [[Edwin David Aponte]]{{Snd}} educator, author, religious leader, scholar of Latino religions and cultures; born in [[Connecticut]] to Puerto Rican parents \n* [[Frank Bonilla]] (1925\u20132010){{Snd}} American academic of Puerto Rican descent who became a leading figure in Puerto Rican Studies.\n* [[Ram\u00f3n E. L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} American space physicist and author; played an instrumental role in the implementation of a hands-on science program in elementary and middle grades Montgomery County Public Schools in Maryland\n* [