rated to the US in the 1850s<ref name=\"CW\">\"The Puerto Rican Diaspora: historical perspectives\"; By Carmen Teresa Whalen, V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez-Hernandez; page 176; Publisher: Temple University Press; {{ISBN|978-1-59213-413-7}}; {{ISBN|1-59213-413-0}}</ref>\n* [[Pedro Rodr\u00edguez (soldier)|Pedro Rodr\u00edguez]] (1912\u20131999){{Snd}} earned two Silver Stars within a seven-day period during the Korean War; Puerto Rican; died in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"ANC\">[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/pedrorod.htm Arlington National Cemetery]</ref>\n* [[Fernando E. Rodr\u00edguez Vargas]] (1888\u20131932){{Snd}} Puerto Rican odontologist (dentist), scientist and a major in the US Army; discovered the bacteria which causes cavities; died in Washington, D.C.\n* [[Maritza S\u00e1enz Ryan]]{{Snd}} U.S. Army officer; head of the Department of Law at the US Military Academy; first woman and first Hispanic West Point graduate to serve as an academic department head; Puerto Rican father, Spanish mother<ref name=\"PV\">[http://www.usma.edu/dcomm/pv/yr2006/06jan06.pdf Pointer View]</ref>\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Santiago-Col\u00f3n]] (1942\u20131968){{Snd}} one of five Puerto Ricans posthumously presented with the Medal of Honor, the highest military decoration awarded by the U.S.; Puerto Rican from New York<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate=October 5, 2010 |url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n45/ProfileSantColon-es.html |title=Puerto Rico Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303194555/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n45/ProfileSantColon-es.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n* [[Frankie Segarra]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic to reach the rank of Master Gunnery Sergeant in his military occupational specialty, 0451 air delivery specialist; parents were Puerto Rican<ref name=\"HHM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usmc.mil/marinelink/image1.nsf/Lookup/200410614333?opendocument|accessdate=2006-05-16|title=Hispanic Heritage Month|work=Marine 