no]]{{Snd}} American New York State Senator; son of Jos\u00e9 Enrique Serrano\n* [[Darren Soto]]{{Snd}} Orlando-based attorney and Democratic politician who serves the member of the Florida House of Representatives for District 49\n*  [[Joey Torres]]{{Snd}} elected mayor of [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[New Jersey]] in 2014, where he had served two prior terms as mayor\n* [[Gloria Tristani]]{{Snd}} served from 1997 to 2001 as the first Hispanic woman member of the Federal Communications Commission\n* [[Miguel del Valle]]{{Snd}} American politician; former [[City Clerk of Chicago]]; Puerto Rican born, American raised<ref>http://www.chicagonow.com/blogs/chicago-muckrakers/2011/01/miguel-del-valle-will-now-take-your-questions.html</ref>\n* [[Nydia Vel\u00e1zquez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican and US Representative<ref name=\"HAC\">[https://www.loc.gov/rr/hispanic/congress/velazquez.html Hispanic Americans in Congress]</ref>\n* [[Ra\u00fal G. Villaronga]]{{Snd}} retired Puerto Rican US Army officer; first Puerto Rican mayor of a Texas city; elected Mayor of [[Killeen, Texas]] in 1992<ref>http://groups.google.com/group/Jibaros/browse_thread/thread/1b425f86e8204aaf Jibaros.com</ref>\n\n==Visual arts==\n* [[Olga Albizu]] (1924\u20132005){{Snd}} Puerto Rican abstract expressionist painter; emigrated to New York in 1948<ref>[http://www.biaggifaure.com/artist-oalbizu.htm#3 Olga Albizu artist profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707232625/http://www.biaggifaure.com/artist-oalbizu.htm#3 |date=2011-07-07 }} at Biaggi Faure Fine Art</ref>\n* [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]] (1960\u20131988){{Snd}} visual artist; African-American of Haitian and Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://thecreativeroutine.tumblr.com/post/918691970/hailing-from-brookyln-jean-michel-basquiat TheCreativeRoutine \u2022 Hailing from Brookyln, Jean-Michel Basquiat]. Retrieved July 27, 2011, to 13:55 pm.</ref>\n* [[David Blaine]]{{Snd}} American illusionist, magician, and endurance artist; of Puerto Rican-Russian Jewish descent<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/19/news/cl-54095 The Houdini of the Hoi Polloi], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 2000-11-19</ref>\n* [[Rafael Ferrer (artist)|Rafael Ferrer]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican artist; 1993 recipient of a Pew Fellowship in the Arts; 2011 recipient of an Annalee and Barnett Newman Foundation Grant\n*[[Elizabeth Marrero]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican performance artist, comedian, known as Macha, the \"papi chulo drag king,\" a character she created in 1999; lives in the US\n* [[Soraida Martinez|Soraida Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} contemporary abstract expressionist artist who creates hard-edge paintings; American of Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/education/teacherartexchange/archive/Feb04/0113.html The Getty: Latino Artist you will LOVE - Soraida Martinez] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303185008/http://www.getty.edu/education/teacherartexchange/archive/Feb04/0113.html |date=2016-03-03 }}</ref>\n* [[Ralph Ortiz]]{{Snd}} American artist, educator, and founder of [[El Museo del Barrio]]\n* [[Manuel Rivera-Ortiz]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican documentary photographer; lives in the US<ref>http://www.jacketflap.com/manuel-rivera-ortiz/19862 About Manuel Rivera-Ortiz</ref>\n* [[Joe Shannon (artist)|Joe Shannon]] \u2013 prolific artist with permanent exhibits in multiple museums in the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edspace.american.edu/artkatzen/2008/05/|title=May 2008 \u2013 Art at the Katzen|date=2008|website=American University|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n* [[Filipo Tirado]], aka \"Pepe Locuaz\"{{Snd}} Puerto Rican puppeteer\n\n== Civil rights and activists ==\n[[File:Mathias Brugman.JPG|thumb|140px|[[Mathias Brugman]]]]\n* [[Mathias Brugman]] (1811\u20131868){{Snd}} leader in Puerto Rico's independence revolution against Spain known as [[Grito de Lares|El Grito de Lares (The Cry of Lares)]]; father was Pierre Brugman from [[Cura\u00e7ao]] of [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-[[Jewish]] ancestry, mother was from Puerto Rico\n* [[Oscar Collazo]] (1914\u20131994){{Snd}} one of two Puerto Ricans who attempted to assassinate US President [[Harry S. Truman]]\n* [[Angelo Falc\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} political scientist; President and founder of [[National Institute for Latino Policy]]; Puerto Rican born and American raised\n* [[Inez Garc\u00eda|In\u00e9z Garc\u00eda]]{{Snd}} cause celebre of the feminist movement; of Puerto Rican and Cuban descent\n* [[Olga Viscal Garriga]] (1929\u20131995){{Snd}} public orator, political activist; descendant of a former governor of Puerto Rico; advocate for Puerto Rican independence\n* [[Isabel Gonz\u00e1lez]] (1882\u20131971){{Snd}} Puerto Rican activist who helped pave the way for Puerto Ricans to be given US citizenship; lived in New York and New Jersey<ref>http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/cgi-bin/getcase.pl?court=us&vol=192&invol=1 U.S. Supreme Court</ref>\n* [[Sonia Gutierrez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-born American educator and Hispanic rights activist.\n* [[Marie Hayd\u00e9e Beltr\u00e1n Torres]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1980/05/24/archives/mrs-torres-gets-life-term-for-fatal-bombing-in-1977-linked-to-the.html Mrs. Torres Gets Life Term For Fatal Bombing in 1977], ''The New York Times'', 24 May 1980</ref>\n* [[\u00d3scar L\u00f3pez Rivera]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803E5DA163DF93BA3575AC0A96F958260|title=12 Imprisoned Puerto Ricans Accept Clemency Conditions|accessdate=17 September 2008|work=The New York Times|date=1999-11-08|author=John M. Broder}}</ref> pardoned by President Barack Obama\n* [[Rosa Mart\u00ednez and Eliana Mart\u00ednez|Eliana Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} young AIDS activist in notable Florida court case regarding the rights of HIV+ children in public schools* [[Sylvia Mendez|Sylvia M\u00e9ndez]]{{Snd}} American civil rights activist; of Mexican-Puerto Rican heritage<ref>http://neatoday.org/2011/02/16/sylvia-mendez-school-desegregation-pioneer-honored-at-white-house/ Sylvia Mendez, School Desegregation Pioneer, Honored at White House. published February 16, 2011 by twalker.</ref>\n* [[Eugene Nelson]]{{Snd}} American labor leader\n\n[[File:ACLU Anthony D Romero.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Anthony Romero]]]]\n* [[Manuel Olivieri Sanchez|Manuel Olivieri S\u00e1nchez]] (born 1888){{Snd}} Puerto Rican court interpreter and civil rights activist; led the legal battle which recognized US citizenship for Puerto Ricans living in Hawaii\n* [[Carmen Pola]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican long-time politician and community activist in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]; first Latina to run for statewide office; first Director of the Office of Constituent Services\n* [[Ron Rivera (public health)|Ronald Rivera]] (1948\u20132008){{Snd}} American activist best known for developing an inexpensive ceramic water filter used to treat gray water in impoverished communities, and for establishing community-based factories to produce the filters around the world\n* [[Sylvia Rae Rivera]] (1951\u20132002){{Snd}} American [[transgender activism|transgender activist]]; founding member of the [[Gay Liberation Front]] and the [[Gay Activists Alliance]]; helped found STAR ([[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]]); of Puerto Rican and Venezuelan descent<ref name=Gan>Gan, Jessi. [https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37719107.pdf \"'Still at the Back of the Bus': Sylvia Rivera's Struggle\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175345/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf |date=2012-04-06 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 124-139.</ref>\n* [[Helen Rodriguez-Trias|Helen Rodr\u00edguez-Tr\u00edas]] (1929\u20132001){{Snd}} American pediatrician, educator and women's rights activist<ref name=\"FoM\">[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_273.html Changing the Face of Medicine]</ref>\n* [[Anthony Romero]]{{Snd}} American executive director of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]]\n* [[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]] (1874\u20131938){{Snd}} Puerto Rican historian, writer, and activist in the US who raised awareness of the social contributions made by Afro-Latin Americans and Afro-Americans; died in New York<ref name=\"AA\">[http://www.pww.org/past-weeks-2001/Arturo%20Alfonso%20Schomburg.htm \"Arturo Alfonso Schomburg: Pionero en la historia afronorteamericana\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227055402/http://pww.org/past-weeks-2001/Arturo%20Alfonso%20Schomburg.htm |date=2009-02-27 }}, ''Nuestro Mondo/People's Weekly World'', accessed 2 Feb 2009</ref>\n*Yolanda Serrano{{Snd}} HIV/AIDS activist and a ''Ms.'' magazine woman of the year\n* [[Alejandrina Torres]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>{{cite book|last=Torres|first=Andr\u00e9s|title=The Puerto Rican movement: voices from the diaspora|publisher=Temple University Press|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKJtYNvKKrgC&pg=PA147&dq=Alejandrina+Torres+no+defense#PPA149,M1|accessdate=2009-03-19 | isbn=978-1-56639-618-9}}</ref>\n* [[Griselio Torresola]] (1925\u20131950){{Snd}} one of two Puerto Rican Nationalists who attempted to assassinate US President Harry Truman; Puerto Rico born\n\n== Physicians and scientists ==\n[[File:Joseph Acaba v2.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Joseph M. Acaba]]]]\n* [[Joseph M. Acaba|Joseph M. Acab\u00e1]]{{Snd}} American educator, hydrogeologist, and NASA astronaut; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"Astronomy PR\"/>\n* [[Oxiris Barbot]], Commissioner of Health of the City of New York\n* [[V\u00edctor Manuel Blanco]], PhD (1918\u20132011){{Snd}} Puerto Rican astronomer; in 1959 discovered \"Blanco 1,\" a galactic cluster; died in Florida<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/BATESVILLE/Obituaries.asp?Page=Notice&PersonID=149179574 Obituary at Legacy.com]</ref>\n* [[Rafael L. Bras|Rafael L. Br\u00e1s]]{{Snd}} American civil engineer; Provost to the Georgia Institute of Technology; Puerto Rican-born\n* [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]]{{Snd}} American [[astrophysics|astrophysicist]], author, and [[science communication|science communicator]]. His mother is of Puerto Rican ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bried|first=Erin|title=Sunchita Tyson|url=http://howtorockyourbaby.com/moms|work=How to Rock Your Baby and other timeless tips for modern moms|publisher=Hyperion|accessdate=2 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320010721/http://howtorockyourbaby.com/moms/|archive-date=2014-03-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Enectal\u00ed Figueroa-Feliciano]], PhD, aka \"Tali\"{{Snd}} astrophysicist and researcher with NASA Goddard Space Flight Center; pioneered the development of position-sensitive detectors\n* [[Ger\u00f3nimo Lluberas]] (1956\u20132003){{Snd}} Puerto Rican physician, humanitarian, writer and composer\n* [[Ram\u00f3n E. L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} space physicist and author\n* [[Lissette Martinez|Lissette Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} lead electrical engineer for the Space Experiment Module program at the [[Wallops Flight Facility]]\n* [[Joseph O. Prewitt D\u00edaz]], PhD{{Snd}} retired psychologist; specialized in psychosocial theory; first Puerto Rican recipient of the American Psychological Association; 2008 International Humanitarian Award<ref>American Psychologist (2008) 63 (8), 327-333.</ref>\n* [[Pedro Rodriguez (NASA)|Pedro Rodr\u00edguez]], PhD{{Snd}} Director of a test laboratory at NASA; inventor of a portable, battery-operated lift seat for people suffering from knee arthritis\n* [[Fernando E. Rodr\u00edguez Vargas]], DDS (1888\u20131932){{Snd}} odontologist (dentist), scientist and a major in the US Army who discovered the bacteria which causes cavities\n* [[Gualberto Rua\u00f1o]], MD, PhD{{Snd}} pioneer in the field of personalized medicine; inventor of molecular diagnostic systems used worldwide for the management of viral diseases\n\n== Religious ==\n* [[Nicky Cruz]] (born 1938){{Snd}} Christian evangelist; founder of Nicky Cruz Outreach, an evangelistic Christian ministry\n* [[Alberto Cuti\u00e9]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican Episcopal cleric better known as Padre Alberto; ordained a Roman Catholic priest in 1995; became an internationally recognizable name by hosting television and radio programs\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Luis de Jes\u00fas]]{{Snd}} founder and leader of Creciendo en Gracia's Christian ministry (Growing In Grace International Ministry, Inc.), based in Miami, Florida\n* [[Bavi Edna Rivera]], aka \"Nedi\"{{Snd}} American suffragan bishop and Episcopal priest; daughter of the late bishop Victor Manuel Rivera and an Anglo mother<ref name=\"A\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecww.org/files/5/BishopRiveraBiography.pdf |title=Diocese of Olympia |access-date=2010-12-14 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5uy9LSiCr?url=http://www.ecww.org/files/5/BishopRiveraBiography.pdf |archive-date=2010-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Victor Manuel Rivera|V\u00edctor Manuel Rivera]] (1916\u20132005){{Snd}} Puerto Rican born American Episcopalian priest and bishop\n\n==Writers==\n\n* [[Jack Ag\u00fceros]]{{Snd}} community activist, poet, writer, and translator\n* [[Quiara Alegr\u00eda Hudes]]{{Snd}} American playwright and author, known for writing the book for the Tony Award-winning musical ''In the Heights''; of Jewish and Puerto Rican descent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143122-26-Miles-Quiara-Hudes-Mother-Daughter-Road-Trip-Tale-Gets-Chicago-Premiere-Starting-Oct-16 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921071804/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143122-26-Miles-Quiara-Hudes-Mother-Daughter-Road-Trip-Tale-Gets-Chicago-Premiere-Starting-Oct-16 |archivedate=2010-09-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Miguel Algar\u00edn]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet, writer, co-founder of the Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9\n* [[Rane Arroyo]] (1954\u20132010){{Snd}} American poet, playwright, and scholar; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Pura Belpr\u00e9]] (1899 or 1903\u20131982){{Snd}} author; first Puerto Rican librarian in New York City<ref