versity Press|page= 85}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Denis]] (born 1954){{Snd}} Author of ''War Against All Puerto Ricans,'' film director, and former New York State Assemblyman\n* [[Sandra Mar\u00eda Esteves]]{{Snd}} American poet, playwright, and graphic artist; of Puerto Rican, Dominican and African American descent<ref>PBS. [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/americancollection/woman/ei_poetry_esteves.html \"Puerto Rican Poetry\"]. Retrieved July 30, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Lawrence La Fountain-Stokes]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author, scholar, and performer; lives in Michigan\n* [[Pedro J. Labarthe]] (1905\u20131966){{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet, journalist, essayist, and novelist\n* [[Tato Laviera]]{{Snd}} Nuyorican poet; born in Puerto Rico; moved to New York City with his family in 1960\n* [[Muna Lee (writer)|Muna Lee]] (1895\u20131965){{Snd}} American author and poet; known for her writings that promoted Pan-Americanism and feminism\n* [[Erika Lopez|\u00c9rika L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} American cartoonist, novelist, and performance artist; of Puerto Rican and German American descent<ref>[[Lawrence La Fountain-Stokes|La Fountain-Stokes, Lawrence]]. ''Queer Ricans: Cultures and Sexualities in the Diaspora.'' Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2009, page 126. {{ISBN|0-8166-4092-0}}</ref>\n* [[Caridad de la Luz]], aka \"La Bruja\" (The \"Good\" Witch){{Snd}} poet, actress and activist; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"LP\">[http://www.eldiariony.com/noticias/especiales/detail.aspx?EspecialId=26&id=1098418 El Diario/La Prensa - Caridad de la Luz]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190806/http://www.eldiariony.com/noticias/especiales/detail.aspx?EspecialId=26&id=1098418 |date=September 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Nemir Matos-Cintr\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author; lives in Florida\n[[File:Arturo Alfonso Schomburg.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]]]]\n* [[John Melendez|John Mel\u00e9ndez]], aka \"Stuttering John\"{{Snd}} American television writer and former radio personality\n* [[Nicholasa Mohr]]{{Snd}} one of the best known Nuyorican writers<ref>[http://www.bookrags.com/biography/nicholasa-mohr-dlb/ Dictionary of Literary Biography intro online]</ref>\n* [[Micol Ostow]]{{Snd}} American author, editor and educator; [[Jewish-American]] father, Puerto Rican mother<ref name=\"LJ\">[http://slayground.livejournal.com/293625.html Live Journal]</ref>\n* [[George P\u00e9rez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-American writer and illustrator of comic books; his family moved from [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]] to the [[New York metropolitan area|New York area]] in the 1940s<ref>{{cite book |title= Modern Masters Volume 2: George P\u00e9rez |last= Nolen-Weathington|first= Eric|authorlink= |year= 2003|publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |isbn= 1-893905-25-X |page= 6|quote = My mom, Luz Maria Izquierdo, and my father, Jorge P\u00e9rez, were both born in Caguas, Puerto Rico, the same year but would not actually meet each other until they moved{{Snd}} I believe the same year, I don't know the exact year{{Snd}} to New Jersey...by the time they were married they had moved to New York.|url= https://books.google.com/?id=bhOPZ2u7C_YC&pg=PA6&dq=George+P%C3%A9rez+Caguas+Luz+Maria+Izquierdo+Jorge+P%C3%A9rez#v=onepage&q=George%20P%C3%A9rez%20Caguas%20Luz%20Maria%20Izquierdo%20Jorge%20P%C3%A9rez&f=false|accessdate= November 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Pedro Pietri]] (1944\u20132004){{Snd}} Nuyorican poet and playwright; co-founded the Nuyorican Poets Cafe; Puerto Rican born and American raised<ref name=\"Pietri\">[http://www.monthlyreview.org/0604pietri.htm Monthly Review]</ref>\n* [[Carmen M. Pursifull]]{{Snd}} former New York City Latin dance and Latin American music figure of the 1950s, and since 1970 in Illinois; English-language free verse poet; of Puerto Rican and Spanish descent<ref>''Probing the Depths, supra,'' at 230.</ref> \n* [[Marie Teresa R\u00edos]] (1917\u20131999){{Snd}} American author of a book which was the basis for the 1960s television sitcom ''[[The Flying Nun]]''; of Puerto Rican and Irish descent{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n* [[\u00c1ngel Rivero M\u00e9ndez]], wrote {{lang|es|Cr\u00f3nica de la guerra hispano-americana en Puerto Rico}}, which is considered one of the most complete works written in regard to that military action\n*[[Esmeralda Santiago]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author and former actress known for her novels and memoirs\n* [[Tony Santiago]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican military historian\n* [[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]], aka Arthur Schomburg (1874\u20131938){{Snd}} Puerto Rican historian, writer, and activist in the US who raised awareness of the social contributions made by Afro-Latin Americans and Afro-Americans; died in New York; immigrated to New York in 1891<ref name=\"AB\">[http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/schomburg.html Robert Knight, \"Arthur Alfonso 'Afroborinque\u00f1o' Schomburg\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000142/http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/schomburg.html |date=2007-09-28 }}, History Notes, Global African Community, accessed 2 Feb 2009</ref>\n*[[Piri Thomas]] (1928\u20132011){{Snd}} writer and American poet; memoir ''Down These Mean Streets'' became a best-seller; Puerto Rican mother, Cuban father\n* [[Edwin Torres (poet)|Edwin Torres]]{{Snd}} Nuyorican poet\n* [[Ed Vega]] (1936\u20132008){{Snd}} Puerto Rican novelist and short story writer<ref name=\"nytobit\">Weber, Bruce (September 9, 2008). [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/09/books/09vegayunque.html Edgardo Vega Yunqu\u00e9, Novelist of the Puerto Rican Experience in New York, Dies at 72.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>\n* [[Irene Vilar]]{{Snd}} editor, literary agent, author of books dealing with national and generational trauma and women's reproductive rights\n* [[William Carlos Williams]] (1883\u20131963){{Snd}} American poet, closely associated with modernism and Imagism; of English and Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://www.gpaulbishop.com/GPB%20History/GPB%20Archive/Section%20-%205/W.C.%20Williams/w_c__williams.htm WILLIAM CARLOS WILLIAMS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723145404/http://www.gpaulbishop.com/GPB%20History/GPB%20Archive/Section%20-%205/W.C.%20Williams/w_c__williams.htm |date=2011-07-23 }}</ref>\n\n== Others ==\n* [[A\u00edda \u00c1lvarez]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic woman and Puerto Rican to hold a US Cabinet-level position; grew up in New York<ref>http://www.gale.cengage.com/free_resources/chh/bio/alvarez_a.htm Hispanic Heritage.</ref>\n* [[Nixzmary Brown]] (1998\u20132006){{Snd}} seven-year-old abused child and murder victim from the Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn section of New York City; of Puerto Rican and Pakistanian descent<ref>http://www.eternalportal.com/tributes/nixzmary-brown/default.asp?action=showpage&pid=104 Online Memorial Tribute</ref>\n* [[Marta Casals Istomin]]{{Snd}} former president of the [[Manhattan School of Music]]; Puerto Rican born<ref name=\"PRH\">[http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n33/ProfileMCasalsIstomin-en.html Puerto Rico Herald]</ref>\n* [[Chris Kubecka]] {{Snd}} (full name Christina Kubecka de Medina, Computer Science, Cyberwar) established international business operations for [[Saudi Aramco]] after the world's most devastating [[Shamoon]] [[cyberwarfare]] attacks. Kubecka helped halt the second wave of [[July 2009 cyberattacks]] cyberwar attacks against South Korea. \n* [[Angie Martinez|Angie Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} American radio personality\n* [[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.|Samuel A. Ram\u00edrez, Sr.]]{{Snd}} first [[Hispanic]] to launch a successful investment banking firm; parents are Puerto Ricans\n* [[F\u00e9lix Rigau Carrera]] (1894\u20131954){{Snd}} first Puerto Rican pilot<ref>{{Cite news|accessdate=|work=Gloucester Gazette-Journal|title=Gloucester Deaths |date=October 19, 1954}}</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez (intelligence)]]{{Snd}} head of [[CIA]] division (2004\u20132008)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n* [[List of Hispanic and Latino Americans]]\n* [[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n* [[List of Spanish Americans]]\n* [[Puerto Rican migration to New York]]\n* [[Puerto Rican citizenship]]\n* [[Outline of Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Cultural diversity in Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Corsican immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Chinese immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[French immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Crypto-Judaism]]\n**[[German immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Irish immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Royal Decree of Graces of 1815]]\n* [[Index of Puerto Rico-related articles]]\n* [[History of women in Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Military history of Puerto Rico]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Piragua (food)]]\n* [[51st state|51-star flag]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090207004017/http://us-puertoricans.org/ US Puerto Ricans.org Re/envisioning the Diaspora]\n\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of American people by ethnic or national origin|Puerto Ricans, List Of Stateside]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by ethnicity|Puerto Rican]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n<!--When adding names to the list, please include a reliable source that describes the person added as \"Puerto Rican\", \"Puerto Ricans in the United States\" or Stateside Puerto Ricans (or a source where the person describes themselves as such), in accordance with Wikipedia's [[No Original Research]] policies.-->\nThis is a list of '''[[Puerto Ricans in the United States]]''', including people born in the US of Puerto Rican descent and Puerto Ricans who live in the US. Since [[Puerto Rico]] is an unincorporated territory of the US, it is easier to migrate to the US from Puerto Rico than from anywhere else in Latin America. Currently, more than 5.5 million Puerto Ricans and their descendants live in the US, significantly more than the population of Puerto Rico itself. The following list contains notable members of the Puerto Rican community.\n{{Americans}}\n\n<!-- To be included in this list, the person must have a Wikipedia article showing they are Stateside Puerto Ricans in United States or must have references showing they are Stateside Puerto Ricans and are notable. \nPlease do not add yourself, non-notable people or fictional characters. Please add citations where appropriate --->\n{{Expand list|date=February 2012}}\n\n== Television show hosts ==\n[[File:La La Anthony by Robert Ector.jpg|thumb|160px|[[La La Anthony]]]]\n* [[La La (entertainer)|La La]]{{Snd}} actress, disc jockey, and television personality\n* [[Daisy Martinez]]{{Snd}} actress, model, chef, [[celebrity|television personality]] and [[author]]; host of [[PBS]] television series ''[[Daisy Cooks!]]''\n* [[John Melendez]]{{Snd}} television writer and former radio personality\n* [[Rogelio Mills]]{{Snd}} television personality; Puerto Rican/Black Hispanic American<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegodlynetwork.com/aboutfounder.html |title=About the Founder |work=The Godly Network |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Antonio S\u00e1nchez (Puerto Rican host)|Antonio S\u00e1nchez]]{{Snd}} radio and television personality, show host and producer\n\n== Business ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Samuel Ramirez.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.]]]] -->\n*[[Kimberly Casiano]]{{Snd}} President and [[Chief Operating Officer]] of [[Casiano Communications]]<ref name=\"PRcabinet\">{{cite web|accessdate=2007-06-10\n|url=http://centropr.org/lib-arc/faids/PDF%20File/OGPRUS%20Guide%20Oct%2018,%202006.pdf.\n|format=PDF\n|title=Finding Aid - The Records of the Offices of the Government of Puerto Rico in the United States, 1930-1993\n|publisher=Archives of the Puerto Rican Diaspora, Centro de Estudios Puertorrique\u00f1os, Hunter College}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n* [[Mar\u00eda Elena Holly]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican widow of rock and roll pioneer [[Buddy Holly]]; lives in Texas and New York<ref>[http://lubbockonline.com/stories/081508/loc_318846994.shtml Buddy and Maria Elena Holly married 50 years ago]</ref>\n* [[Ralph Mercado]]{{Snd}} promoter of Latin American music, including Latin jazz, Latin rock, merengue and salsa; established a network of businesses\n*[[Lisette Nieves]]{{Snd}} founder of Atrevete Latino Youth, Inc., an organization which focuses on the educational and leadership training of young [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]]s\n* [[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic to launch a successful investment banking firm\n* [[\u00c1ngel Ramos (industrialist)|Angel Ramos]]{{Snd}} founder of Telemundo, the second largest Spanish-language television network in the US\n* [[Xavier Romeu]]{{Snd}} Executive Director of [[Puerto Rico Industrial Development Company]]\n* [[Herb Scannell]]{{Snd}} President of BBC Worldwide America\n* [[Nina Tassler]]{{Snd}} television executive; President of CBS Entertainment since September 2004\n*[[Richard Velazquez]]{{Snd}} first Puerto Rican automotive designer for [[Porsche]]; first [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] [[Xbox]] product planner; co-founder and President of [[NSHMBA]] Seattle\n* [[Maria Vizcarrondo-De Soto]]{{Snd}} President and CEO of the United Way of Essex and West Hudson\n\n== Actors and actresses ==\n[[File:Yancey Arias 2010.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Yancey Arias]]]]\n[[File:Raquel Castro 2011.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Raquel Castro]]]]\n* [[Kirk Acevedo]]{{Snd}} actor, [[HBO]] series ''[[Oz (TV series)|Oz]]'', ''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]'', ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''\n* [[Daniella Alonso]]{{Snd}} actress\n* [[Trini Alvarado]]{{Snd}} actress, flamenco dancer, and flamenco singer\n* [[Philip Anthony-Rodriguez]]{{Snd}} actor and singer\n* [[Victor Argo]]{{Snd}} actor\n* [[Yancey Arias]]{{Snd}} American actor of Colombian and Puerto Rican descent \n* [[Rick Aviles]]{{Snd}} stand-up comedian and actor, ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]''\n* [[Jake T. Austin]]{{Snd}} actor, ''[[Wizards 