lla]]\n* [[Travis Pastrana]]{{Snd}} American motorsports competitor and stunt performer\n* [[Orlando Perez]]{{Snd}} American footballer of C.D. Chivas USA\n* [[Rico Ramos]]{{Snd}} American super bantamweight boxer and current WBA world super bantamweight champion\n* [[Ram\u00f3n Rivas]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican professional basketball player; born in New York, of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Jorge Rivera (fighter)|Jorge Rivera]]{{Snd}} American mixed martial artist; featured on ''The Ultimate Fighter 4''; of Puerto Rican descent; born in [[Massachusetts]]; lived in Puerto Rico for a short time as a child<ref>[http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=news.detail&gid=12390 The Veteran\u2019s Veteran - Jorge Rivera] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030003542/http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=news.detail&gid=12390 |date=2008-10-30 }}</ref>\n* [[Ron Rivera]]{{Snd}} American football player and head coach<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kroichick |first1=Ron |title=Ron Rivera\u2019s footprints trace to Northern California |url=https://www.sfgate.com/collegesports/article/Ron-Rivera-s-footprints-trace-to-Northern-6797204.php |website=SF Gate |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Chi Chi Rodriguez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican professional golfer\n* [[John Ruiz]]{{Snd}} former American professional boxer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latinosportslegends.com/Ruiz_John-bio.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624013553/http://latinosportslegends.com/Ruiz_John-bio.htm |archivedate=2011-06-24 }}\nBoxer, John Ruiz-Latino Legends in Sports</ref>\n* [[Daniel Santiago]]{{Snd}} professional American basketball player; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Lisa Marie Varon]]{{Snd}} American professional wrestler, bodybuilder and fitness competitor; of Puerto Rican and Turkish descent\n\n== Criminals ==\n* [[Salvador Agron|Salvador Agr\u00f3n]], aka \"The Capeman\" (1943\u20131986){{Snd}} Puerto Rican gang member who murdered two teenagers in a Hell's Kitchen park in 1959\n* [[Ariel Castro]]{{Snd}} former school bus driver who kidnapped, raped, and tortured three women in Cleveland, Ohio and held them captive for a decade\n* [[Raymond M\u00e1rquez]], aka \"Spanish Raymond\"{{Snd}} reputed American gangster; parents are from Puerto Rico<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/06/nyregion/longtime-numbers-king-of-new-york-goes-public-to-clear-his-name.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm New York Times; \"Longtime Numbers King of New York Goes Public to Clear His Name\" By SELWYN RAAB; Published: July 06, 1997]</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Padilla (prisoner)|Jos\u00e9 Padilla]], aka Abdullah al-Muhajir or Muhajir Abdullah{{Snd}} American convicted of aiding terrorists\n* [[Joshua Rosa]]{{Snd}} American convicted murderer in the state of Florida; parents are Puerto Rican\n\n== Diplomats ==\n[[File: Mari Carmen Aponte ambassador.jpg|thumb|150px|Mari Carmen Aponte]]\n* [[Mari Carmen Aponte]]{{Snd}} US Ambassador to [[El Salvador]]\n* [[Adrian A. Basora]]{{Snd}} American diplomat, and former US Ambassador to the [[Czech Republic]]\n* [[C\u00e9sar Benito Cabrera]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Mauritius]] and the [[Seychelles]]\n* [[Gabriel Guerra-Mondrag\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} US Ambassador to [[Chile]] 1994&ndash;1998\n* [[Luis Guinot]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Costa Rica]]\n* [[Hans Hertell]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to the [[Dominican Republic]]\n* [[Victor Marrero]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to the [[Organization of American States|OAS]]\n* [[Carmen Maria Martinez]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Zambia]]\n* [[Spencer Matthews King]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Guyana]]\n* [[Edward G. Miller, Jr.]] (1911\u20131968){{Snd}} lawyer; Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs 1949\u20131952<ref>\"Edward G. Miller Jr., 56, Dies' Acheson's Latin America Aide\", ''The New York Times'', 16 Apr. 1968.</ref>\n* [[Teodoro Moscoso]]{{Snd}} former US Ambassador to [[Venezuela]] and head of [[Alliance for Progress]]\n* [[Horacio Rivero]]{{Snd}} Admiral (Ret.), former US Ambassador to [[Spain]]\n\n== Educators ==\n[[File:Joseph Acaba v2.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Joseph M. Acaba]]]]\n* [[Joseph M. Acaba|Joseph M. Acab\u00e1]]{{Snd}} educator, hydrogeologist, and NASA astronaut; American of Puerto Rican parent<ref name=\"Astronomy PR\">[http://astronomypr.com/articulos_acaba.html Astronomy PR] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506104134/http://www.astronomypr.com/articulos_acaba.html |date=2009-05-06 }}</ref>\n* [[Edwin David Aponte]]{{Snd}} educator, author, religious leader, scholar of Latino religions and cultures; born in [[Connecticut]] to Puerto Rican parents \n* [[Frank Bonilla]] (1925\u20132010){{Snd}} American academic of Puerto Rican descent who became a leading figure in Puerto Rican Studies.\n* [[Ram\u00f3n E. L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} American space physicist and author; played an instrumental role in the implementation of a hands-on science program in elementary and middle grades Montgomery County Public Schools in Maryland\n* [[Andres Ramos Mattei]] (1940\u20131987){{Snd}} Puerto Rican sugar industry historian; died in New Brunswick, New Jersey<ref>[http://projects.chass.utoronto.ca/wshn/number12.html ''Announcement.''] World Sugar History Newsletter. Number 12, June 1988. Retrieved 30 November 2011.</ref>\n* [[Carlos Albizu Miranda]] (1920\u20131984){{Snd}} first Hispanic educator to have a North American University renamed in his honor; one of the first Hispanics to earn a Ph.D. in Psychology in the US; Puerto Rican born and American raised<ref name=\"UPR\">[https://archive.today/20130416113818/http://www.universia.pr/portada/actualidad/noticia_actualidad.jsp?noticia=17434 Universia Puerto Rico]</ref>\n* [[Antonia Pantoja]] (1922\u20132002){{Snd}} educator, social worker, feminist, civil rights leader; founder of ASPIRA, the Puerto Rican Forum, Boricua College and Producir\n* [[\u00c1ngel Ramos (educator)|\u00c1ngel Ramos]]{{Snd}} founder of the National Hispanic Council of the Deaf and Hard of Hearing; Superintendent of the Idaho School for the Deaf and the Blind; one of the few deaf people of Hispanic descent to earn a doctorate from Gallaudet University\n* [[Carlos E. Santiago]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican American labor economist; 7th chancellor of University of Wisconsin\u2013Milwaukee\n* [[Ninfa Segarra]]{{Snd}} last President of the [[Board of Education|New York City Board of Education]]\n\n== Journalists ==\n[[File:Marysol Castro at the 2008 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Marysol Castro]]]]\n* [[Mar\u00eda Celeste Arrar\u00e1s]]{{Snd}} journalist and TV news presenter\n* [[Lynda Baquero]]{{Snd}} American correspondent for WNBC news in New York City; of Puerto Rican ancestry<ref>[http://www.comitenoviembre.org/English/LyndaBaquero.html Comite Noviembre: Puerto Rican Heritage Month - Lynda Baquero]</ref>\n* [[Marysol Castro]]{{Snd}} American television journalist and weather anchor for ''[[The Early Show]]'' on [[CBS]]<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/video?id=3168258 ''What Marysol Castro Learned From Mom'']</ref>\n* [[Carmen Dominicci]]{{Snd}} television journalist\n* [[Jackie Guerrido]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican television weather forecaster and journalist\n* [[Juan Gonzalez (journalist)|Juan Gonzalez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican born investigative journalist<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Juan Gonzalez|work=jrank.org |url=http://www.jrank.org/cultures/pages/3925/Juan-Gonz%C3%A1lez.html}}</ref>\n* [[Kimberly Guilfoyle]]{{Snd}} American cable news personality; one of the rotating co-hosts on ''The Five'' on Fox News Channel; host of an Internet-only crime-related program for Fox News; Puerto Rican mother, Irish father\n* [[Tai Hernandez]]{{Snd}} reporter for WNYW; former correspondent for ABC News\n* [[Alycia Lane]]{{Snd}} American television journalist; of Puerto Rican and Welsh descent<ref name = bio>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/20071217_Alycia_Lane_bio.html\n |title=Alycia Lane Biography|author=|publisher=Philly.com|accessdate=2008-03-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071219083103/http://www.philly.com/philly/news/20071217_Alycia_Lane_bio.html |archivedate = 2007-12-19}}</ref> \n* [[Lynda L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} Emmy Award-winning Puerto Rican American journalist; youngest sister of actress and singer [[Jennifer Lopez]]\n* [[Natalie Morales (journalist)|Natalie Morales]]{{Snd}} television journalist<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6503803.html Biography: Natalie Morales]</ref>\n* [[Denisse Oller]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican broadcaster, journalist, newspaper columnist; former cooking show host and news anchor at WXTV in New York City\n* [[Audrey Puente]]{{Snd}} American meteorologist for WWOR-TV in New York City; daughter of [[Tito Puente]]\n* [[Carlos D. Ramirez]] (1946\u20131999){{Snd}} American publisher; purchased ''El Diario La Prensa'', the oldest Spanish-language newspaper in the US\n[[File:GeraldoRiveraSept2010.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Geraldo Rivera]]]]\n* [[Jorge L. Ramos]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican announcer of Telemundo's New York City affiliate; moved to [[New York City]] in 1976<ref>[http://www.thelampnyc.org/staff/ The LAMP: Jorge L. Ramos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802061437/http://www.thelampnyc.org/staff/ |date=2009-08-02 }} from ''www.thelampnyc.org''</ref>\n* [[Craig Rivera]]{{Snd}} American television journalist, producer, and correspondent for Fox News Channel; father was a Puerto Rican of Sephardic Jew descent\n* [[Geraldo Rivera]]{{Snd}} American talk-show host, journalist; brother of Craig Rivera<ref>[http://www.snopes.com/media/celebrity/geraldo.asp Geraldo Rivera]</ref>\n* [[Darlene Rodriguez]]{{Snd}} American co-anchor of ''Today'' in New York; of Puerto Rican ancestry<ref>[http://www.heartsmartwomenbook.com/bookforeword.html Heart Smart for Black Women and Latinas: Foreword by Darlene Rodriguez Co-Anchor, Today in New York WNBC-TV]</ref>\n* [[Edna Schmidt]]{{Snd}} American journalist; former news anchor for ''Noticiero Univision Edicion Nocturna''\n* [[Ray Suarez]]{{Snd}} television and radio journalist\n* [[Elizabeth Vargas]]{{Snd}} television journalist; American of Puerto Rican descent<ref name=\"EV\">[http://www.classictvhits.com/cast.php?id=2720 Elizabeth Vargas]</ref>\n* [[Jane Velez-Mitchell]]{{Snd}} American award-winning television journalist and bestselling author; mother is Puerto Rican,<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/printArticle.aspx?id=98258 ''Anchored Woman''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418065024/http://www.advocate.com/printArticle.aspx?id=98258 |date=2012-04-18 }} from ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' October 2009</ref> father is [[Irish American]]\n\n== Judges and law enforcement ==\n* [[Jose Baez (lawyer)|Jose B\u00e1ez]]{{Snd}} criminal defense attorney; notable for his defense of accused child murderer [[Caylee Anthony|Casey Anthony]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 A. Cabranes]]{{Snd}} judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit; formerly a practicing lawyer, government official, and law teacher; first Puerto Rican appointed to a federal judgeship in the continental US\n* [[Albert Diaz (judge)|Albert D\u00edaz]]{{Snd}} American judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=observer_20091009>{{cite news|first=Gary L. |last=Wright |author2=Jim Morrill |title=White House evaluates Diaz for 4th Circuit Court |work=[[Charlotte Observer]] |page=1A |date=October 9, 2009 |accessdate=4 November 2009 |quote= |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/408/story/992162.html }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n[[File:Nick Estavillo.JPG|thumb|140px|[[Nicholas Estavillo]]]]\n* [[Nicholas Estavillo]]{{Snd}} first Puerto Rican and first Hispanic in the history of the [[NYPD]] to reach the three-star rank of Chief of Patrol<ref name=\"CPtR\">[http://www.vosizneias.com/9325/2007/05/21/new-york-ny-veteran-nypd-chief-of/ New York, NY - Veteran NYPD Chief Of Patrol To Retire]</ref>\n* [[Faith Evans (U.S. Marshal)|Faith Evans]]{{Snd}} Hawaiian-Puerto Rican; first woman to be named U.S. Marshal\n* [[Julio M. Fuentes]]{{Snd}} Circuit Judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit; first Hispanic judge to serve the Third Circuit; Puerto Rican born, American raised<ref>http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol4n20/PRJurist-en.html</ref>\n* [[Juan Manuel Garc\u00eda Passalacqua]] (1937\u20132010){{Snd}} political commentator, lawyer; Puerto Rican, died in Ohio<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author= Inter News Service |title= Diversas voces lamentan la muerte de Garc\u00eda Passalacqua |work= |publisher= el nuevo dia |location= |id= |pages= |page= |date= July 3, 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-07 |language=Spanish |url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/lluevenmensajesdedueloporgarciapassalacqua-735231.html}}</ref>\n[[File:Carmen M. Ortiz.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Carmen Ortiz]]]]\n* [[Dora Irizarry]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican federal judge in New York\n* [[Irma Lozada]]{{Snd}} first female police officer to die in action in New York<ref name=\"NYT1\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/22/nyregion/22slain.html?_r=1 Recalling a Slain Officer, and the Equality of Peril]</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mel\u00e9ndez-P\u00e9rez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-born U.S. Customs and Border Protection Inspector at Orlando International Airport who became a key figure for the 9/11 Commission when he refused entry to an alleged terrorist prior to the September 11, 2001 attacks\n* [[Carmen Ortiz]]{{Snd}} prosecutor attorney, Boston, Massachusetts; American born \n* [[Juan P\u00e9rez-Gim\u00e9nez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican born, U.S. federal judge in [[senior status]]\n* [[Roberto A. Rivera-Soto]]{{Snd}} Associate Justice of the New Jersey Supreme Court; American born, Puerto Rican raised\n* [[Vanessa Ruiz]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican associate Judge of the District of Columbia Court of Appeals, the highest court for the District of Columbia<ref>[https://www.oyez.org/cases/1980-1989/1981/1981_80_988/ Oyez: Havens Realty Corp. v. Coleman, 455 U.S. 363 (1982), U.S. Supreme Court Case Summary & Oral Argument<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* [[Benito Romano]]{{Snd}} first American of Puerto Rican heritage to hold the US Attorney's post in New York on an interim basis\n* [[Joe S\u00e1nchez]]{{Snd}} American highly decorated former New York City police officer; author whose books give an insight as to the corruption within the department; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"NYDN\">[http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/bronx/2008/07/16/2008-07-16_fired_nypd_cop_writes_gritty_book_to_set.html Fired NYPD cop writes gritty book to set record straight, BY John Marzulli]</ref>\n* [[Sonia Maria Sotomayor]]{{Snd}} Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the U.S. since August 2009; the Court's 111th justice, its first Hispanic justice, and its third female justice<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/politics&id=6831739 |title=Judge Sonia Sotomayor bio. |accessdate=July 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528000356/http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news%2Fpolitics&id=6831739 |archive-date=May 28, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Edgardo Ramos]]{{Snd}}  United States District Judge of the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York since 2011.\n* [[Edwin Torres (judge)|Edwin Torres]]{{Snd}} New York state supreme court judge and author; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"herald\">{{cite news|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol4n48/ProfTorres-en.html |title=Puerto Rico Profile: Judge Edwin Torres |date=2000-12-01 |publisher=Puerto Rico Herald |accessdate=2007-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106172450/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol4n48/ProfTorres-en.html |archivedate=2008-01-06 }}</ref>\n* [[Juan R. Torruella]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican jurist; currently a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the First Circuit; first and to date only Hispanic to serve in that court\n\n== Military ==\n[[File:ADM Rivero, Horacio Jr.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Horacio Rivero, Jr.]]]]\n[[File:Carmen Conteras Bozak.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Carmen Contreras-Bozak]]]]\n[[File:Felices se.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Salvador E. Felices]]]]\n[[File:Virgil R. Miller.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Virgil R. Miller]]]]\n[[File:Maritza Ryan.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Maritza S\u00e1enz Ryan]]]]\n* [[Domingo Arroyo, Jr.]] (1971\u20131993){{Snd}} U.S. Marine; first Puerto Rican and American serviceman killed in Operation Restore Hope during the Somalian Civil War; his family moved to the US when he was 14, seeking better living conditions\n* [[Joseph B. Aviles, Sr.|Joseph B. Avil\u00e9s]] (1897\u20131990){{Snd}} served in the U.S. Navy and later in the Coast Guard; in 1925, became the first Hispanic Chief Petty Officer in the US Coast Guard; Puerto Rican, lived in Maryland<ref>[http://www.interment.net/data/search-usa-maryland.htm?cx=partner-pub-1928517298809652%3Ae1kcewlu31x&cof=FORID%3A10&ie=ISO-8859-1&q=Joseph+B.+Aviles&sa=Search Baltimore National Cemetery]</ref>\n* [[Rafael Celestino Ben\u00edtez]] (1917\u20131999){{Snd}} highly decorated submarine commander who led the rescue effort of the crew members of the USS ''Cochino'' during the Cold War\n* [[Jos\u00e9 M. Cabanillas]] (1901\u20131979){{Snd}} Puerto Rican executive Officer of the USS ''Texas'', which participated in the invasions of North Africa and the Battle of Normandy (D-Day) during [[World War II]]; died in [[Virginia]]\n* [[Iv\u00e1n Castro]]{{Snd}} U.S. Army officer who has continued serving on active duty in the Special Forces despite losing his eyesight; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=nr>{{cite magazine |title=Captain Extraordinary |author=Nordlinger, Jay |magazine=[[National Review]] |date=2009-02-09 |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=16\u201317|author-link=Jay Nordlinger }}</ref>\n* [[Richard Carmona]]{{Snd}} American physician and public health administrator<ref>http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Obesity-called-a-threat-to-U-S-security-845630.php Obesity called a threat to US security</ref>\n* [[Carmen Contreras-Bozak]] (born 1919){{Snd}} first Hispanic to serve in the U.S. Women's Army Corps, where she served as an interpreter and in numerous administrative positions; Puerto Rican; lives in Tampa, Florida<ref name=\"WAC\">[http://www.utopia.utexas.edu/explore/latino/narratives/07Bozak_Carmen.html Young woman's life defined by service in Women's Army Corp] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060919122433/http://utopia.utexas.edu/explore/latino/narratives/07Bozak_Carmen.html |date=2006-09-19 }}</ref>\n* [[Linda Garcia Cubero|Linda Garc\u00eda Cubero]]{{Snd}} former U.S. Air Force officer; of Mexican-American-Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Ruben A. Cubero|Rub\u00e9n A. Cubero]]{{Snd}} highly decorated member of the U.S. Air Force; first Hispanic graduate of the US Air Force Academy to be named Dean of the Faculty of the academy; parents were Puerto Rican<ref name=\"AF\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0RBE/is_2004_Annual/ai_n8572547/ Brigadier General Ruben A. Cubero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111014337/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0RBE/is_2004_Annual/ai_n8572547/ |date=2016-01-11 }}, Retrieved August 15, 2011</ref>\n* [[Alberto D\u00edaz, Jr.]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic Director of the San Diego Naval District and Balboa Naval Hospital; Puerto Rican born and raised\n* [[Rafael O'Ferrall]]{{Snd}} [[United States Army]] officer; first [[Hispanic]] of Puerto Rican descent to become the Deputy Commanding General for the Joint Task Force at [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base|Guantanamo Bay]], [[Cuba]]\n* [[Salvador E. Felices]] (1923\u20131987){{Snd}} first Puerto Rican to reach the rank of major general (two-star) in the U.S. Air Force; died in Florida\n* [[Diego E. Hern\u00e1ndez]]{{Snd}} retired US Navy officer; first Hispanic to be named Vice Commander, North American Aerospace Defense Command; Puerto Rican resident of  Miami\n*[[Lester Mart\u00ednez L\u00f3pez]], MD, MPH (born 1955){{Snd}} first Hispanic to head the Army Medical and Research Command at Fort Detrick, Maryland\n* [[Carlos Lozada]] (1946\u20131967){{Snd}} member of the U.S. Army; one of five Puerto Ricans who posthumously received the Medal of Honor for their actions in combat; Puerto Rican born, raised in New York City\n* [[Angel Mendez|\u00c1ngel M\u00e9ndez]] (1946\u20131967){{Snd}} U.S. Marine, posthumously awarded the Navy Cross\n* [[Virgil Rasmuss Miller]] (1900\u20131968){{Snd}} U.S. Army officer who served as Regimental Commander of the 442d Regimental Combat Team, a unit composed of \"Nisei\" (second generation Americans of Japanese descent), during World War II<ref name=USMA>{{cite journal|url=http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/assembly/vol28no2.pdf |publisher=Association of Graduates, U.S. Military Academy |title=Be Thou at Peace: Virgil Rasmus Miller, Class of 1924 |pages=132\u2013133 |volume=28 |issue=2 |journal=Assembly |date=Summer 1969 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208131753/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/assembly/vol28no2.pdf |archivedate=2012-02-08 }}</ref>\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Andr\u00e9s Negroni]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican historian, senior aerospace defense executive, author; first Puerto Rican graduate of the U.S. Air Force Academy; lives in Vienna, Virginia<ref name=\"ownFamily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rootsweb.com/~prwgw/negroni_01.htm |title=Historical Summary of the Negroni Family |last=Negroni |first=H\u00e9ctor Andr\u00e9s |authorlink=H\u00e9ctor Andr\u00e9s Negroni |date=April 1996 |publisher=Boletin de la Sociedad Puertorrique\u00f1a de Genealog\u00eda Vol VIII |accessdate=11 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006103214/http://www.rootsweb.com/~prwgw/negroni_01.htm |archivedate=6 October 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[Antonia Novello]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican physician and public health administrator; US Surgeon General\n* [[Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s Ortiz]] (1967\u20132007){{Snd}} first American nurse to die in combat during Operation Iraqi Freedom; first Army nurse to die in combat since the Vietnam War; parents were Puerto Rican\n* [[Evelio Otero, Jr.]]{{Snd}} former officer in the U.S. Air Force who led the establishment of the first ever US Central Command Headquarters in Qatar\n[[File:Frederic Louis Riefkohl.JPG|thumb|140px|[[Rudolph W. Riefkohl]]]]\n* [[Hector E. Pagan|H\u00e9ctor E. Pag\u00e1n]]{{Snd}} U.S. Army officer; first Hispanic of Puerto Rican descent to become Deputy Commanding General of the US Army John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Center and School at Fort Bragg, North Carolina\n* [[Jos\u00e9 M. Portela]]{{Snd}} retired officer of the U.S. Air Force; served in the position of Assistant Adjutant General for Air while also serving as commander of the Puerto Rico Air National Guard\n* [[Marion Frederic Ramirez de Arellano|Marion Frederic Ram\u00edrez de Arellano]] (1913\u20131980){{Snd}} submarine commander in the US Navy; first Hispanic submarine commanding officer\n* [[Frederick Lois Riefkohl]] (1889\u20131969){{Snd}} Puerto Rican officer in the U.S. Navy; first Puerto Rican to graduate from the U.S. Naval Academy and to be awarded the Navy Cross; lived and died in Florida<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usna.edu/cemetery/PDF%20Files/Section%206/1129-%20Riefkohl,%20F.%20L.pdf|title=United States Naval Academy Cemetery & Columbarium|access-date=2012-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207103447/http://www.usna.edu/cemetery/PDF%20Files/Section%206/1129-%20Riefkohl,%20F.%20L.pdf|archive-date=2012-02-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Rudolph W. Riefkohl]] (1885\u20131950){{Snd}} US Army officer; instrumental in helping the people of Poland overcome the 1919 typhus epidemic<ref>[http://www.airpower.maxwell.af.mil/airchronicles/aureview/1973/jan-feb/marsh.html Divorce\u2014Military Style]</ref>\n* [[Manuel Rivera, Jr.]] (1959\u20131991) \u2013 first American serviceman of Puerto Rican descent to die in Operation Desert Shield<ref name=\"NYT\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/11/style/chronicle-769392.html?src=pm \"Style\"; New York Times; by: Nadine Brozan; August 11, 1992]</ref>\n* [[Pedro N. Rivera]]{{Snd}} retired Puerto Rican US Air Force officer; in 1994 became the first Hispanic medical commander in the Air Force; lives in [[Alexandria, Virginia]]<ref>[http://www.healthpages.com/directory/physicians/98720/DR_Pedro_N_Rivera_MD.html Healthpages] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029085039/http://www.healthpages.com/directory/physicians/98720/DR_Pedro_N_Rivera_MD.html |date=2007-10-29 }}</ref>\n* [[Elmelindo Rodrigues Smith]] (1935\u20131967) \u2013 U.S. Army soldier posthumously awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] for his actions in the [[Vietnam War]]; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Augusto Rodr\u00edguez (soldier)|Augusto Rodr\u00edguez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican officer in the Union Army during the American Civil War; immigrated to the US in the 1850s<ref name=\"CW\">\"The Puerto Rican Diaspora: historical perspectives\"; By Carmen Teresa Whalen, V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez-Hernandez; page 176; Publisher: Temple University Press; {{ISBN|978-1-59213-413-7}}; {{ISBN|1-59213-413-0}}</ref>\n* [[Pedro Rodr\u00edguez (soldier)|Pedro Rodr\u00edguez]] (1912\u20131999){{Snd}} earned two Silver Stars within a seven-day period during the Korean War; Puerto Rican; died in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"ANC\">[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/pedrorod.htm Arlington National Cemetery]</ref>\n* [[Fernando E. Rodr\u00edguez Vargas]] (1888\u20131932){{Snd}} Puerto Rican odontologist (dentist), scientist and a major in the US Army; discovered the bacteria which causes cavities; died in Washington, D.C.\n* [[Maritza S\u00e1enz Ryan]]{{Snd}} U.S. Army officer; head of the Department of Law at the US Military Academy; first woman and first Hispanic West Point graduate to serve as an academic department head; Puerto Rican father, Spanish mother<ref name=\"PV\">[http://www.usma.edu/dcomm/pv/yr2006/06jan06.pdf Pointer View]</ref>\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Santiago-Col\u00f3n]] (1942\u20131968){{Snd}} one of five Puerto Ricans posthumously presented with the Medal of Honor, the highest military decoration awarded by the U.S.; Puerto Rican from New York<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate=October 5, 2010 |url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n45/ProfileSantColon-es.html |title=Puerto Rico Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303194555/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n45/ProfileSantColon-es.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n* [[Frankie Segarra]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic to reach the rank of Master Gunnery Sergeant in his military occupational specialty, 0451 air delivery specialist; parents were Puerto Rican<ref name=\"HHM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usmc.mil/marinelink/image1.nsf/Lookup/200410614333?opendocument|accessdate=2006-05-16|title=Hispanic Heritage Month|work=Marine Corps News|date=October 1, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041112124218/http://www.usmc.mil/marinelink/mcn2000.nsf/lookupstoryref/200410614134|archivedate=2004-11-12}}</ref>\n* [[Frances M. Vega]] (1983\u20132003){{Snd}} first female soldier of Puerto Rican descent to die in a combat zone, in Operation Iraqi Freedom\n* [[Pedro del Valle]] (1893\u20131978){{Snd}} U.S. Marine Corps officer; first Hispanic to reach the rank of lieutenant general; in 1900 his family emigrated to the US and became US citizens<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/delValle_PA.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516214408/http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/delValle_PA.htm |archivedate=2011-05-16 }} Who's Who in Marine Corps History</ref>\n* [[Humbert Roque Versace]] (1937\u20131965) \u2013 American U.S. Army officer of Puerto Rican-Italian descent; awarded the US' highest military decoration, the Medal of Honor, for his heroic actions while a prisoner of war during the Vietnam War<ref>http://www.elboricua.com/MedalHonor.html Puerto Rican Medal of Honor</ref>\n\n== Political ==\n* [[Herman Badillo]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-born US Representative; first Puerto Rican elected to the US Congress\n* [[Roberto Rexach Ben\u00edtez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican politician; former Senator and Representative\n* [[Adolfo Carri\u00f3n, Jr.]]{{Snd}} [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[politician]]; of Puerto Rican descent, from [[City Island, New York]]<ref>Pickert, Kate; and Jame, Randy [http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1880883,00.html \"Urban Policy Director Adolfo Carrion\"], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', February 20, 2009. Accessed October 15, 2009. \"Is 47 and married to a lawyer. They have three daughters and a son and live on City Island in the Bronx.\"</ref>\n* [[Ruth Noem\u00ed Col\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican; 66th Secretary of State of New York\n* [[Pedro Cort\u00e9s]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican former Secretary of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania\n[[File: Rub\u00e9n D\u00edaz, Jr., 2012.jpg|thumb|150px|Rub\u00e9n D\u00edaz, Jr.]]\n* [[Lorraine Cort\u00e9s-V\u00e1zquez]]{{Snd}} 65th Secretary of State of New York, serving in the Cabinet of Governor David Paterson; of Puerto Rican and [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] descent<ref>[http://www.danr.org/ip.asp?op=Press080922 New York Secretary of State Lorraine Cort\u00e9s - V\u00e1zquez To Address The DANR 11th Annual National Conference in Providence] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115221853/http://www.danr.org/ip.asp?op=Press080922 |date=2009-01-15 }} from ''The Dominican American National Roundtable'', date September 22, 2008. Retrieved June 13, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Nelson Antonio Denis]]{{Snd}} American former New York politician who represented [[East Harlem]] in the [[New York State Assembly]]; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Rub\u00e9n D\u00edaz, Sr.]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican born US politician; Democrat; represents the 32nd District in the New York State Senate<ref>http://www.nysenate.gov/senator/ruben-diaz/bio Ruben Diaz's Biography</ref>\n* [[Rub\u00e9n D\u00edaz, Jr.]]{{Snd}} Democratic Party politician from the Bronx in New York City; son of New York State Senator Rub\u00e9n D\u00edaz, Sr.\n* [[Wilda Diaz|Wilda D\u00edaz]]{{Snd}} Mayor of [[Perth Amboy, New Jersey]] in May 2008\n* [[Martin Malave Dilan|Mart\u00edn Malav\u00e9 Dil\u00e1n]]{{Snd}} member of the New York State Senate representing the 17th Senatorial District\n* [[Pedro Espada, Jr.]]{{Snd}} Democratic member of the New York Senate for the 33rd Senate District; Puerto Rican born, American raised<ref>Rauh, Grace. [http://www.ny1.com/content/news_beats/politics/90167/bronx-s-espada-to-be-top-hispanic-state-official/Default.aspx \"Bronx's Espada To Be Top Hispanic State Official\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[NY1]]'', June 6, 2008. Accessed June 9, 2009.</ref>\n[[File:Maurice Ferre 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|Maurice Ferre]]\n[[File:Josieserrano.jpeg|thumb|150px|Josie Serrano]]\n[[File:Gloria Tristani.jpg|thumb|150px|Gloria Tristani]]\n* [[Maurice Ferre|Maurice Ferr\u00e9]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican former six-term Mayor of Miami\n* [[Bonnie Garcia|Bonnie Garc\u00eda]]{{Snd}} former representative of California's 80th Assembly District, serving eastern Riverside County and all of Imperial County\n* [[Robert Garcia (New York politician)|Robert Garc\u00eda]]{{Snd}} former Democratic US Representative who represented New York's 21st district, 1978\u20131990\n* [[Luis Guti\u00e9rrez]]{{Snd}} US Representative; American of Puerto Rican descent<ref name=\"Ndia\">{{cite news|title=Los independentistas eran los que m\u00e1s me aceptaban|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/losindependentistaseranlosquemasmeaceptaban-799839.html|accessdate=17 October 2010|newspaper=El Nuevo Dia|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* [[Ra\u00f