al G. Villaronga]]{{Snd}} retired Puerto Rican US Army officer; first Puerto Rican mayor of a Texas city; elected Mayor of [[Killeen, Texas]] in 1992<ref>http://groups.google.com/group/Jibaros/browse_thread/thread/1b425f86e8204aaf Jibaros.com</ref>\n\n==Visual arts==\n* [[Olga Albizu]] (1924\u20132005){{Snd}} Puerto Rican abstract expressionist painter; emigrated to New York in 1948<ref>[http://www.biaggifaure.com/artist-oalbizu.htm#3 Olga Albizu artist profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707232625/http://www.biaggifaure.com/artist-oalbizu.htm#3 |date=2011-07-07 }} at Biaggi Faure Fine Art</ref>\n* [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]] (1960\u20131988){{Snd}} visual artist; African-American of Haitian and Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://thecreativeroutine.tumblr.com/post/918691970/hailing-from-brookyln-jean-michel-basquiat TheCreativeRoutine \u2022 Hailing from Brookyln, Jean-Michel Basquiat]. Retrieved July 27, 2011, to 13:55 pm.</ref>\n* [[David Blaine]]{{Snd}} American illusionist, magician, and endurance artist; of Puerto Rican-Russian Jewish descent<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/19/news/cl-54095 The Houdini of the Hoi Polloi], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 2000-11-19</ref>\n* [[Rafael Ferrer (artist)|Rafael Ferrer]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican artist; 1993 recipient of a Pew Fellowship in the Arts; 2011 recipient of an Annalee and Barnett Newman Foundation Grant\n*[[Elizabeth Marrero]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican performance artist, comedian, known as Macha, the \"papi chulo drag king,\" a character she created in 1999; lives in the US\n* [[Soraida Martinez|Soraida Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} contemporary abstract expressionist artist who creates hard-edge paintings; American of Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/education/teacherartexchange/archive/Feb04/0113.html The Getty: Latino Artist you will LOVE - Soraida Martinez] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303185008/http://www.getty.edu/education/teacherartexchange/archive/Feb04/0113.html |date=2016-03-03 }}</ref>\n* [[Ralph Ortiz]]{{Snd}} American artist, educator, and founder of [[El Museo del Barrio]]\n* [[Manuel Rivera-Ortiz]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican documentary photographer; lives in the US<ref>http://www.jacketflap.com/manuel-rivera-ortiz/19862 About Manuel Rivera-Ortiz</ref>\n* [[Joe Shannon (artist)|Joe Shannon]] \u2013 prolific artist with permanent exhibits in multiple museums in the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edspace.american.edu/artkatzen/2008/05/|title=May 2008 \u2013 Art at the Katzen|date=2008|website=American University|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n* [[Filipo Tirado]], aka \"Pepe Locuaz\"{{Snd}} Puerto Rican puppeteer\n\n== Civil rights and activists ==\n[[File:Mathias Brugman.JPG|thumb|140px|[[Mathias Brugman]]]]\n* [[Mathias Brugman]] (1811\u20131868){{Snd}} leader in Puerto Rico's independence revolution against Spain known as [[Grito de Lares|El Grito de Lares (The Cry of Lares)]]; father was Pierre Brugman from [[Cura\u00e7ao]] of [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-[[Jewish]] ancestry, mother was from Puerto Rico\n* [[Oscar Collazo]] (1914\u20131994){{Snd}} one of two Puerto Ricans who attempted to assassinate US President [[Harry S. Truman]]\n* [[Angelo Falc\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} political scientist; President and founder of [[National Institute for Latino Policy]]; Puerto Rican born and American raised\n* [[Inez Garc\u00eda|In\u00e9z Garc\u00eda]]{{Snd}} cause celebre of the feminist movement; of Puerto Rican and Cuban descent\n* [[Olga Viscal Garriga]] (1929\u20131995){{Snd}} public orator, political activist; descendant of a former governor of Puerto Rico; advocate for Puerto Rican independence\n* [[Isabel Gonz\u00e1lez]] (1882\u20131971){{Snd}} Puerto Rican activist who helped pave the way for Puerto Ricans to be given US citizenship; lived in New York and New Jersey<ref>http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/cgi-bin/getcase.pl?court=us&vol=192&invol=1 U.S. Supreme Court</ref>\n* [[Sonia Gutierrez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-born American educator and Hispanic rights activist.\n* [[Marie Hayd\u00e9e Beltr\u00e1n Torres]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1980/05/24/archives/mrs-torres-gets-life-term-for-fatal-bombing-in-1977-linked-to-the.html Mrs. Torres Gets Life Term For Fatal Bombing in 1977], ''The New York Times'', 24 May 1980</ref>\n* [[\u00d3scar L\u00f3pez Rivera]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803E5DA163DF93BA3575AC0A96F958260|title=12 Imprisoned Puerto Ricans Accept Clemency Conditions|accessdate=17 September 2008|work=The New York Times|date=1999-11-08|author=John M. Broder}}</ref> pardoned by President Barack Obama\n* [[Rosa Mart\u00ednez and Eliana Mart\u00ednez|Eliana Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} young AIDS activist in notable Florida court case regarding the rights of HIV+ children in public schools* [[Sylvia Mendez|Sylvia M\u00e9ndez]]{{Snd}} American civil rights activist; of Mexican-Puerto Rican heritage<ref>http://neatoday.org/2011/02/16/sylvia-mendez-school-desegregation-pioneer-honored-at-white-house/ Sylvia Mendez, School Desegregation Pioneer, Honored at White House. published February 16, 2011 by twalker.</ref>\n* [[Eugene Nelson]]{{Snd}} American labor leader\n\n[[File:ACLU Anthony D Romero.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Anthony Romero]]]]\n* [[Manuel Olivieri Sanchez|Manuel Olivieri S\u00e1nchez]] (born 1888){{Snd}} Puerto Rican court interpreter and civil rights activist; led the legal battle which recognized US citizenship for Puerto Ricans living in Hawaii\n* [[Carmen Pola]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican long-time politician and community activist in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]; first Latina to run for statewide office; first Director of the Office of Constituent Services\n* [[Ron Rivera (public health)|Ronald Rivera]] (1948\u20132008){{Snd}} American activist best known for developing an inexpensive ceramic water filter used to treat gray water in impoverished communities, and for establishing community-based factories to produce the filters around the world\n* [[Sylvia Rae Rivera]] (1951\u20132002){{Snd}} American [[transgender activism|transgender activist]]; founding member of the [[Gay Liberation Front]] and the [[Gay Activists Alliance]]; helped found STAR ([[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]]); of Puerto Rican and Venezuelan descent<ref name=Gan>Gan, Jessi. [http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf \"'Still at the Back of the Bus': Sylvia Rivera's Struggle\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175345/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf |date=2012-04-06 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 124-139.</ref>\n* [[Helen Rodriguez-Trias|Helen Rodr\u00edguez-Tr\u00edas]] (1929\u20132001){{Snd}} American pediatrician, educator and women's rights activist<ref name=\"FoM\">[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_273.html Changing the Face of Medicine]</ref>\n* [[Anthony Romero]]{{Snd}} American executive director of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]]\n* [[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]] (1874\u20131938){{Snd}} Puerto Rican historian, writer, and activist in the US who raised awareness of the social contributions made by Afro-Latin Americans and Afro-Americans; died in New York<ref name=\"AA\">[http://www.pww.org/past-weeks-2001/Arturo%20Alfonso%20Schomburg.htm \"Arturo Alfonso Schomburg: Pionero en la historia afronorteamericana\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227055402/http://pww.org/past-weeks-2001/Arturo%20Alfonso%20Schomburg.htm |date=2009-02-27 }}, ''Nuestro Mondo/People's Weekly World'', accessed 2 Feb 2009</ref>\n*Yolanda Serrano{{Snd}} HIV/AIDS activist and a ''Ms.'' magazine woman of the year\n* [[Alejandrina Torres]]{{Snd}} nationalist<ref>{{cite book|last=Torres|first=Andr\u00e9s|title=The Puerto Rican movement: voices from the diaspora|publisher=Temple University Press|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKJtYNvKKrgC&pg=PA147&dq=Alejandrina+Torres+no+defense#PPA149,M1|accessdate=2009-03-19 | isbn=978-1-56639-618-9}}</ref>\n* [[Griselio Torresola]] (1925\u20131950){{Snd}} one of two Puerto Rican Nationalists who attempted to assassinate US President Harry Truman; Puerto Rico born\n\n== Physicians and scientists ==\n[[File:Joseph Acaba v2.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Joseph M. Acaba]]]]\n* [[Joseph M. Acaba|Joseph M. Acab\u00e1]]{{Snd}} American educator, hydrogeologist, and NASA astronaut; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"Astronomy PR\"/>\n* [[Oxiris Barbot]], Commissioner of Health of the City of New York\n* [[V\u00edctor Manuel Blanco]], PhD (1918\u20132011){{Snd}} Puerto Rican astronomer; in 1959 discovered \"Blanco 1,\" a galactic cluster; died in Florida<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/BATESVILLE/Obituaries.asp?Page=Notice&PersonID=149179574 Obituary at Legacy.com]</ref>\n* [[Rafael L. Bras|Rafael L. Br\u00e1s]]{{Snd}} American civil engineer; Provost to the Georgia Institute of Technology; Puerto Rican-born\n* [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]]{{Snd}} American [[astrophysics|astrophysicist]], author, and [[science communication|science communicator]]. His mother is of Puerto Rican ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bried|first=Erin|title=Sunchita Tyson|url=http://howtorockyourbaby.com/moms|work=How to Rock Your Baby and other timeless tips for modern moms|publisher=Hyperion|accessdate=2 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320010721/http://howtorockyourbaby.com/moms/|archive-date=2014-03-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Enectal\u00ed Figueroa-Feliciano]], PhD, aka \"Tali\"{{Snd}} astrophysicist and researcher with NASA Goddard Space Flight Center; pioneered the development of position-sensitive detectors\n* [[Ger\u00f3nimo Lluberas]] (1956\u20132003){{Snd}} Puerto Rican physician, humanitarian, writer and composer\n* [[Ram\u00f3n E. L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} space physicist and author\n* [[Lissette Martinez|Lissette Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} lead electrical engineer for the Space Experiment Module program at the [[Wallops Flight Facility]]\n* [[Joseph O. Prewitt D\u00edaz]], PhD{{Snd}} retired psychologist; specialized in psychosocial theory; first Puerto Rican recipient of the American Psychological Association; 2008 International Humanitarian Award<ref>American Psychologist (2008) 63 (8), 327-333.</ref>\n* [[Pedro Rodriguez (NASA)|Pedro Rodr\u00edguez]], PhD{{Snd}} Director of a test laboratory at NASA; inventor of a portable, battery-operated lift seat for people suffering from knee arthritis\n* [[Fernando E. Rodr\u00edguez Vargas]], DDS (1888\u20131932){{Snd}} odontologist (dentist), scientist and a major in the US Army who discovered the bacteria which causes cavities\n* [[Gualberto Rua\u00f1o]], MD, PhD{{Snd}} pioneer in the field of personalized medicine; inventor of molecular diagnostic systems used worldwide for the management of viral diseases\n\n== Religious ==\n* [[Nicky Cruz]] (born 1938){{Snd}} Christian evangelist; founder of Nicky Cruz Outreach, an evangelistic Christian ministry\n* [[Alberto Cuti\u00e9]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican Episcopal cleric better known as Padre Alberto; ordained a Roman Catholic priest in 1995; became an internationally recognizable name by hosting television and radio programs\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Luis de Jes\u00fas]]{{Snd}} founder and leader of Creciendo en Gracia's Christian ministry (Growing In Grace International Ministry, Inc.), based in Miami, Florida\n* [[Bavi Edna Rivera]], aka \"Nedi\"{{Snd}} American suffragan bishop and Episcopal priest; daughter of the late bishop Victor Manuel Rivera and an Anglo mother<ref name=\"A\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecww.org/files/5/BishopRiveraBiography.pdf |title=Diocese of Olympia |access-date=2010-12-14 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5uy9LSiCr?url=http://www.ecww.org/files/5/BishopRiveraBiography.pdf |archive-date=2010-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Victor Manuel Rivera|V\u00edctor Manuel Rivera]] (1916\u20132005){{Snd}} Puerto Rican born American Episcopalian priest and bishop\n\n==Writers==\n\n* [[Jack Ag\u00fceros]]{{Snd}} community activist, poet, writer, and translator\n* [[Quiara Alegr\u00eda Hudes]]{{Snd}} American playwright and author, known for writing the book for the Tony Award-winning musical ''In the Heights''; of Jewish and Puerto Rican descent<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143122-26-Miles-Quiara-Hudes-Mother-Daughter-Road-Trip-Tale-Gets-Chicago-Premiere-Starting-Oct-16 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921071804/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/143122-26-Miles-Quiara-Hudes-Mother-Daughter-Road-Trip-Tale-Gets-Chicago-Premiere-Starting-Oct-16 |archivedate=2010-09-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Miguel Algar\u00edn]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet, writer, co-founder of the Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9\n* [[Rane Arroyo]] (1954\u20132010){{Snd}} American poet, playwright, and scholar; of Puerto Rican descent\n* [[Pura Belpr\u00e9]] (1899 or 1903\u20131982){{Snd}} author; first Puerto Rican librarian in New York City<ref>Nu\u00f1ez,Victoria. \"Remembering Pura Belpr\u00e9's Early Career at the 135th Street New York Public Library: Interracial Cooperation and Puerto Rican Settlement during the Harlem Renaissance.\" Centro Journal 21.1 (2009): 52-77. Print.</ref>\n* [[Giannina Braschi]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet and novelist; lives in New York<ref>https://books.google.com/books/about/Cuerpos_Errantes_wandering_Bodies.html?id=zj0tihPBymUC Cuerpos Errantes/wandering Bodies:\nLiteratura Latina Y Latinoamericana En Estados Unidos/latin And Latinamerican Literature In The United States</ref>\n* [[Julia de Burgos]] (1914\u20131953){{Snd}} considered by many as the greatest Puerto Rican poet and one of the greatest female poets of Latin America; died in New York<ref>[http://www.literatura.us/julia/crono.html Julia de Burgos. Literatura.es]</ref>\n* [[Judith Ortiz Cofer]] (born 1952){{Snd}} author; Puerto Rican-born and American raised<ref>http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-488 Judith Ortiz Cofer</ref>\n* [[Jes\u00fas Col\u00f3n]] (1901\u20131974){{Snd}} Puerto Rican writer, known as the \"father of the Nuyorican movement\"<ref name=\"Colon\">[http://www.ccc.commnet.edu/latinoguide/secondary/JesusColon.htm Jesus Colon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722154410/http://www.ccc.commnet.edu/latinoguide/secondary/JesusColon.htm |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n* [[Victor Hern\u00e1ndez Cruz|V\u00edctor Hern\u00e1ndez Cruz]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet; New York resident<ref name=poets>[http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/681 Poets.org - Poetry, Poems, Bios & More - Victor Hern\u00e1ndez Cruz<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* [[Nicholas Dante]] (1941\u20131991){{Snd}} American dancer and writer; Puerto Rican parents<ref>{{cite news|first=Natalie|last=Crohn Schmitt|title=Complicates|year=1990|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GRL-8cD6n5oC&pg=PA85&dq=nicholas+dante+puerto&ei=Y8tBSq-zF6GeygTqyJhO|publication-date=1990|ISBN=0-8101-0836-4|publisher=Northwestern University Press|page= 85}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Denis]] (born 1954){{Snd}} Author of ''War Against All Puerto Ricans,'' film director, and former New York State Assemblyman\n* [[Sandra Mar\u00eda Esteves]]{{Snd}} American poet, playwright, and graphic artist; of Puerto Rican, Dominican and African American descent<ref>PBS. [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/americancollection/woman/ei_poetry_esteves.html \"Puerto Rican Poetry\"]. Retrieved July 30, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Lawrence La Fountain-Stokes]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author, scholar, and performer; lives in Michigan\n* [[Pedro J. Labarthe]] (1905\u20131966){{Snd}} Puerto Rican poet, journalist, essayist, and novelist\n* [[Tato Laviera]]{{Snd}} Nuyorican poet; born in Puerto Rico; moved to New York City with his family in 1960\n* [[Muna Lee (writer)|Muna Lee]] (1895\u20131965){{Snd}} American author and poet; known for her writings that promoted Pan-Americanism and feminism\n* [[Erika Lopez|\u00c9rika L\u00f3pez]]{{Snd}} American cartoonist, novelist, and performance artist; of Puerto Rican and German American descent<ref>[[Lawrence La Fountain-Stokes|La Fountain-Stokes, Lawrence]]. ''Queer Ricans: Cultures and Sexualities in the Diaspora.'' Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2009, page 126. {{ISBN|0-8166-4092-0}}</ref>\n* [[Caridad de la Luz]], aka \"La Bruja\" (The \"Good\" Witch){{Snd}} poet, actress and activist; parents are Puerto Rican<ref name=\"LP\">[http://www.eldiariony.com/noticias/especiales/detail.aspx?EspecialId=26&id=1098418 El Diario/La Prensa - Caridad de la Luz]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190806/http://www.eldiariony.com/noticias/especiales/detail.aspx?EspecialId=26&id=1098418 |date=September 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Nemir Matos-Cintr\u00f3n]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author; lives in Florida\n[[File:Arturo Alfonso Schomburg.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]]]]\n* [[John Melendez|John Mel\u00e9ndez]], aka \"Stuttering John\"{{Snd}} American television writer and former radio personality\n* [[Nicholasa Mohr]]{{Snd}} one of the best known Nuyorican writers<ref>[http://www.bookrags.com/biography/nicholasa-mohr-dlb/ Dictionary of Literary Biography intro online]</ref>\n* [[Micol Ostow]]{{Snd}} American author, editor and educator; [[Jewish-American]] father, Puerto Rican mother<ref name=\"LJ\">[http://slayground.livejournal.com/293625.html Live Journal]</ref>\n* [[George P\u00e9rez]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican-American writer and illustrator of comic books; his family moved from [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]] to the [[New York metropolitan area|New York area]] in the 1940s<ref>{{cite book |title= Modern Masters Volume 2: George P\u00e9rez |last= Nolen-Weathington|first= Eric|authorlink= |year= 2003|publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |isbn= 1-893905-25-X |page= 6|quote = My mom, Luz Maria Izquierdo, and my father, Jorge P\u00e9rez, were both born in Caguas, Puerto Rico, the same year but would not actually meet each other until they moved{{Snd}} I believe the same year, I don't know the exact year{{Snd}} to New Jersey...by the time they were married they had moved to New York.|url= https://books.google.com/?id=bhOPZ2u7C_YC&pg=PA6&dq=George+P%C3%A9rez+Caguas+Luz+Maria+Izquierdo+Jorge+P%C3%A9rez#v=onepage&q=George%20P%C3%A9rez%20Caguas%20Luz%20Maria%20Izquierdo%20Jorge%20P%C3%A9rez&f=false|accessdate= November 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Pedro Pietri]] (1944\u20132004){{Snd}} Nuyorican poet and playwright; co-founded the Nuyorican Poets Cafe; Puerto Rican born and American raised<ref name=\"Pietri\">[http://www.monthlyreview.org/0604pietri.htm Monthly Review]</ref>\n* [[Carmen M. Pursifull]]{{Snd}} former New York City Latin dance and Latin American music figure of the 1950s, and since 1970 in Illinois; English-language free verse poet; of Puerto Rican and Spanish descent<ref>''Probing the Depths, supra,'' at 230.</ref> \n* [[Marie Teresa R\u00edos]] (1917\u20131999){{Snd}} American author of a book which was the basis for the 1960s television sitcom ''[[The Flying Nun]]''; of Puerto Rican and Irish descent{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n* [[\u00c1ngel Rivero M\u00e9ndez]], wrote {{lang|es|Cr\u00f3nica de la guerra hispano-americana en Puerto Rico}}, which is considered one of the most complete works written in regard to that military action\n*[[Esmeralda Santiago]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican author and former actress known for her novels and memoirs\n* [[Tony Santiago]]{{Snd}} Puerto Rican military historian\n* [[Arturo Alfonso Schomburg]], aka Arthur Schomburg (1874\u20131938){{Snd}} Puerto Rican historian, writer, and activist in the US who raised awareness of the social contributions made by Afro-Latin Americans and Afro-Americans; died in New York; immigrated to New York in 1891<ref name=\"AB\">[http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/schomburg.html Robert Knight, \"Arthur Alfonso 'Afroborinque\u00f1o' Schomburg\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000142/http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/schomburg.html |date=2007-09-28 }}, History Notes, Global African Community, accessed 2 Feb 2009</ref>\n*[[Piri Thomas]] (1928\u20132011){{Snd}} writer and American poet; memoir ''Down These Mean Streets'' became a best-seller; Puerto Rican mother, Cuban father\n* [[Edwin Torres (poet)|Edwin Torres]]{{Snd}} Nuyorican poet\n* [[Ed Vega]] (1936\u20132008){{Snd}} Puerto Rican novelist and short story writer<ref name=\"nytobit\">Weber, Bruce (September 9, 2008). [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/09/books/09vegayunque.html Edgardo Vega Yunqu\u00e9, Novelist of the Puerto Rican Experience in New York, Dies at 72.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>\n* [[Irene Vilar]]{{Snd}} editor, literary agent, author of books dealing with national and generational trauma and women's reproductive rights\n* [[William Carlos Williams]] (1883\u20131963){{Snd}} American poet, closely associated with modernism and Imagism; of English and Puerto Rican descent<ref>[http://www.gpaulbishop.com/GPB%20History/GPB%20Archive/Section%20-%205/W.C.%20Williams/w_c__williams.htm WILLIAM CARLOS WILLIAMS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723145404/http://www.gpaulbishop.com/GPB%20History/GPB%20Archive/Section%20-%205/W.C.%20Williams/w_c__williams.htm |date=2011-07-23 }}</ref>\n\n== Others ==\n* [[A\u00edda \u00c1lvarez]]{{Snd}} first Hispanic woman and Puerto Rican to hold a US Cabinet-level position; grew up in New York<ref>http://www.gale.cengage.com/free_resources/chh/bio/alvarez_a.htm Hispanic Heritage.</ref>\n* [[Nixzmary Brown]] (1998\u20132006){{Snd}} seven-year-old abused child and murder victim from the Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn section of New York City; of Puerto Rican and Pakistanian descent<ref>http://www.eternalportal.com/tributes/nixzmary-brown/default.asp?action=showpage&pid=104 Online Memorial Tribute</ref>\n* [[Marta Casals Istomin]]{{Snd}} former president of the [[Manhattan School of Music]]; Puerto Rican born<ref name=\"PRH\">[http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/vol3n33/ProfileMCasalsIstomin-en.html Puerto Rico Herald]</ref>\n* [[Chris Kubecka]] {{Snd}} (full name Christina Kubecka de Medina, Computer Science, Cyberwar) established international business operations for [[Saudi Aramco]] after the world's most devastating [[Shamoon]] [[cyberwarfare]] attacks. Kubecka helped halt the second wave of [[July 2009 cyberattacks]] cyberwar attacks against South Korea. \n* [[Angie Martinez|Angie Mart\u00ednez]]{{Snd}} American radio personality\n* [[Samuel A. Ramirez, Sr.|Samuel A. Ram\u00edrez, Sr.]]{{Snd}} first [[Hispanic]] to launch a successful investment banking firm; parents are Puerto Ricans\n* [[F\u00e9lix Rigau Carrera]] (1894\u20131954){{Snd}} first Puerto Rican pilot<ref>{{Cite news|accessdate=|work=Gloucester Gazette-Journal|title=Gloucester Deaths |date=October 19, 1954}}</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez (intelligence)]]{{Snd}} head of [[CIA]] division (2004\u20132008)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n* [[List of Hispanic and Latino Americans]]\n* [[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n* [[List of Spanish Americans]]\n* [[Puerto Rican migration to New York]]\n* [[Puerto Rican citizenship]]\n* [[Outline of Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Cultural diversity in Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Corsican immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Chinese immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[French immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Crypto-Judaism]]\n**[[German immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Irish immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n**[[Royal Decree of Graces of 1815]]\n* [[Index of Puerto Rico-related articles]]\n* [[History of women in Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Military history of Puerto Rico]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Piragua (food)]]\n* [[51st state|51-star flag]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090207004017/http://us-puertoricans.org/ US Puerto Ricans.org Re/envisioning the Diaspora]\n\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of American people by ethnic or national origin|Puerto Ricans, List Of Stateside]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by ethnicity|Puerto Rican]]\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCivil rights and activists:bad link repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Stateside_Puerto_Ricans"}
{"title_page": "Sylvia Rivera", "text_new": "{{For|Bolivian feminist and theorist|Silvia Rivera Cusicanqui}}\n{{Short description|20th-century American gay liberation and transgender rights activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n<!--Per Wikipedia:Manual of style, use she/her to refer to Sylvia Rivera throughout her life.-->\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Sylvia Rivera\n|image = Sylvia Rae Rivera.jpg\n|caption = Rivera, in the \"gay camp\" at the Christopher Street Piers {{circa}} 2000\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1951|07|02}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2002|02|19|1951|07|02}}\n|death_place = New York City, United States\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality = American\n|occupation = [[Activism|Activist]]\n|known_for = [[Gay liberation]],<ref name=\"nytobit\">Dunlap, David W. (February 20, 2002). Sylvia Rivera, 50, Figure in Birth of the Gay Liberation Movement. ''New York Times''</ref> [[transgender]] activist, advocate for the homeless.<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/35975275 |title= Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier |time=Repeatedly throughout interview}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref>\n}}\n'''Sylvia Rivera''' (July 2, 1951 \u2013 February 19, 2002) was a [[Latinas|Latina]] American [[gay liberation]] and [[transgender activism|transgender rights activist]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/20/nyregion/sylvia-rivera-50-figure-in-birth-of-the-gay-liberation-movement.html|title=Sylvia Rivera, 50, Figure in Birth of the Gay Liberation Movement|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=February 20, 2002|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 1, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=RiveraInterview95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/35975275  |title= Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier |time=14:17}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 Transgender People Who Influenced American Culture|url=http://time.com/130734/transgender-celebrities-actors-athletes-in-america/|publisher=Time Magazine}}</ref> prominent as an activist and community worker in [[LGBT history in New York|New York]]. Rivera, who identified as a [[drag queen]],<ref name=QueensInExile>Rivera, Sylvia, \"Queens In Exile, The Forgotten Ones\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"feinberg1\">Leslie Feinberg (September 24, 2006). [http://www.workers.org/2006/us/lavender-red-73/ Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries.] ''[[Workers World Party]]''. \"Stonewall combatants Sylvia Rivera and Marsha \"Pay It No Mind\" Johnson... Both were self-identified drag queens.\"</ref><ref name=Rivera95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/37548074 |title= Sylvia Rivera Reflects on the Spirit of Marsha P Johnson |time=1:27}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref> participated in demonstrations with the [[Gay Liberation Front]].<ref name=GLFphotos>Photographs by [[Diana Davies (photographer)|Diana Davies]], in the Gay Liberation Front series: [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/91436004-b7ea-9d9a-e040-e00a180668be Rivera wears an \"E\" t-shirt] in a line of activists to spell out \"Gay Power\".</ref>\n\nWith close friend [[Marsha P. Johnson]], Rivera co-founded the [[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]] (STAR), a group dedicated to helping homeless young drag queens, gay youth, and [[trans woman|trans women]].<ref name=\"NPR\">[[Marsha P. Johnson]] died in 1992. In 2001, Rivera \"resurrected\" the group, renaming it \"Street Transgender Action Revolutionaries.\" SoundPortraits (July 4, 2001). [http://soundportraits.org/on-air/remembering_stonewall/update.php Update on Remembering Stonewall.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702203403/http://soundportraits.org/on-air/remembering_stonewall/update.php |date=July 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRivera was born and raised in New York City and lived most of her life in or near the city; she was of [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] and [[Venezuelan American|Venezuelan]] descent.<ref name=QueensInExile/> She was abandoned by her birth father Jos\u00e9 Rivera early in life and became an orphan after her mother died by suicide when Rivera was three years old.<ref name=Gan>Gan, Jessi. [https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37719107.pdf \"'Still at the Back of the Bus': Sylvia Rivera's Struggle\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175345/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf |date=April 6, 2012 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 124\u2013139.</ref> Rivera was then raised by her Venezuelan grandmother, who disapproved of Rivera's effeminate behavior, particularly after Rivera began to wear makeup in fourth grade.<ref name=Gan/> As a result, Rivera began living on the streets at the age of 11 and was forced to work as a [[Child prostitution|child prostitute]]. She was taken in by the local community of [[drag queen]]s, who gave her the name Sylvia.<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{cite book|author=Cohen, Stephan|date=2007|title=The Gay Liberation Youth Movement in New York: 'An Army of Lovers Cannot Fail'|location=London|publisher=[[Routledge]]|pages=|isbn=0-8070-7941-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/transgenderwarri00fein}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nRivera's activism began in 1970 after she joined the [[Gay Activists Alliance]] at 18 years old, where she fought for not only the rights of gay people but also for the inclusion of drag queens like herself in the movement.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gaycitynews.nyc/stories/2019/15/david-carter-stonewall-2019-06-27-gcn.html |title=Exploding the Myths of Stonewall |author=Carter, David |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref>  Rivera sometimes exaggerated her importance, purporting to have been active during the [[civil rights movement]] and through the [[opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|movement against the Vietnam war]] and [[Second-wave feminism#Overview in the United States|second-wave feminist movement]]s, but she could not prove her claims.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> After her older friend, [[Marsha P. Johnson]], was being praised for being involved in the [[Stonewall Riots]], Rivera  claimed that she was also present there.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/><ref name=LGMNY>Rivera, Sylvia. [https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37719106.pdf \"Sylvia Rivera's Talk at LGMNY, June 2001, Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center, New York City\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175409/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719106.pdf |date=April 6, 2012 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 116\u2013123.</ref> Stonewall historian David Carter, however, questioned Rivera's claims to have ever been at the riots that night, based on contradictory statements she made as well as testimony relayed to him by early gay rights activists, including [[Marsha P. Johnson]], who denied Rivera was present at the riots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaytoday.com/interview/070104in.asp|title=David Carter: Historian of The Stonewall Riots|publisher=Gay Today|author=Paul D. Cain}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Rivera famously spoke at a gay rights rally after she and Johnson were reportedly banned for making other gay activists \"look bad\". Afterwards, she told anyone who would listen that she was involved in the Stonewall riots, to which Johnson replied, \"Sylvia, you know you weren't there\", after which Rivera was silent.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> When the Stonewall riots occurred, Rivera was only 17 years old and according to [[Bob Kohler]], who was there on the two nights of the riots, \"always hung out uptown at Bryant Park\" and never came downtown.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Johnson told gay rights historian Eric Marcus in 1987 that in the hours prior to her arriving downtown to join the other protesters at the riots, she had a party uptown and mentioned that \"Rivera and them were over in the [Bryant] park having a cocktail.\"<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Kohler told Carter that, although Rivera had not been at the uprising, he hoped Carter would nonetheless portray her as having been there. Another Stonewall veteran, Thomas Lanigan-Schmidt, claimed that he wanted to add her \"so that young Puerto Rican transgender people on the street would have a role model.\"<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Kohler and Rivera had a discussion over what to include in the book and denied Rivera's requests to be portrayed as being the one to throw the first molotov cocktail, throwing the first brick, and having thrown the first bottle, only allowing Rivera to be portrayed as someone who had \"thrown a bottle\" as opposed to being \"the first\".<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> [[Randy Wicker]], who was part of the more assimilationist [[Mattachine Society]] and was an early critic of the violent, militant tactics used by Johnson and other Stonewall veterans, said Johnson had told him that Sylvia was not at Stonewall \"as she was asleep after taking heroin uptown\".<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Rivera would also claim to have been involved in Puerto Rican and African American youth activism, particularly with the [[Young Lords]] and [[Black Panthers]].<ref name=Gan/>\n\nAt different times in her life, Rivera battled [[substance abuse]] and lived on the streets, largely in the gay homeless community at the [[Christopher Street]] docks.<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95/> Her experiences made her more focused on advocacy for those who, in her view, mainstream society and the [[cultural assimilation|assimilationist]] sectors of the lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender ([[LGBT]]) communities were leaving behind.<ref name=Cleninden171>Clendinen, Dudley, and Nagourney, Adam (1999). ''Out for Good'', Simon & Schuster. {{ISBN|0-684-81091-3}}, pp. 171\u2013172.</ref> For these reasons Rivera projected her voice to give her community power. She fought for herself but most importantly for the rights of people of color and low-income LGBT people. As someone who suffered from systematic poverty and racism, Rivera used her voice for unity, sharing her stories, pain, and struggles to show her community they are not alone. She amplified the voices of the most vulnerable members of the gay community: drag queens, homeless youth, [[LGBT people in prison|gay inmates in prison and jail]], and transgender people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shepard|first=Benjamin|date=2012|title=From Community Organization to Direct Services: The Street Trans Action Revolutionaries to Sylvia Rivera Law Project|url=|journal=Journal of Social Service Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nJohnson was Rivera's friend and ally. Their discussions led to activism and in 1970, Rivera and Johnson co-founded [[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]] (STAR). STAR offered services and advocacy for homeless queer youth,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=Samuel|date=2013|title=Trans Power! Sylvia Lee Rivera's STAR and the Black Panther Party|url=|journal=Left History|volume=17|pages=|via=}}</ref> and fought for the [[Sexual Orientation Non-Discrimination Act]] in New York. SONDA prohibits discrimination on the basis of [[sexual orientation]] in employment, housing, public accommodations, education, credit, and the exercise of civil rights.<ref name=\"Cohen\" />\n\nAt the 1973 Christopher Street Liberation Day Rally in New York City, Rivera, representing STAR, gave a brief speech from the main stage in which she called out the heterosexual males who were preying on vulnerable members of the community. Rivera espoused what could be seen as a [[third gender]] perspective, saying that LGBT prisoners seeking help \"do not write women. They do not write men. They write to STAR.\"<ref name=video73>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/45479858 |title=y'all better quiet down! |time=1:40 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525022745/https://vimeo.com/45479858 |archive-date=May 25, 2015 |df= }}</ref> At the same event, Rivera and fellow queen [[Lee Brewster]] jumped onstage during feminist activist [[Jean O'Leary]]'s speech and shouts at the crowd her \u201cY\u2019all Better Quiet Down,\" speech, stating, \"You go to bars because of what drag queens did for you, and ''these bitches'' tell us to quit being ourselves!\"<ref name=Cleninden171/><ref name=\"duberman236\">Duberman, Martin (1993). ''Stonewall'', Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-525-93602-5}}, p. 236.</ref>\n\nIn early July 1992, shortly after the [[New York City LGBT Pride March|New York City Pride March]], Johnson's body was found floating in the Hudson River off the [[Christopher Street Pier|West Village Piers]]. Police promptly ruled Johnson's death a suicide, despite the presence of a head wound.<ref name=PeoplesMemorialWholeVideo>Wicker, Randolfe (1992) {{cite video |title=\"Marsha P Johnson \u2013 People's Memorial\"}}  Accessed July 26, 2015.</ref> Johnson's friends and supporters, Rivera included, insisted Johnson had not been suicidal, and a people's postering campaign later declared that Johnson had earlier been harassed near the spot where her body was found. In May 1995, Rivera tried to commit suicide by walking into the Hudson River.<ref name=\"nytsuicide\">Staff report (May 24, 1995). About New York; Still Here: Sylvia, Who Survived Stonewall, Time and the River. ''[[New York Times]]''</ref> That year she also appeared in the [[Arthur Dong]] documentary episode \"Out Rage '69\", part of the [[PBS]] series ''The Question of Equality'',<ref name=\"outrage69\">Goodman, Walter (November 4, 1995). [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E0DF1739F937A35752C1A963958260&sec=&pagewanted=1 Television Review: The Gay Search for Equality.] ''New York Times''</ref> and gave an extensive interview to gay journalist [[Randy Wicker]] in which she discussed her suicide attempts, Johnson's life and death, and her advocacy for poor and working-class gays made homeless by [[HIV/AIDS in the United States|the AIDS crisis]].<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95/>\n\nIn the last five years of her life, Rivera renewed her political activity, giving many speeches about the Stonewall Uprising<ref name=SuperLesbian>\"It was a rebellion, it was an uprising, it was a civil rights disobedience \u2014 it wasn't no damn riot.\" \u2013 Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie in {{cite web|last=K |first=Kristi |url=http://thekword.com/2014/05/28/something-like-a-super-lesbian-storme-delarverie-in-memoriam/ |title=Something Like A Super Lesbian: Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie (In Memoriam) |publisher=thekword.com |date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> and the necessity for transgender people, including drag queens and [[Butch and femme|butch dykes]], to fight for their legacy at the forefront of the LGBT movement. She traveled to Italy for the [[WorldPride#WorldPride Rome 2000|Millennium March in 2000]], where she was acclaimed as the \"mother of all gay people\".<ref name=LGMNY/> In early 2001, after a service at the [[Metropolitan Community Church of New York]] referring to the [[Star of Bethlehem]] announcing the [[Nativity of Jesus|birth of Jesus]], she decided to resurrect STAR as an active political organization (now changing \"[[Transvestite]]\" to the more recently coined term \"Transgender,\" which at that time was understood to include all [[gender-nonconforming]] people).<ref name=TWF>Feinberg, Leslie (1996) ''Transgender Warriors: Making History''. Boston: Beacon Press. {{ISBN|0-8070-7941-3}}</ref> STAR fought for the [[LGBT rights in New York#Discrimination protections|New York City Transgender Rights Bill]] and for a trans-inclusive [[Sexual Orientation Non-Discrimination Act|New York State Sexual Orientation Non Discrimination Act]]. STAR also sponsored street pressures for justice for [[Amanda Milan]], a transgender woman murdered in 2000.<ref name=LGMNY/> Rivera attacked [[Human Rights Campaign]] and [[Empire State Pride Agenda]] as organizations that were standing in the way of transgender rights. On her deathbed she met with Matt Foreman and Joe Grabarz of ESPA to negotiate transgender inclusion in its political structure and agenda.\n\nRivera was angered by her perception that the significance of drag queens and drag culture was being minimized by the ostensibly assimilationist gay rights agenda, particularly by new would-be \"gay leaders\" who were focusing on military service ([[Don't Ask Don't Tell]]) and [[Gay marriage|marriage equality]].<ref name=LGMNY/><ref name=Hoffman>Hoffman, Amy (2007) ''An Army of Ex-Lovers: My life at the Gay Community News''. University of Massachusetts Press 978-1558496217</ref> Rivera's conflicts with these newer LGBT groups were emblematic of the mainstream LGBT movement's strained relationship to the radical politics of many earlier gay liberation activists. After Rivera's death, [[Michael Bronski]] recalled her anger when she felt that she was being marginalized within the community:\n\n<blockquote>After Gay Liberation Front folded and the more reformist Gay Activists Alliance (GAA) became New York's primary gay rights group, Sylvia Rivera worked hard within their ranks in 1971 to promote a citywide gay rights, anti-discrimination ordinance. But for all of her work, when it came time to make deals, GAA dropped the portions in the civil rights bill that dealt with transvestitism and drag \u2014 it just wasn't possible to pass it with such \"extreme\" elements included. As it turned out, it wasn't possible to pass the bill anyway until 1986. But not only was the language of the bill changed, GAA \u2014 which was becoming increasingly more conservative, several of its founders and officers had plans to run for public office \u2014 even changed its political agenda to exclude issues of transvestitism and drag. It was also not unusual for Sylvia to be urged to \"front\" possibly dangerous demonstrations, but when the press showed up, she would be pushed aside by the more middle-class, \"straight-appearing\" leadership. In 1995, Rivera was still hurt: \"When things started getting more mainstream, it was like, 'We don't need you no more'\". But, she added, \"Hell hath no fury like a drag queen scorned\".<ref name=Bronski>Bronski, Michael (April 2002). [https://zcomm.org/zmagazine/sylvia-rivera-1951-2002-by-michael-bronski/ Sylvia Rivera: 1951\u20132002.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113203206/http://www.zmag.org/ZMag/articles/april02bronski.htm |date=2005-11-13 }} in ''Z Magazine''. \"Hell hath no fury like a drag queen scorned\".</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Bronski, Rivera was banned from [[Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center|New York's Gay & Lesbian Community Center]] for several years in the mid-1990s, because, on a cold winter's night, she aggressively demanded that the Center take care of poor and homeless queer youth. A short time before her death, Bronski reports that she said:\n\n<blockquote>One of our main goals now is to destroy the Human Rights Campaign, because I'm tired of sitting on the back of the bumper. It's not even the back of the bus anymore \u2014 it's the back of the bumper. The bitch on wheels is back.<ref name=Bronski/></blockquote>\n\nRivera's struggles did not relate exclusively to gay and trans people, as they intersected with issues of poverty and discrimination faced by people of color, which caused friction in the GAA as it was mainly made up of white middle-class gays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bese.com/the-crusade-of-transgender-activist-sylvia-rivera/|title=The Crusade of Transgender Activist Sylvia Rivera|date=2018-06-08|website=BESE|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The transgender person-of-color activist and scholar Jessi Gan discusses how mainstream LGBT groups have routinely dismissed or not paid sufficient attention to Rivera's [[Latinas|Latina]] identity, while Puerto Rican and Latino groups have often not fully acknowledged Rivera's contribution to their struggles for civil rights.<ref name=Gan/> Tim Retzloff has discussed this issue with respect to the omission of discussions about race and ethnicity in mainstream [[LGBT history in the United States|U.S. LGBT history]], particularly with regard to Rivera's legacy.<ref name=Retzloff>Retzloff, Tim. [https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/377/37719108.pdf \"Eliding Trans Latino/a Queer Experience in U.S. LGBT History: Jos\u00e9 Sarria and Sylvia Rivera Reexamined\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828001018/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719108.pdf |date=August 28, 2010 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 140\u2013161.</ref>\n\n==Gender identity==\nRivera's [[gender identity]] was complex and varied throughout her life.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /><ref name=\"RiveraWholeInterview95\" /> In 1971, she spoke of herself as a \"half sister\".<ref name=\"HalfSisters\">Rivera, Sylvia, \"Transvestites: Your Half Sisters and Half Brothers of the Revolution\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013. \"Transvestites are homosexual men and women who dress in clothes of the opposite sex.\"</ref> In her essay \"Transvestites: Your Half Sisters and Half Brothers of the Revolution\", she specifically claims her use of ''[[transvestite]]'' as applying to only the gay community: \"Transvestites are homosexual men and women who dress in clothes of the opposite sex.\"<ref name=\"HalfSisters\" />\n\nIn interviews and writings in her later years, notably her 1995 interview with [[Randy Wicker]] and her 2002 essay, \"Queens In Exile, The Forgotten Ones,\" she expressed a [[Genderqueer|fluid take on gender]], referring to herself alternately as a [[gay man]],<ref name=\"RiveraInterview95\" /> a [[gay girl]],<ref name=\"RiveraWholeInterview95\" /> a [[drag queen]]/street queen,<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /><ref name=\"feinberg1\" /><ref name=Rivera95 /> and again as a gay man,<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /> embodying all of these experiences and seeing none of these identities as excluding the others.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" />  Rivera writes of having considered [[gender reassignment surgery]] much earlier in life, but of ultimately choosing to reject it, [[Transgender hormone therapy (male-to-female)|taking hormones]] only near the end of her life.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" />\n\n<blockquote>I left home at age 10 in 1961. I hustled on 42nd Street. The early 60s was not a good time for drag queens, effeminate boys or boys that wore makeup like we did. Back then we were beat up by the police, by everybody. I didn't really come out as a drag queen until the late 60s when drag queens were arrested, what degradation there was. I remember the first time I got arrested, I wasn't even in full drag. I was walking down the street and the cops just snatched me.<ref name=\"StonewallSTAR\">Rivera, Sylvia, \"I'm Glad I Was in The Stonewall Riot\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013.</ref>\n\nPeople now want to call me a lesbian because I'm with Julia,<ref>Julia Murray, Rivera's partner in the last years of her life</ref> and I say, \"No. I'm just me. I'm not a lesbian.\" I'm tired of being labeled. I don't even like the label ''transgender''. I'm tired of living with labels. I just want to be who I am. I am Sylvia Rivera. Ray Rivera left home at the age of 10 to become Sylvia. And that's who I am.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Death==\nRivera died during the dawn hours of February 19, 2002, at [[Saint Vincent's Catholic Medical Center|St. Vincent's Hospital]], of complications from [[Hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/> Activist [[Riki Wilchins]] noted, \"In many ways, Sylvia was the [[Rosa Parks]] of the modern transgender movement, a term that was not even coined until two decades after Stonewall\".<ref name=\"voiceobit\">{{cite web |url-status=dead |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0209,wilchins,32645,1.html |title=A Woman for Her Time: In Memory of Stonewall Warrior Sylvia Rivera |last1=Wilchins |first1=Riki |date=February 27, 2002 |website=Village Voice |publisher= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619094746/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0209,wilchins,32645,1.html |archive-date=June 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:SylviaRiveraWay.jpg|thumb|Street sign in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]], named in Rivera\u2019s honor]]\n\nAs an active member of the [[Metropolitan Community Church of New York]], Rivera ministered through the Church's [[food pantry]], which provides food to hungry people. As well, recalling her life as a child on the streets, she remained a passionate advocate for [[queer]] youth. MCC New York has a food pantry called the Sylvia Rivera Food Pantry, and its queer youth shelter is called Sylvia's Place, both in her honor.<ref name=\"sylviasplaceobit\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20060619122836/http://www.sylviasplace.org/sylvia_obituary.htm Sylvia Rivera's obituary] via MCCNY</ref>\n\nNamed in her honor (and established in 2002), the [[Sylvia Rivera Law Project]] is dedicated \"to guarantee that all people are free to self-determine [[gender identity]] and expression, regardless of income or race, and without facing harassment, discrimination or violence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://srlp.org/|title=SRLP (Sylvia Rivera Law Project)|website=SRLP (Sylvia Rivera Law Project)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, actor/comedian [[Jade Esteban Estrada]] portrays Rivera in the well-received solo musical ''ICONS: The Lesbian and Gay History of the World, Vol. 1'' (directed by Aliza Washabaugh-Durand and produced by Aliza Washabaugh-Durand and Christopher Durand) winning Rivera renewed national attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhopemcc.org/news/ghmcc-news/754-jade-esteban-estrada-icons.html|title=Good Hope Metropolitan Community Church|website=Good Hope MCC|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the corner of Christopher and Hudson streets was renamed \"Sylvia Rivera Way\" in her honour. This intersection is in [[Greenwich Village]], the neighborhood in New York City where Rivera started organizing, and is only two blocks from the Stonewall Inn.<ref name=nyblade>Withers, James (November 25, 2005). [http://www.newyorkblade.com/2005/11-25/news/localnews/rivera.cfm Remembering Sylvia Rivera: Though a divisive figure, trans activist and Stonewall rioter gets honored with street sign.] ''[[New York Blade]]''</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, a new musical based upon Rivera's life, ''Sylvia So Far'', premiered in New York at La Mama in a production starring Bianca Leigh as Rivera and Peter Proctor as Marsha P. Johnson. The composer and lyricist is Timothy Mathis (''Wallflowers, Our Story Too, The Conjuring''), a friend of Rivera's in real life. The show moved off-Broadway in the winter of 2007/2008.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe Spring 2007 issue of ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'', which was dedicated to \"Puerto Rican Queer Sexualities\" and published at [[Hunter College]], included a special dossier on Sylvia Rivera, including a transcription of a talk by Rivera from 2001 as well as two academic essays exploring the intersections of Rivera's trans and Latina identities.<ref name=Gan/><ref name=LGMNY/><ref name=Retzloff/> The articles in this journal issue complement other essays by Puerto Rican scholars who have also emphasized Rivera's pioneering role.<ref>Aponte-Par\u00e9s, Luis. \"Outside/In: Crossing Queer and Latino Boundaries\". In ''Mambo Montage: The Latinization of New York'', eds. Agust\u00edn La\u00f3-Montes and Arlene D\u00e1vila, 363-85. New York: Columbia University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-231-11274-2}}</ref><ref>La Fountain-Stokes, Lawrence. \"1898 and the History of a Queer Puerto Rican Century: Imperialism, Diaspora, and Social Transformation\". ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 11. 1 (Fall 1999): 91\u2013110. First published in ''Chicano/Latino Homoerotic Identities'', ed. David William Foster, 197\u2013215. Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-8153-3228-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, The Social Justice Hub at [[The New School]]\u2019s newly opened University Center was named the Baldwin Rivera Boggs Center after activists [[James Baldwin]], Sylvia Rivera, and [[Grace Lee Boggs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschoolfreepress.com/2015/12/24/students-seek-more-support-from-the-university-in-an-effort-to-maintain-a-socially-just-identity/|title=Students Seek More Support From the University in an Effort to Maintain a Socially Just Identity|last=Moore|first=Talia|date=2015-12-24|website=The New School Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a portrait of Rivera was added to the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ring |first=Trudy |url=http://www.advocate.com/transgender/2015/10/27/sylvia-rivera-gets-place-national-portrait-gallery |title=Sylvia Rivera Gets a Place in the National Portrait Gallery |publisher=Advocate.com |date= |accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Rivera was inducted into the [[Legacy Walk]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Windy City Times |url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Legacy-Walk-unveils-2-new-plaques-under-rainbow-sky-/56836.html |title=1315 \u2013 Legacy Walk unveils 2 new plaques under rainbow sky \u2013 Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive \u2013 Windy City Times |publisher=Windycitymediagroup.com |date= |accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''[[Happy Birthday, Marsha!]]'' a short film about Rivera and [[Marsha P. Johnson]], set in the hours before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]] in New York City, was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A560503573/ITOF?u=uni_rodit&sid=ITOF&xid=4f07abe2|title=Artist, professor explore transgender history through art|last=Luo|first=Steven|date=2018-10-30|work=UWIRE Text|access-date=2019-04-19|page=1|language=English}}</ref>\n\nA large, painted mural depicting Rivera and [[Marsha P. Johnson]] went on display in Dallas, Texas in 2019 to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Stonewall riots. The painting of the \"two pioneers of the gay rights movement\" in front of a transgender flag claims to be the world's largest mural honoring the trans community.<ref>{{cite web|author=Vic Parsons |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/12/12/marsha-p-johnson-sylvia-rivera-largest-trans-vandalised-moustaches-stonewall/amp/ |title=Mural of Marsha P Johnson and Sylvia Rivera vandalised with moustaches |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, it was announced that LGBT rights activists Marsha P. Johnson and Sylvia Rivera would be commemorated with a monument in New York's Greenwich Village, near the epicenter of the historic Stonewall riots. The monument was publicly announced on May 30, in honor of the 50th anniversary of Stonewall and just in time for Pride month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jacobs |first=Julia |title=Two Transgender Activists Are Getting a Monument in New York |date=May 29, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/29/arts/transgender-monument-stonewall.html |website=NY Times |accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the Italian city of [[Livorno]] dedicated a green area to Rivera, called Parco Sylvia Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livornotoday.it/cronaca/sylvia-rivera-area-verde-venezia.html|title=Venezia, intitolata un'area verde a Sylvia Rivera|website=LivornoToday|language=it|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Rivera was one of the inaugural fifty American \u201cpioneers, trailblazers, and heroes\u201d inducted on the [[National LGBTQ Wall of Honor]] within the [[Stonewall National Monument]] (SNM) in [[New York City]]\u2019s [[Stonewall Inn]].<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/new-york/stonewall-inn-lgbtq-wall-honor|title=National LGBTQ Wall of Honor unveiled at Stonewall Inn|last=Glasses-Baker|first=Becca|date=June 27, 2019|website=www.metro.us|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref><ref name=\"SDGLN\">{{cite web|url=https://sdgln.com/news/2019/06/19/national-lgbtq-wall-honor-be-unveiled-historic-stonewall-inn|title=National LGBTQ Wall of Honor to be unveiled at historic Stonewall Inn|last=SDGLN|first=Timothy Rawles-Community Editor for|date=2019-06-19|website=San Diego Gay and Lesbian News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref> The SNM is the first [[National monument (United States)|U.S. national monument]] dedicated to [[LGBT rights in the United States|LGBTQ rights]] and [[History of LGBT people|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/news//272833|title=Groups seek names for Stonewall 50 honor wall|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> and the wall\u2019s unveiling was timed to take place during the [[Stonewall 50 \u2013 WorldPride NYC 2019|50th anniversary]] of the [[Stonewall riots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sfbaytimes.com/stonewall-50/|title=Stonewall 50|date=2019-04-03|website=San Francisco Bay Times|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nSeason 1, episode 1 of the [[Making Gay History]] podcast is titled (and about) Sylvia Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://makinggayhistory.com/season-one/ |title=Season One |publisher=Making Gay History |date= |accessdate=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n* [[Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Vimeo|35975275|Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier}} September 21, 1995. \n*{{Vimeo|45479858|\"Gay Power!\"}} \u2013 Sylvia Rivera speaks at Gay Liberation Rally, New York City, 1973\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150717192808/http://mccny.org/resources/mccny-charities/ MCCNY Charities] \u2013 the Sylvia Rivera Food Pantry and Homeless Youth Services\n* [http://www.stonewallvets.org/ Stonewall Veterans Association]\n* [http://www.srlp.org/ Sylvia Rivera Law Project]\n* [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keywords=Sylvia+Rivera# Photographs of Sylvia Rivera by Diana Davies] at the [[New York Public Library]] Digital Collections. In the [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/collections/diana-davies-photographs#/?tab=navigation&roots=24:6b1a8580-c5b1-012f-bf18-58d385a7bc34 Gay Liberation Front series] [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/91436004-b7ea-9d9a-e040-e00a180668be Rivera wears an \"E\" t-shirt] in a line of activists to spell out \"Gay Power\"\n\n{{VH1 Trailblazer Honors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rivera, Sylvia}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Venezuelan descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American drag queens]]\n[[Category:Gay Liberation Front members]]\n[[Category:LGBT Protestants]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in New York City]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Transfeminists]]\n[[Category:Transgender rights activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Activists for Hispanic and Latino American civil rights]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|Bolivian feminist and theorist|Silvia Rivera Cusicanqui}}\n{{Short description|20th-century American gay liberation and transgender rights activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n<!--Per Wikipedia:Manual of style, use she/her to refer to Sylvia Rivera throughout her life.-->\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Sylvia Rivera\n|image = Sylvia Rae Rivera.jpg\n|caption = Rivera, in the \"gay camp\" at the Christopher Street Piers {{circa}} 2000\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1951|07|02}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2002|02|19|1951|07|02}}\n|death_place = New York City, United States\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality = American\n|occupation = [[Activism|Activist]]\n|known_for = [[Gay liberation]],<ref name=\"nytobit\">Dunlap, David W. (February 20, 2002). Sylvia Rivera, 50, Figure in Birth of the Gay Liberation Movement. ''New York Times''</ref> [[transgender]] activist, advocate for the homeless.<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/35975275 |title= Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier |time=Repeatedly throughout interview}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref>\n}}\n'''Sylvia Rivera''' (July 2, 1951 \u2013 February 19, 2002) was a [[Latinas|Latina]] American [[gay liberation]] and [[transgender activism|transgender rights activist]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/20/nyregion/sylvia-rivera-50-figure-in-birth-of-the-gay-liberation-movement.html|title=Sylvia Rivera, 50, Figure in Birth of the Gay Liberation Movement|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=February 20, 2002|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 1, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=RiveraInterview95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/35975275  |title= Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier |time=14:17}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 Transgender People Who Influenced American Culture|url=http://time.com/130734/transgender-celebrities-actors-athletes-in-america/|publisher=Time Magazine}}</ref> prominent as an activist and community worker in [[LGBT history in New York|New York]]. Rivera, who identified as a [[drag queen]],<ref name=QueensInExile>Rivera, Sylvia, \"Queens In Exile, The Forgotten Ones\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"feinberg1\">Leslie Feinberg (September 24, 2006). [http://www.workers.org/2006/us/lavender-red-73/ Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries.] ''[[Workers World Party]]''. \"Stonewall combatants Sylvia Rivera and Marsha \"Pay It No Mind\" Johnson... Both were self-identified drag queens.\"</ref><ref name=Rivera95>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/37548074 |title= Sylvia Rivera Reflects on the Spirit of Marsha P Johnson |time=1:27}} September 21, 1995. Accessed July 24, 2015.</ref> participated in demonstrations with the [[Gay Liberation Front]].<ref name=GLFphotos>Photographs by [[Diana Davies (photographer)|Diana Davies]], in the Gay Liberation Front series: [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/91436004-b7ea-9d9a-e040-e00a180668be Rivera wears an \"E\" t-shirt] in a line of activists to spell out \"Gay Power\".</ref>\n\nWith close friend [[Marsha P. Johnson]], Rivera co-founded the [[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]] (STAR), a group dedicated to helping homeless young drag queens, gay youth, and [[trans woman|trans women]].<ref name=\"NPR\">[[Marsha P. Johnson]] died in 1992. In 2001, Rivera \"resurrected\" the group, renaming it \"Street Transgender Action Revolutionaries.\" SoundPortraits (July 4, 2001). [http://soundportraits.org/on-air/remembering_stonewall/update.php Update on Remembering Stonewall.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702203403/http://soundportraits.org/on-air/remembering_stonewall/update.php |date=July 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRivera was born and raised in New York City and lived most of her life in or near the city; she was of [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] and [[Venezuelan American|Venezuelan]] descent.<ref name=QueensInExile/> She was abandoned by her birth father Jos\u00e9 Rivera early in life and became an orphan after her mother died by suicide when Rivera was three years old.<ref name=Gan>Gan, Jessi. [http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf \"'Still at the Back of the Bus': Sylvia Rivera's Struggle\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175345/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719107.pdf |date=April 6, 2012 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 124\u2013139.</ref> Rivera was then raised by her Venezuelan grandmother, who disapproved of Rivera's effeminate behavior, particularly after Rivera began to wear makeup in fourth grade.<ref name=Gan/> As a result, Rivera began living on the streets at the age of 11 and was forced to work as a [[Child prostitution|child prostitute]]. She was taken in by the local community of [[drag queen]]s, who gave her the name Sylvia.<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{cite book|author=Cohen, Stephan|date=2007|title=The Gay Liberation Youth Movement in New York: 'An Army of Lovers Cannot Fail'|location=London|publisher=[[Routledge]]|pages=|isbn=0-8070-7941-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/transgenderwarri00fein}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nRivera's activism began in 1970 after she joined the [[Gay Activists Alliance]] at 18 years old, where she fought for not only the rights of gay people but also for the inclusion of drag queens like herself in the movement.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gaycitynews.nyc/stories/2019/15/david-carter-stonewall-2019-06-27-gcn.html |title=Exploding the Myths of Stonewall |author=Carter, David |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref>  Rivera sometimes exaggerated her importance, purporting to have been active during the [[civil rights movement]] and through the [[opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|movement against the Vietnam war]] and [[Second-wave feminism#Overview in the United States|second-wave feminist movement]]s, but she could not prove her claims.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> After her older friend, [[Marsha P. Johnson]], was being praised for being involved in the [[Stonewall Riots]], Rivera  claimed that she was also present there.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/><ref name=LGMNY>Rivera, Sylvia. [http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719106.pdf \"Sylvia Rivera's Talk at LGMNY, June 2001, Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center, New York City\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406175409/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719106.pdf |date=April 6, 2012 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 116\u2013123.</ref> Stonewall historian David Carter, however, questioned Rivera's claims to have ever been at the riots that night, based on contradictory statements she made as well as testimony relayed to him by early gay rights activists, including [[Marsha P. Johnson]], who denied Rivera was present at the riots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaytoday.com/interview/070104in.asp|title=David Carter: Historian of The Stonewall Riots|publisher=Gay Today|author=Paul D. Cain}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Rivera famously spoke at a gay rights rally after she and Johnson were reportedly banned for making other gay activists \"look bad\". Afterwards, she told anyone who would listen that she was involved in the Stonewall riots, to which Johnson replied, \"Sylvia, you know you weren't there\", after which Rivera was silent.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> When the Stonewall riots occurred, Rivera was only 17 years old and according to [[Bob Kohler]], who was there on the two nights of the riots, \"always hung out uptown at Bryant Park\" and never came downtown.<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Johnson told gay rights historian Eric Marcus in 1987 that in the hours prior to her arriving downtown to join the other protesters at the riots, she had a party uptown and mentioned that \"Rivera and them were over in the [Bryant] park having a cocktail.\"<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Kohler told Carter that, although Rivera had not been at the uprising, he hoped Carter would nonetheless portray her as having been there. Another Stonewall veteran, Thomas Lanigan-Schmidt, claimed that he wanted to add her \"so that young Puerto Rican transgender people on the street would have a role model.\"<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Kohler and Rivera had a discussion over what to include in the book and denied Rivera's requests to be portrayed as being the one to throw the first molotov cocktail, throwing the first brick, and having thrown the first bottle, only allowing Rivera to be portrayed as someone who had \"thrown a bottle\" as opposed to being \"the first\".<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> [[Randy Wicker]], who was part of the more assimilationist [[Mattachine Society]] and was an early critic of the violent, militant tactics used by Johnson and other Stonewall veterans, said Johnson had told him that Sylvia was not at Stonewall \"as she was asleep after taking heroin uptown\".<ref name=\"StonewallMyths\"/> Rivera would also claim to have been involved in Puerto Rican and African American youth activism, particularly with the [[Young Lords]] and [[Black Panthers]].<ref name=Gan/>\n\nAt different times in her life, Rivera battled [[substance abuse]] and lived on the streets, largely in the gay homeless community at the [[Christopher Street]] docks.<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95/> Her experiences made her more focused on advocacy for those who, in her view, mainstream society and the [[cultural assimilation|assimilationist]] sectors of the lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender ([[LGBT]]) communities were leaving behind.<ref name=Cleninden171>Clendinen, Dudley, and Nagourney, Adam (1999). ''Out for Good'', Simon & Schuster. {{ISBN|0-684-81091-3}}, pp. 171\u2013172.</ref> For these reasons Rivera projected her voice to give her community power. She fought for herself but most importantly for the rights of people of color and low-income LGBT people. As someone who suffered from systematic poverty and racism, Rivera used her voice for unity, sharing her stories, pain, and struggles to show her community they are not alone. She amplified the voices of the most vulnerable members of the gay community: drag queens, homeless youth, [[LGBT people in prison|gay inmates in prison and jail]], and transgender people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shepard|first=Benjamin|date=2012|title=From Community Organization to Direct Services: The Street Trans Action Revolutionaries to Sylvia Rivera Law Project|url=|journal=Journal of Social Service Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nJohnson was Rivera's friend and ally. Their discussions led to activism and in 1970, Rivera and Johnson co-founded [[Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries]] (STAR). STAR offered services and advocacy for homeless queer youth,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=Samuel|date=2013|title=Trans Power! Sylvia Lee Rivera's STAR and the Black Panther Party|url=|journal=Left History|volume=17|pages=|via=}}</ref> and fought for the [[Sexual Orientation Non-Discrimination Act]] in New York. SONDA prohibits discrimination on the basis of [[sexual orientation]] in employment, housing, public accommodations, education, credit, and the exercise of civil rights.<ref name=\"Cohen\" />\n\nAt the 1973 Christopher Street Liberation Day Rally in New York City, Rivera, representing STAR, gave a brief speech from the main stage in which she called out the heterosexual males who were preying on vulnerable members of the community. Rivera espoused what could be seen as a [[third gender]] perspective, saying that LGBT prisoners seeking help \"do not write women. They do not write men. They write to STAR.\"<ref name=video73>{{cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/45479858 |title=y'all better quiet down! |time=1:40 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525022745/https://vimeo.com/45479858 |archive-date=May 25, 2015 |df= }}</ref> At the same event, Rivera and fellow queen [[Lee Brewster]] jumped onstage during feminist activist [[Jean O'Leary]]'s speech and shouts at the crowd her \u201cY\u2019all Better Quiet Down,\" speech, stating, \"You go to bars because of what drag queens did for you, and ''these bitches'' tell us to quit being ourselves!\"<ref name=Cleninden171/><ref name=\"duberman236\">Duberman, Martin (1993). ''Stonewall'', Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-525-93602-5}}, p. 236.</ref>\n\nIn early July 1992, shortly after the [[New York City LGBT Pride March|New York City Pride March]], Johnson's body was found floating in the Hudson River off the [[Christopher Street Pier|West Village Piers]]. Police promptly ruled Johnson's death a suicide, despite the presence of a head wound.<ref name=PeoplesMemorialWholeVideo>Wicker, Randolfe (1992) {{cite video |title=\"Marsha P Johnson \u2013 People's Memorial\"}}  Accessed July 26, 2015.</ref> Johnson's friends and supporters, Rivera included, insisted Johnson had not been suicidal, and a people's postering campaign later declared that Johnson had earlier been harassed near the spot where her body was found. In May 1995, Rivera tried to commit suicide by walking into the Hudson River.<ref name=\"nytsuicide\">Staff report (May 24, 1995). About New York; Still Here: Sylvia, Who Survived Stonewall, Time and the River. ''[[New York Times]]''</ref> That year she also appeared in the [[Arthur Dong]] documentary episode \"Out Rage '69\", part of the [[PBS]] series ''The Question of Equality'',<ref name=\"outrage69\">Goodman, Walter (November 4, 1995). [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E0DF1739F937A35752C1A963958260&sec=&pagewanted=1 Television Review: The Gay Search for Equality.] ''New York Times''</ref> and gave an extensive interview to gay journalist [[Randy Wicker]] in which she discussed her suicide attempts, Johnson's life and death, and her advocacy for poor and working-class gays made homeless by [[HIV/AIDS in the United States|the AIDS crisis]].<ref name=RiveraWholeInterview95/>\n\nIn the last five years of her life, Rivera renewed her political activity, giving many speeches about the Stonewall Uprising<ref name=SuperLesbian>\"It was a rebellion, it was an uprising, it was a civil rights disobedience \u2014 it wasn't no damn riot.\" \u2013 Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie in {{cite web|last=K |first=Kristi |url=http://thekword.com/2014/05/28/something-like-a-super-lesbian-storme-delarverie-in-memoriam/ |title=Something Like A Super Lesbian: Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie (In Memoriam) |publisher=thekword.com |date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> and the necessity for transgender people, including drag queens and [[Butch and femme|butch dykes]], to fight for their legacy at the forefront of the LGBT movement. She traveled to Italy for the [[WorldPride#WorldPride Rome 2000|Millennium March in 2000]], where she was acclaimed as the \"mother of all gay people\".<ref name=LGMNY/> In early 2001, after a service at the [[Metropolitan Community Church of New York]] referring to the [[Star of Bethlehem]] announcing the [[Nativity of Jesus|birth of Jesus]], she decided to resurrect STAR as an active political organization (now changing \"[[Transvestite]]\" to the more recently coined term \"Transgender,\" which at that time was understood to include all [[gender-nonconforming]] people).<ref name=TWF>Feinberg, Leslie (1996) ''Transgender Warriors: Making History''. Boston: Beacon Press. {{ISBN|0-8070-7941-3}}</ref> STAR fought for the [[LGBT rights in New York#Discrimination protections|New York City Transgender Rights Bill]] and for a trans-inclusive [[Sexual Orientation Non-Discrimination Act|New York State Sexual Orientation Non Discrimination Act]]. STAR also sponsored street pressures for justice for [[Amanda Milan]], a transgender woman murdered in 2000.<ref name=LGMNY/> Rivera attacked [[Human Rights Campaign]] and [[Empire State Pride Agenda]] as organizations that were standing in the way of transgender rights. On her deathbed she met with Matt Foreman and Joe Grabarz of ESPA to negotiate transgender inclusion in its political structure and agenda.\n\nRivera was angered by her perception that the significance of drag queens and drag culture was being minimized by the ostensibly assimilationist gay rights agenda, particularly by new would-be \"gay leaders\" who were focusing on military service ([[Don't Ask Don't Tell]]) and [[Gay marriage|marriage equality]].<ref name=LGMNY/><ref name=Hoffman>Hoffman, Amy (2007) ''An Army of Ex-Lovers: My life at the Gay Community News''. University of Massachusetts Press 978-1558496217</ref> Rivera's conflicts with these newer LGBT groups were emblematic of the mainstream LGBT movement's strained relationship to the radical politics of many earlier gay liberation activists. After Rivera's death, [[Michael Bronski]] recalled her anger when she felt that she was being marginalized within the community:\n\n<blockquote>After Gay Liberation Front folded and the more reformist Gay Activists Alliance (GAA) became New York's primary gay rights group, Sylvia Rivera worked hard within their ranks in 1971 to promote a citywide gay rights, anti-discrimination ordinance. But for all of her work, when it came time to make deals, GAA dropped the portions in the civil rights bill that dealt with transvestitism and drag \u2014 it just wasn't possible to pass it with such \"extreme\" elements included. As it turned out, it wasn't possible to pass the bill anyway until 1986. But not only was the language of the bill changed, GAA \u2014 which was becoming increasingly more conservative, several of its founders and officers had plans to run for public office \u2014 even changed its political agenda to exclude issues of transvestitism and drag. It was also not unusual for Sylvia to be urged to \"front\" possibly dangerous demonstrations, but when the press showed up, she would be pushed aside by the more middle-class, \"straight-appearing\" leadership. In 1995, Rivera was still hurt: \"When things started getting more mainstream, it was like, 'We don't need you no more'\". But, she added, \"Hell hath no fury like a drag queen scorned\".<ref name=Bronski>Bronski, Michael (April 2002). [https://zcomm.org/zmagazine/sylvia-rivera-1951-2002-by-michael-bronski/ Sylvia Rivera: 1951\u20132002.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113203206/http://www.zmag.org/ZMag/articles/april02bronski.htm |date=2005-11-13 }} in ''Z Magazine''. \"Hell hath no fury like a drag queen scorned\".</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Bronski, Rivera was banned from [[Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center|New York's Gay & Lesbian Community Center]] for several years in the mid-1990s, because, on a cold winter's night, she aggressively demanded that the Center take care of poor and homeless queer youth. A short time before her death, Bronski reports that she said:\n\n<blockquote>One of our main goals now is to destroy the Human Rights Campaign, because I'm tired of sitting on the back of the bumper. It's not even the back of the bus anymore \u2014 it's the back of the bumper. The bitch on wheels is back.<ref name=Bronski/></blockquote>\n\nRivera's struggles did not relate exclusively to gay and trans people, as they intersected with issues of poverty and discrimination faced by people of color, which caused friction in the GAA as it was mainly made up of white middle-class gays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bese.com/the-crusade-of-transgender-activist-sylvia-rivera/|title=The Crusade of Transgender Activist Sylvia Rivera|date=2018-06-08|website=BESE|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The transgender person-of-color activist and scholar Jessi Gan discusses how mainstream LGBT groups have routinely dismissed or not paid sufficient attention to Rivera's [[Latinas|Latina]] identity, while Puerto Rican and Latino groups have often not fully acknowledged Rivera's contribution to their struggles for civil rights.<ref name=Gan/> Tim Retzloff has discussed this issue with respect to the omission of discussions about race and ethnicity in mainstream [[LGBT history in the United States|U.S. LGBT history]], particularly with regard to Rivera's legacy.<ref name=Retzloff>Retzloff, Tim. [http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719108.pdf \"Eliding Trans Latino/a Queer Experience in U.S. LGBT History: Jos\u00e9 Sarria and Sylvia Rivera Reexamined\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828001018/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/377/37719108.pdf |date=August 28, 2010 }} ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 19.1 (Spring 2007): 140\u2013161.</ref>\n\n==Gender identity==\nRivera's [[gender identity]] was complex and varied throughout her life.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /><ref name=\"RiveraWholeInterview95\" /> In 1971, she spoke of herself as a \"half sister\".<ref name=\"HalfSisters\">Rivera, Sylvia, \"Transvestites: Your Half Sisters and Half Brothers of the Revolution\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013. \"Transvestites are homosexual men and women who dress in clothes of the opposite sex.\"</ref> In her essay \"Transvestites: Your Half Sisters and Half Brothers of the Revolution\", she specifically claims her use of ''[[transvestite]]'' as applying to only the gay community: \"Transvestites are homosexual men and women who dress in clothes of the opposite sex.\"<ref name=\"HalfSisters\" />\n\nIn interviews and writings in her later years, notably her 1995 interview with [[Randy Wicker]] and her 2002 essay, \"Queens In Exile, The Forgotten Ones,\" she expressed a [[Genderqueer|fluid take on gender]], referring to herself alternately as a [[gay man]],<ref name=\"RiveraInterview95\" /> a [[gay girl]],<ref name=\"RiveraWholeInterview95\" /> a [[drag queen]]/street queen,<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /><ref name=\"feinberg1\" /><ref name=Rivera95 /> and again as a gay man,<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /> embodying all of these experiences and seeing none of these identities as excluding the others.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" />  Rivera writes of having considered [[gender reassignment surgery]] much earlier in life, but of ultimately choosing to reject it, [[Transgender hormone therapy (male-to-female)|taking hormones]] only near the end of her life.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" />\n\n<blockquote>I left home at age 10 in 1961. I hustled on 42nd Street. The early 60s was not a good time for drag queens, effeminate boys or boys that wore makeup like we did. Back then we were beat up by the police, by everybody. I didn't really come out as a drag queen until the late 60s when drag queens were arrested, what degradation there was. I remember the first time I got arrested, I wasn't even in full drag. I was walking down the street and the cops just snatched me.<ref name=\"StonewallSTAR\">Rivera, Sylvia, \"I'm Glad I Was in The Stonewall Riot\" in ''Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries: Survival, Revolt, and Queer Antagonist Struggle''. Untorelli Press, 2013.</ref>\n\nPeople now want to call me a lesbian because I'm with Julia,<ref>Julia Murray, Rivera's partner in the last years of her life</ref> and I say, \"No. I'm just me. I'm not a lesbian.\" I'm tired of being labeled. I don't even like the label ''transgender''. I'm tired of living with labels. I just want to be who I am. I am Sylvia Rivera. Ray Rivera left home at the age of 10 to become Sylvia. And that's who I am.<ref name=\"QueensInExile\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Death==\nRivera died during the dawn hours of February 19, 2002, at [[Saint Vincent's Catholic Medical Center|St. Vincent's Hospital]], of complications from [[Hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/> Activist [[Riki Wilchins]] noted, \"In many ways, Sylvia was the [[Rosa Parks]] of the modern transgender movement, a term that was not even coined until two decades after Stonewall\".<ref name=\"voiceobit\">{{cite web |url-status=dead |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0209,wilchins,32645,1.html |title=A Woman for Her Time: In Memory of Stonewall Warrior Sylvia Rivera |last1=Wilchins |first1=Riki |date=February 27, 2002 |website=Village Voice |publisher= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619094746/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0209,wilchins,32645,1.html |archive-date=June 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:SylviaRiveraWay.jpg|thumb|Street sign in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]], named in Rivera\u2019s honor]]\n\nAs an active member of the [[Metropolitan Community Church of New York]], Rivera ministered through the Church's [[food pantry]], which provides food to hungry people. As well, recalling her life as a child on the streets, she remained a passionate advocate for [[queer]] youth. MCC New York has a food pantry called the Sylvia Rivera Food Pantry, and its queer youth shelter is called Sylvia's Place, both in her honor.<ref name=\"sylviasplaceobit\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20060619122836/http://www.sylviasplace.org/sylvia_obituary.htm Sylvia Rivera's obituary] via MCCNY</ref> \n\nNamed in her honor (and established in 2002), the [[Sylvia Rivera Law Project]] is dedicated \"to guarantee that all people are free to self-determine [[gender identity]] and expression, regardless of income or race, and without facing harassment, discrimination or violence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://srlp.org/|title=SRLP (Sylvia Rivera Law Project)|website=SRLP (Sylvia Rivera Law Project)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, actor/comedian [[Jade Esteban Estrada]] portrays Rivera in the well-received solo musical ''ICONS: The Lesbian and Gay History of the World, Vol. 1'' (directed by Aliza Washabaugh-Durand and produced by Aliza Washabaugh-Durand and Christopher Durand) winning Rivera renewed national attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhopemcc.org/news/ghmcc-news/754-jade-esteban-estrada-icons.html|title=Good Hope Metropolitan Community Church|website=Good Hope MCC|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the corner of Christopher and Hudson streets was renamed \"Sylvia Rivera Way\" in her honour. This intersection is in [[Greenwich Village]], the neighborhood in New York City where Rivera started organizing, and is only two blocks from the Stonewall Inn.<ref name=nyblade>Withers, James (November 25, 2005). [http://www.newyorkblade.com/2005/11-25/news/localnews/rivera.cfm Remembering Sylvia Rivera: Though a divisive figure, trans activist and Stonewall rioter gets honored with street sign.] ''[[New York Blade]]''</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, a new musical based upon Rivera's life, ''Sylvia So Far'', premiered in New York at La Mama in a production starring Bianca Leigh as Rivera and Peter Proctor as Marsha P. Johnson. The composer and lyricist is Timothy Mathis (''Wallflowers, Our Story Too, The Conjuring''), a friend of Rivera's in real life. The show moved off-Broadway in the winter of 2007/2008.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe Spring 2007 issue of ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'', which was dedicated to \"Puerto Rican Queer Sexualities\" and published at [[Hunter College]], included a special dossier on Sylvia Rivera, including a transcription of a talk by Rivera from 2001 as well as two academic essays exploring the intersections of Rivera's trans and Latina identities.<ref name=Gan/><ref name=LGMNY/><ref name=Retzloff/> The articles in this journal issue complement other essays by Puerto Rican scholars who have also emphasized Rivera's pioneering role.<ref>Aponte-Par\u00e9s, Luis. \"Outside/In: Crossing Queer and Latino Boundaries\". In ''Mambo Montage: The Latinization of New York'', eds. Agust\u00edn La\u00f3-Montes and Arlene D\u00e1vila, 363-85. New York: Columbia University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-231-11274-2}}</ref><ref>La Fountain-Stokes, Lawrence. \"1898 and the History of a Queer Puerto Rican Century: Imperialism, Diaspora, and Social Transformation\". ''CENTRO: Journal of the Center for Puerto Rican Studies'' 11. 1 (Fall 1999): 91\u2013110. First published in ''Chicano/Latino Homoerotic Identities'', ed. David William Foster, 197\u2013215. Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-8153-3228-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, The Social Justice Hub at [[The New School]]\u2019s newly opened University Center was named the Baldwin Rivera Boggs Center after activists [[James Baldwin]], Sylvia Rivera, and [[Grace Lee Boggs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschoolfreepress.com/2015/12/24/students-seek-more-support-from-the-university-in-an-effort-to-maintain-a-socially-just-identity/|title=Students Seek More Support From the University in an Effort to Maintain a Socially Just Identity|last=Moore|first=Talia|date=2015-12-24|website=The New School Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a portrait of Rivera was added to the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ring |first=Trudy |url=http://www.advocate.com/transgender/2015/10/27/sylvia-rivera-gets-place-national-portrait-gallery |title=Sylvia Rivera Gets a Place in the National Portrait Gallery |publisher=Advocate.com |date= |accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Rivera was inducted into the [[Legacy Walk]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Windy City Times |url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Legacy-Walk-unveils-2-new-plaques-under-rainbow-sky-/56836.html |title=1315 \u2013 Legacy Walk unveils 2 new plaques under rainbow sky \u2013 Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive \u2013 Windy City Times |publisher=Windycitymediagroup.com |date= |accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''[[Happy Birthday, Marsha!]]'' a short film about Rivera and [[Marsha P. Johnson]], set in the hours before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]] in New York City, was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A560503573/ITOF?u=uni_rodit&sid=ITOF&xid=4f07abe2|title=Artist, professor explore transgender history through art|last=Luo|first=Steven|date=2018-10-30|work=UWIRE Text|access-date=2019-04-19|page=1|language=English}}</ref>\n\nA large, painted mural depicting Rivera and [[Marsha P. Johnson]] went on display in Dallas, Texas in 2019 to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Stonewall riots. The painting of the \"two pioneers of the gay rights movement\" in front of a transgender flag claims to be the world's largest mural honoring the trans community.<ref>{{cite web|author=Vic Parsons |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/12/12/marsha-p-johnson-sylvia-rivera-largest-trans-vandalised-moustaches-stonewall/amp/ |title=Mural of Marsha P Johnson and Sylvia Rivera vandalised with moustaches |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, it was announced that LGBT rights activists Marsha P. Johnson and Sylvia Rivera would be commemorated with a monument in New York's Greenwich Village, near the epicenter of the historic Stonewall riots. The monument was publicly announced on May 30, in honor of the 50th anniversary of Stonewall and just in time for Pride month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jacobs |first=Julia |title=Two Transgender Activists Are Getting a Monument in New York |date=May 29, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/29/arts/transgender-monument-stonewall.html |website=NY Times |accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the Italian city of [[Livorno]] dedicated a green area to Rivera, called Parco Sylvia Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livornotoday.it/cronaca/sylvia-rivera-area-verde-venezia.html|title=Venezia, intitolata un'area verde a Sylvia Rivera|website=LivornoToday|language=it|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Rivera was one of the inaugural fifty American \u201cpioneers, trailblazers, and heroes\u201d inducted on the [[National LGBTQ Wall of Honor]] within the [[Stonewall National Monument]] (SNM) in [[New York City]]\u2019s [[Stonewall Inn]].<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/new-york/stonewall-inn-lgbtq-wall-honor|title=National LGBTQ Wall of Honor unveiled at Stonewall Inn|last=Glasses-Baker|first=Becca|date=June 27, 2019|website=www.metro.us|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref><ref name=\"SDGLN\">{{cite web|url=https://sdgln.com/news/2019/06/19/national-lgbtq-wall-honor-be-unveiled-historic-stonewall-inn|title=National LGBTQ Wall of Honor to be unveiled at historic Stonewall Inn|last=SDGLN|first=Timothy Rawles-Community Editor for|date=2019-06-19|website=San Diego Gay and Lesbian News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref> The SNM is the first [[National monument (United States)|U.S. national monument]] dedicated to [[LGBT rights in the United States|LGBTQ rights]] and [[History of LGBT people|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/news//272833|title=Groups seek names for Stonewall 50 honor wall|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> and the wall\u2019s unveiling was timed to take place during the [[Stonewall 50 \u2013 WorldPride NYC 2019|50th anniversary]] of the [[Stonewall riots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sfbaytimes.com/stonewall-50/|title=Stonewall 50|date=2019-04-03|website=San Francisco Bay Times|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nSeason 1, episode 1 of the [[Making Gay History]] podcast is titled (and about) Sylvia Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://makinggayhistory.com/season-one/ |title=Season One |publisher=Making Gay History |date= |accessdate=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n* [[Storm\u00e9 DeLarverie]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Vimeo|35975275|Randy Wicker Interviews Sylvia Rivera on the Pier}} September 21, 1995. \n*{{Vimeo|45479858|\"Gay Power!\"}} \u2013 Sylvia Rivera speaks at Gay Liberation Rally, New York City, 1973\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150717192808/http://mccny.org/resources/mccny-charities/ MCCNY Charities] \u2013 the Sylvia Rivera Food Pantry and Homeless Youth Services\n* [http://www.stonewallvets.org/ Stonewall Veterans Association]\n* [http://www.srlp.org/ Sylvia Rivera Law Project]\n* [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keywords=Sylvia+Rivera# Photographs of Sylvia Rivera by Diana Davies] at the [[New York Public Library]] Digital Collections. In the [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/collections/diana-davies-photographs#/?tab=navigation&roots=24:6b1a8580-c5b1-012f-bf18-58d385a7bc34 Gay Liberation Front series] [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/91436004-b7ea-9d9a-e040-e00a180668be Rivera wears an \"E\" t-shirt] in a line of activists to spell out \"Gay Power\"\n\n{{VH1 Trailblazer Honors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rivera, Sylvia}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Venezuelan descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American drag queens]]\n[[Category:Gay Liberation Front members]]\n[[Category:LGBT Protestants]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in New York City]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Transfeminists]]\n[[Category:Transgender rights activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Activists for Hispanic and Latino American civil rights]]\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "bad link repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylvia_Rivera"}
{"title_page": "List of National Football League annual rushing touchdowns leaders", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Tomlinson warming up.jpg|thumb|200px|LaDainian Tomlinson led the league in 2006, and set the NFL record for most rushing touchdowns in a season, with 28.]]\nThis is a season-by-season list of [[National Football League]] players who have led the [[season (sports)|regular season]] in [[rush (gridiron football)|rushing]] [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=list>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rush_td_year_by_year.htm|title=NFL Year-by-Year Rushing Touchdowns Leaders|publisher=Sports-Reference|work=Pro-Football-Reference|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Although ''rushing'' has both an [[American football#offensive unit|offensive]] and a [[American football#defensive unit|defensive]] meaning, this list charts offensive rushing touchdowns, usually scored by a [[running back]], either a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] or a [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]].\n\nRecord-keeping for rushing touchdowns began in [[1932 NFL season|1932]], when [[Bronko Nagurski]] of the [[Chicago Bears]] led the league with 4 rushing touchdowns. Since then, [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] has set the record for rushing touchdowns in a season, when he led the league in [[2006 NFL season|2006]], with 28 rushing touchdowns, while playing with the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/ladainian-tomlinson-breaks-single-season-touchdown-record|title=LaDainian Tomlinson breaks single-season touchdown record|publisher=History|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Prior to Tomlinson's setting of the record, [[Priest Holmes]] of the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] and [[Shaun Alexander]] of the [[Seattle Seahawks]], jointly held the record with 27, reaching that mark in [[2003 NFL season]] and [[2005 NFL season|2005]], respectively.\n\n[[Jim Brown]] holds the record for most league-leading seasons in rushing touchdowns, with 5 ([[1957 NFL season|1957]], [[1958 NFL season|1958]], [[1959 NFL season|1959]], [[1963 NFL season|1963]], and [[1965 NFL season|1965]]).<ref>{{cite web|last=Peticca|first=Mike|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2013/07/cleveland_browns_100_best_all-_60.html|title=Cleveland Browns' 100 best all-time players: No. 2, Jim Brown (video)|publisher=Cleveland|work=The Plain Dealer|date=July 29, 2013|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> [[Dutch Clark]] became the first player to lead the league in consecutive seasons ([[1936 NFL season|1936]] and [[1937 NFL season|1937]]), although in 1937 he co-led the league. The first sole rushing touchdowns leader in consecutive seasons was [[Johnny Drake]], when he led in [[1939 NFL season|1939]] and [[1940 NFL season|1940]]. [[Steve Van Buren]] was the first to lead the league in 3 consecutive seasons, from [[1947 NFL season|1947]] to [[1949 NFL season|1949]], a figure later matched by Jim Brown (1957 to 1959) and [[Leroy Kelly]] ([[1966 NFL season|1966]] to [[1968 NFL season|1968]]). [[Marcus Allen]] is the only player in NFL history to lead the league in rushing touchdowns while playing with 2 different teams; in [[1982 NFL season|1982]], Allen led the league while playing with the [[Oakland Raiders]], and in [[1993 NFL season|1993]], he led the league while playing with the Kansas City Chiefs.\n\nIn [[1943 NFL season|1943]], [[Bill Paschal]] became the first NFL player to post a 10+ rushing touchdowns season, when playing for the [[New York Giants]]. 40 seasons later, in [[1983 NFL season|1983]], [[John Riggins]] posted the league's first 20+ rushing touchdowns season. Steve Van Buren was the first player to lead the league with consecutive 10+ rushing touchdowns seasons, in 1947 and [[1948 NFL season|1948]]; he would add a third consecutive in 1949. [[Emmitt Smith]] posted the first consecutive league-leading 20+ rushing touchdowns seasons in [[1994 NFL season|1994]] and [[1995 NFL season|1995]]\u2013an achievement later matched by [[Priest Holmes]], in [[2003 NFL season|2003]] and [[2004 NFL season|2004]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dean|first=Rick|url=http://cjonline.com/stories/010504/leg_main.shtml|title=High Priest\u2013KC's Holmes tops pair of NFL charts|publisher=The Capital-Journal|date=January 5, 2004|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==List==\nThe following is the season-by-season listing:<ref name=list/>\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Bronko Nagurski.jpg|thumb|200px|Bronko Nagurski led the league in rushing touchdowns in 1932]] -->\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Dutch Clark.jpg|thumb|200px|Dutch Clark became the first to lead the league in rushing touchdowns in consecutive seasons, with his 1936 & 1937 efforts]] -->[[File:JimBrownByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|200px|In 1965, Jim Brown led the league in rushing touchdowns for a fifth time, an NFL record]]\n[[File:Marcus Allen.jpg|thumb|200px|Marcus Allen, league leader in 1982 and 1993 the only player to lead the league in rushing touchdowns with 2 different teams]]\n[[File:John Riggins.jpg|thumb|200px|John Riggins led the league in 1983 with the first 20+ rushing touchdown season]]\n[[File:Marshawn Lynch vs. Redskins 2014.jpg|thumb|200px|Marshawn Lynch co-lead the league in receiving touchdowns in 2013 and 2014]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align center:;\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"|Set record*\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style= style=\"width:70%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Player\n! TDs\n! Team\n|-\n| 1932\n| [[Bronko Nagurski]]\n| 4\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1933\n| [[Glenn Presnell]]\n| 6\n| [[The Portsmouth Spartans|Portsmouth Spartans]]\n|-\n| 1934\n| [[Dutch Clark]]<br>[[Beattie Feathers]]\n| 8\n| [[Detroit Lions]]<br>[[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1935\n| [[Ernie Caddel]]\n| 6\n| [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1936\n| [[Dutch Clark]]\n| 7\n| [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1937\n| [[Cliff Battles]]<br>[[Dutch Clark]]<br>[[Clarke Hinkle]]\n| 5\n| [[W