| 2009\n| [[Adrian Peterson]]\n| 18\n| [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[Arian Foster]]\n| 16\n| [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[LeSean McCoy]]\n| 17\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Arian Foster]]\n| 15\n| [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Jamaal Charles]]<br>[[Marshawn Lynch]]\n| 12\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]<br> [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[Marshawn Lynch]]<br>[[DeMarco Murray]]\n| 13\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]<br> [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Devonta Freeman]]<br>[[Jeremy Hill (American football)|Jeremy Hill]]<br>[[Adrian Peterson]]<br>[[DeAngelo Williams]]\n| 11\n| [[Atlanta Falcons]]<br>[[Cincinnati Bengals]]<br>[[Minnesota Vikings]]<br>[[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[LeGarrette Blount]]\n| 18\n| [[New England Patriots]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Todd Gurley|Todd Gurley II]]\n| 13\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Todd Gurley|Todd Gurley II]]\n| 17\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[Derrick Henry]]<br>[[Aaron Jones (running back)|Aaron Jones]]\n| 16\n| [[Tennessee Titans]]<br>[[Green Bay Packers]]\n|}\n\n==Other rushing touchdowns leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! League\n! Player\n! TDs\n! Team\n|-\n| 1946\n| [[All-America Football Conference|AAFC]]\n| [[Len Eshmont]]<br>[[Don Greenwood (American football)|Don Greenwood]]<br>[[John Kimbrough]]<br>[[Spec Sanders]]\n| 6\n| [[San Francisco 49ers]]<br>[[Cleveland Browns]]<br>[[Los Angeles Dons]]<br>[[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]]\n|-\n| 1947\n| AAFC\n| [[Spec Sanders]]\n| 18\n| [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]]\n|-\n| 1948\n| AAFC\n| [[Chet Mutryn]]<br>[[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]]\n| 10\n| [[Buffalo Bills (AAFC)|Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| 1949\n| AAFC\n| [[Marion Motley]]<br>[[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]]\n| 8\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]<br>[[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| 1960\n| [[American Football League|AFL]]\n| [[Abner Haynes]]\n| 9\n| [[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]\n|-\n| 1961\n| AFL\n| [[Abner Haynes]]<br>[[Paul Lowe]]\n| 9\n| [[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]<br>[[San Diego Chargers]]\n|-\n| 1962\n| AFL\n| [[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Abner Haynes]]\n| 13\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]\n|-\n| 1963\n| AFL\n| [[Cookie Gilchrist]]\n| 12\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1964\n| AFL\n| [[Sid Blanks]]<br>[[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Daryle Lamonica]]\n| 6\n| [[Houston Oilers]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1965\n| AFL\n| [[Wray Carlton]]<br>[[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Paul Lowe]]<br>[[Curtis McClinton]]\n| 6\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Denver Broncos]]<br>[[San Diego Chargers]]<br>[[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n|-\n| 1966\n| AFL\n| [[Jim Nance]]\n| 11\n| [[Boston Patriots]]\n|-\n| 1967\n| AFL\n| [[Emerson Boozer]]\n| 10\n| [[New York Jets]]\n|-\n| 1968\n| AFL\n| [[Paul Robinson (American football)|Paul Robinson]]\n| 8\n| [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n|-\n| 1969\n| AFL\n| [[Jim Kiick]]\n| 9\n| [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n[[List of National Football League career rushing touchdowns leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NFL rushing touchdowns leaders}}\n{{American Football League rushing touchdowns leaders}}\n{{NFL records}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League records and achievements|Rushing touchdowns leaders]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Tomlinson warming up.jpg|thumb|200px|LaDainian Tomlinson led the league in 2006, and set the NFL record for most rushing touchdowns in a season, with 28.]]\nThis is a season-by-season list of [[National Football League]] players who have led the [[season (sports)|regular season]] in [[rush (gridiron football)|rushing]] [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=list>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rush_td_year_by_year.htm|title=NFL Year-by-Year Rushing Touchdowns Leaders|publisher=Sports-Reference|work=Pro-Football-Reference|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Although ''rushing'' has both an [[American football#offensive unit|offensive]] and a [[American football#defensive unit|defensive]] meaning, this list charts offensive rushing touchdowns, usually scored by a [[running back]], either a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] or a [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]].\n\nRecord-keeping for rushing touchdowns began in [[1932 NFL season|1932]], when [[Bronko Nagurski]] of the [[Chicago Bears]] led the league with 4 rushing touchdowns. Since then, [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] has set the record for rushing touchdowns in a season, when he led the league in [[2006 NFL season|2006]], with 28 rushing touchdowns, while playing with the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/ladainian-tomlinson-breaks-single-season-touchdown-record|title=LaDainian Tomlinson breaks single-season touchdown record|publisher=History|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> Prior to Tomlinson's setting of the record, [[Priest Holmes]] of the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] and [[Shaun Alexander]] of the [[Seattle Seahawks]], jointly held the record with 27, reaching that mark in [[2003 NFL season]] and [[2005 NFL season|2005]], respectively.\n\n[[Jim Brown]] holds the record for most league-leading seasons in rushing touchdowns, with 5 ([[1957 NFL season|1957]], [[1958 NFL season|1958]], [[1959 NFL season|1959]], [[1963 NFL season|1963]], and [[1965 NFL season|1965]]).<ref>{{cite web|last=Peticca|first=Mike|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2013/07/cleveland_browns_100_best_all-_60.html|title=Cleveland Browns' 100 best all-time players: No. 2, Jim Brown (video)|publisher=Cleveland|work=The Plain Dealer|date=July 29, 2013|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> [[Dutch Clark]] became the first player to lead the league in consecutive seasons ([[1936 NFL season|1936]] and [[1937 NFL season|1937]]), although in 1937 he co-led the league. The first sole rushing touchdowns leader in consecutive seasons was [[Johnny Drake]], when he led in [[1939 NFL season|1939]] and [[1940 NFL season|1940]]. [[Steve Van Buren]] was the first to lead the league in 3 consecutive seasons, from [[1947 NFL season|1947]] to [[1949 NFL season|1949]], a figure later matched by Jim Brown (1957 to 1959) and [[Leroy Kelly]] ([[1966 NFL season|1966]] to [[1968 NFL season|1968]]). [[Marcus Allen]] is the only player in NFL history to lead the league in rushing touchdowns while playing with 2 different teams; in [[1982 NFL season|1982]], Allen led the league while playing with the [[Oakland Raiders]], and in [[1993 NFL season|1993]], he led the league while playing with the Kansas City Chiefs.\n\nIn [[1943 NFL season|1943]], [[Bill Paschal]] became the first NFL player to post a 10+ rushing touchdowns season, when playing for the [[New York Giants]]. 40 seasons later, in [[1983 NFL season|1983]], [[John Riggins]] posted the league's first 20+ rushing touchdowns season. Steve Van Buren was the first player to lead the league with consecutive 10+ rushing touchdowns seasons, in 1947 and [[1948 NFL season|1948]]; he would add a third consecutive in 1949. [[Emmitt Smith]] posted the first consecutive league-leading 20+ rushing touchdowns seasons in [[1994 NFL season|1994]] and [[1995 NFL season|1995]]\u2013an achievement later matched by [[Priest Holmes]], in [[2003 NFL season|2003]] and [[2004 NFL season|2004]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dean|first=Rick|url=http://cjonline.com/stories/010504/leg_main.shtml|title=High Priest\u2013KC's Holmes tops pair of NFL charts|publisher=The Capital-Journal|date=January 5, 2004|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==List==\nThe following is the season-by-season listing:<ref name=list/>\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Bronko Nagurski.jpg|thumb|200px|Bronko Nagurski led the league in rushing touchdowns in 1932]] -->\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Dutch Clark.jpg|thumb|200px|Dutch Clark became the first to lead the league in rushing touchdowns in consecutive seasons, with his 1936 & 1937 efforts]] -->[[File:JimBrownByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|200px|In 1965, Jim Brown led the league in rushing touchdowns for a fifth time, an NFL record]]\n[[File:Marcus Allen.jpg|thumb|200px|Marcus Allen, league leader in 1982 and 1993 the only player to lead the league in rushing touchdowns with 2 different teams]]\n[[File:John Riggins.jpg|thumb|200px|John Riggins led the league in 1983 with the first 20+ rushing touchdown season]]\n[[File:Marshawn Lynch vs. Redskins 2014.jpg|thumb|200px|Marshawn Lynch co-lead the league in receiving touchdowns in 2013 and 2014]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align center:;\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"|Set record*\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style= style=\"width:70%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Player\n! TDs\n! Team\n|-\n| 1932\n| [[Bronko Nagurski]]\n| 4\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1933\n| [[Glenn Presnell]]\n| 6\n| [[The Portsmouth Spartans|Portsmouth Spartans]]\n|-\n| 1934\n| [[Dutch Clark]]<br>[[Beattie Feathers]]\n| 8\n| [[Detroit Lions]]<br>[[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1935\n| [[Ernie Caddel]]\n| 6\n| [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1936\n| [[Dutch Clark]]\n| 7\n| [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1937\n| [[Cliff Battles]]<br>[[Dutch Clark]]<br>[[Clarke Hinkle]]\n| 5\n| [[Washington Redskins]]<br>[[Detroit Lions]]<br>[[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| 1938\n| [[Andy Farkas]]\n| 6\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1939\n| [[Johnny Drake]]\n| 9\n| [[History of the St. Louis Rams#NFL Cleveland Rams (1937\u20131945)|Cleveland Rams]]\n|-\n| 1940\n| [[Johnny Drake]]\n| 9\n| [[History of the St. Louis Rams#NFL Cleveland Rams (1937\u20131945)|Cleveland Rams]]\n|-\n| 1941\n| [[Hugh Gallarneau]]\n| 8\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1942\n| [[Gary Famiglietti]]\n| 8\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1943\n| [[Bill Paschal]]\n| 10\n| [[New York Giants]]\n|-\n| 1944\n| [[Bill Paschal]]\n| 9\n| [[New York Giants]]\n|-\n| 1945\n| [[Steve Van Buren]]\n| 15\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 1946\n| [[Ted Fritsch]]\n| 9\n| [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| 1947\n| [[Steve Van Buren]]\n| 13\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 1948\n| [[Steve Van Buren]]\n| 10\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 1949\n| [[Steve Van Buren]]\n| 11\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 1950\n| [[Johnny Lujack]]\n| 11\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1951\n| [[Rob Goode]]\n| 9\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1952\n| [[Dan Towler]]\n| 10\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1953\n| [[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]]\n| 10\n| [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| 1954\n| [[Dan Towler]]\n| 11\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1955\n| [[Alan Ameche]]\n| 9\n| [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore Colts]]\n|-\n| 1956\n| [[Rick Casares]]\n| 12\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1957\n| [[Jim Brown]]\n| 9\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1958\n| [[Jim Brown]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 17*\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1959\n| [[Jim Brown]]\n| 14\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1960\n| [[Paul Hornung]]\n| 13\n| [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| 1961\n| [[Jim Taylor (fullback)|Jim Taylor]]\n| 15\n| [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| 1962\n| [[Jim Taylor (fullback)|Jim Taylor]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 19*\n| [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| 1963\n| [[Jim Brown]]\n| 12\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1964\n| [[Lenny Moore]]\n| 16\n| [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore Colts]]\n|-\n| 1965\n| [[Jim Brown]]\n| 17\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1966\n| [[Leroy Kelly]]\n| 15\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1967\n| [[Leroy Kelly]]\n| 11\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1968\n| [[Leroy Kelly]]\n| 16\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| 1969\n| [[Tom Matte]]\n| 11\n| [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore Colts]]\n|-\n| 1970\n| [[MacArthur Lane]]\n| 11\n| [[History of the St. Louis Cardinals (NFL)|St. Louis Cardinals]]\n|-\n| 1971\n| [[Duane Thomas]]\n| 11\n| [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 1972\n| [[Mercury Morris]]\n| 12\n| [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|-\n| 1973\n| [[Floyd Little]]<br>[[O. J. Simpson]]\n| 12\n| [[Denver Broncos]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1974\n| [[Tom Sullivan (American football)|Tom Sullivan]]\n| 11\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 1975\n| [[Pete Banaszak]]<br>[[O. J. Simpson]]\n| 16\n| [[Oakland Raiders]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1976\n| [[Franco Harris]]\n| 14\n| [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|-\n| 1977\n| [[Walter Payton]]\n| 14\n| [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| 1978\n| [[David Sims (running back)|David Sims]]\n| 14\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| 1979\n| [[Earl Campbell]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 19*\n| [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]]\n|-\n| 1980\n| [[Earl Campbell]]<br>[[Billy Sims]]\n| 13\n| [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]]<br>[[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1981\n| [[Chuck Muncie]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 19*\n| [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| [[Marcus Allen]]\n| 11\n| [[History of the Los Angeles Raiders|Los Angeles Raiders]]\n|-\n| 1983\n| [[John Riggins]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 24*\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1984\n| [[Eric Dickerson]]<br>[[John Riggins]]\n| 14\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]<br>[[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1985\n| [[Joe Morris (American football)|Joe Morris]]\n| 21\n| [[New York Giants]]\n|-\n| 1986\n| [[George Rogers (American football)|George Rogers]]\n| 18\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Johnny Hector]]<br>[[Charles White (American football)|Charles White]]\n| 11\n| [[New York Jets]]<br>[[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1988\n| [[Greg Bell (American football)|Greg Bell]]\n| 16\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1989\n| [[Greg Bell (American football)|Greg Bell]]\n| 15\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1990\n| [[Derrick Fenner]]<br>[[Cleveland Gary]]\n| 14\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]<br>[[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 1991\n| [[Barry Sanders]]\n| 16\n| [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| 1992\n| [[Emmitt Smith]]\n| 18\n| [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| [[Marcus Allen]]\n| 12\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| [[Emmitt Smith]]\n| 21\n| [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[Emmitt Smith]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 25*\n| [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| [[Terry Allen (running back)|Terry Allen]]\n| 21\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| [[Abdul-Karim al-Jabbar|Karim Abdul-Jabbar]]<br>[[Terrell Davis]]\n| 15\n| [[Miami Dolphins]]<br>[[Denver Broncos]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| [[Terrell Davis]]\n| 21\n| [[Denver Broncos]]\n|-\n| 1999\n| [[Stephen Davis (American football)|Stephen Davis]]\n| 17\n| [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| [[Marshall Faulk]]\n| 18\n| [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| [[Shaun Alexander]]\n| 14\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[Priest Holmes]]\n| 21\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[Priest Holmes]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 27*\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n|-\n| 2004\n| [[LaDainian Tomlinson]]\n| 17\n| [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]]\n\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Shaun Alexander]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 27*\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[LaDainian Tomlinson]]\n| style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"| 28*\n| [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]]\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[LaDainian Tomlinson]]\n| 15\n| [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[DeAngelo Williams]]\n| 18\n| [[Carolina Panthers]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[Adrian Peterson]]\n| 18\n| [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[Arian Foster]]\n| 16\n| [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[LeSean McCoy]]\n| 17\n| [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Arian Foster]]\n| 15\n| [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Jamaal Charles]]<br>[[Marshawn Lynch]]\n| 12\n| [[Kansas City Chiefs]]<br> [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[Marshawn Lynch]]<br>[[DeMarco Murray]]\n| 13\n| [[Seattle Seahawks]]<br> [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Devonta Freeman]]<br>[[Jeremy Hill (American football)|Jeremy Hill]]<br>[[Adrian Peterson]]<br>[[DeAngelo Williams]]\n| 11\n| [[Atlanta Falcons]]<br>[[Cincinnati Bengals]]<br>[[Minnesota Vikings]]<br>[[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[LeGarrette Blount]]\n| 18\n| [[New England Patriots]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Todd Gurley|Todd Gurley II]]\n| 13\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Todd Gurley|Todd Gurley II]]\n| 17\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[Derrick Henry]]<br>[[Aaron Jones (running back)|Aaron Jones]]\n| 16\n| [[Tennessee Titans]]<br>[[Green Bay Packers]]\n|}\n\n==Other rushing touchdowns leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! League\n! Player\n! TDs\n! Team\n|-\n| 1946\n| [[All-America Football Conference|AAFC]]\n| [[Len Eshmont]]<br>[[Don Greenwood (American football)|Don Greenwood]]<br>[[John Kimbrough]]<br>[[Spec Sanders]]\n| 6\n| [[San Francisco 49ers]]<br>[[Cleveland Browns]]<br>[[Los Angeles Dons]]<br>[[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]]\n|-\n| 1947\n| AAFC\n| [[Spec Sanders]]\n| 18\n| [[New York Yankees (AAFC)|New York Yankees]]\n|-\n| 1948\n| AAFC\n| [[Chet Mutryn]]<br>[[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]]\n| 10\n| [[Buffalo Bills (AAFC)|Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| 1949\n| AAFC\n| [[Marion Motley]]<br>[[Joe Perry (American football)|Joe Perry]]\n| 8\n| [[Cleveland Browns]]<br>[[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| 1960\n| [[American Football League|AFL]]\n| [[Abner Haynes]]\n| 9\n| [[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]\n|-\n| 1961\n| AFL\n| [[Abner Haynes]]<br>[[Paul Lowe]]\n| 9\n| [[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]<br>[[San Diego Chargers]]\n|-\n| 1962\n| AFL\n| [[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Abner Haynes]]\n| 13\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Dallas Texans (AFL)|Dallas Texans]]\n|-\n| 1963\n| AFL\n| [[Cookie Gilchrist]]\n| 12\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1964\n| AFL\n| [[Sid Blanks]]<br>[[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Daryle Lamonica]]\n| 6\n| [[Houston Oilers]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| 1965\n| AFL\n| [[Wray Carlton]]<br>[[Cookie Gilchrist]]<br>[[Paul Lowe]]<br>[[Curtis McClinton]]\n| 6\n| [[Buffalo Bills]]<br>[[Denver Broncos]]<br>[[San Diego Chargers]]<br>[[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n|-\n| 1966\n| AFL\n| [[Jim Nance]]\n| 11\n| [[Boston Patriots]]\n|-\n| 1967\n| AFL\n| [[Emerson Boozer]]\n| 10\n| [[New York Jets]]\n|-\n| 1968\n| AFL\n| [[Paul Robinson (American football)|Paul Robinson]]\n| 8\n| [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n|-\n| 1969\n| AFL\n| [[Jim Kiick]]\n| 9\n| [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n[[List of National Football League rushing touchdowns leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NFL rushing touchdowns leaders}}\n{{American Football League rushing touchdowns leaders}}\n{{NFL records}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League records and achievements|Rushing touchdowns leaders]]\n", "name_user": "WakandaForever188", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_National_Football_League_annual_rushing_touchdowns_leaders"}
{"title_page": "Batman Returns (Atari Lynx game)", "text_new": "{{about|the 1992 Atari Lynx video game|the other video games based on the eponymous film|Batman Returns (video game)|the 1992 film|Batman Returns}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title      = Batman Returns\n|image      = Atari Lynx Batman Returns cover art.jpg\n|developer  = [[Atari Corporation]]\n|publisher  = Atari Corporation\n|producer   = John Skruch\n|programmer = Eric Ginner<br />Jerome Strach\n|artist     = Eric Blumrich<br />Eric Elliot<br />Melody Rondeau\n|composer   = Alex Rudis <small>(Uncredited)</small><ref name=\"AEOv1i1\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=AE Online NewsRoom - Batman Returns!|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=1|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=May 1, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />Robert Vieira\n|series     = ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]''\n|platforms  = [[Atari Lynx]]\n|released   = {{vgrelease|NA|June [[1992 in video gaming|1992]]|EU|1992}}\n|genre      = [[Action game|Action]]-[[beat 'em up]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Batman Returns''''' is a [[1992 in video gaming|1992]] [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[Action game|action]]-[[beat 'em up]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Atari Corporation]] in North America and Europe exclusively for the [[Atari Lynx]].<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/Atari_Explorer_May_June_1992.pdf|title=Entertainment: Batman Returns - Atari Welcomes The Caped Crusader To The Silver LCD!|magazine=Atari Explorer|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|format=PDF|date=May-June 1992|pages=29\u201331|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926091538/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/Atari_Explorer_May_June_1992.pdf|archive-date=2018-09-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EGM36\">{{cite magazine|first=|last=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_036#page/n69/mode/2up|title=Next Wave - Batman Returns|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=36|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=July 1992|pages=70-73}}</ref> Based on the popular [[DC Comics]] [[superhero]] [[Batman]], it is inspired by the [[Warner Bros.]]'s [[1992 in film|1992]] [[Batman Returns|film of the same name]]. In the main storyline, Batman must confront both [[Catwoman (Batman Returns)|Catwoman]] and the [[Penguin (character)|Penguin]].\n\nHeaded by ''[[Checkered Flag (1991 video game)|Checkered Flag]]'' [[Video game producer|producer]] John Skruch, ''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Atari Corp. for their [[Video game#Platforms|platform]]. The team undertook the Lynx version in [[1991 in video gaming|1991]] but a tight development cycle and multiple issues were faced during the creation process before its eventual launch to the market, which were attributed to the film's production schedule.\n\n''Batman Returns'' on the Lynx was met with mixed reception from critics and reviewers alike since its release; common complaints were towards the high level of difficulty, steep learning curve and repetitive gameplay, although it was praised for its presentation, detailed graphics and sound design. The title later became a [[pack-in game]] for the [[Atari Lynx#Lynx II|Lynx II]] in certain regions.<ref name=\"AGamer\">{{cite web|last=Kromin|first=Igor|url=https://atarigamer.com/pages/atari-lynx-ii-console-box---batman-returns---p-n-pa4401|title=Atari Lynx II Console Box - Batman Returns - P/N PA4401|website=atarigamer.com|date=September 2, 2019|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222044849/https://atarigamer.com/pages/atari-lynx-ii-console-box---batman-returns---p-n-pa4401|archive-date=2020-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Z35\">{{cite magazine|last=Lopez|first=Amaya|url=https://archive.org/stream/Zero_Issue_35_1992-09_Dennis_Publishing_GB#page/n6/mode/1up|title=Smaaart! - News: Batman's Silica Job|magazine=[[Zero (video game magazine)|Zero]]|issue=35|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=September 1992|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:LYNX Batman Returns.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx is a side-scrolling action-beat 'em up game where players take control of Batman through four increasingly difficult stages fighting against multiple adversaries such as the Red Triangle Gang in order to stop both Catwoman and the Penguin from spreading terror across [[Gotham City]] as the main objective.<ref name=\"EGM36\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\">''Batman Returns'' game manual (Atari Lynx, US)</ref><ref name=\"BRLYNX\">{{cite web|last=Pac|first=Classic|url=http://atariage.com/forums/topic/71230-1992-lynx-catalog/#entry874742|title=1992 Lynx Catalog|website=[[AtariAge]]|date=June 15, 2005|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In the first stage, Batman must face off the Red Triangle Gang with Penguin as the end level [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]]. The second stage pits Batman against the police on the rooftops with Catwoman as the end level boss. The third stage is about defeating Penguin's forces in the sewers, while the Penguin is fought for the last time in the fourth stage.<ref name=\"BRLYNX\"/> Along the way, Batman can grab a variety of [[Item (gaming)|item]]s to aid him on his journey against enemies such as [[batarang]]s and [[bat]]-shaped [[Health (gaming)|health]] pickups.<ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNX\"/>\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was created by most of the same staff that worked on previous projects at Atari Corp. for their platform such as ''Checkered Flag'', ''[[Klax (video game)|Klax]]'' and ''[[Warbirds (video game)|Warbirds]]'', among others.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=BATMAN RETURNS - ATARI WELCOMES THE CAPED CRUSADER: An Interview with John Skruch|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=4|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=June 14, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its development was supervised by producer John Skruch, with both Eric Ginner and Jerome Strach acting as co-[[Video game programmer|programmer]]s.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The [[visual art]] team was led by Susan G. McBride, who also worked as [[animator]] alongside [[Video game artist|artist]]s Eric Blumrich, Eric \"Coyote\" Elliott, Melody Rondeau, Philip Temple and Robb Mariani.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Mariani came from Atari's [[Chicago]] division, while both Blumrich and Temple were brought as contractors.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The audio was handled by [[Video game composer|composer]]s Robert \"Bob\" Vieira and Alex \"LX\" Rudis, although the latter is not named as such in the credits of the game.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/>\n\n[[File:Atari-Lynx-II-Handheld-Angled.jpg|right|thumb|''Batman Returns'' for the Atari Lynx went through a turbulent development cycle before launch to coincide with the film's premiere. It later became a pack-in game for the Lynx II.]]\nJohn Skruch recounted the game's creation process and history through publications like ''Atari Explorer''.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Skruch stated that Atari undertook the project in September 1991 but due to the movie's tight production schedule, the team did not received a preliminary synopsis of the plot until November of the same year.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Conceptualization began at that point until other original production materials such as stills and a [[shooting script]] arrived on January 1992, when the development team was prepared to start programming work, although members of the staff worked on the Lynx [[Video game conversion|conversion]] of ''[[Rampart (video game)|Rampart]]'' during their [[leisure]] early in the development cycle.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> \n\nSkruch also stated that several issues were faced during development like approval from actors of [[publicity still]]s with appearance of their likeness before their distribution, as well as redesigning certain aspects in the game to be more in line with the final movie version due to constant changes during the filming process.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> When designing the game, Skruch and the team wanted to convey major scenes of the film in an action game format, while gameplay was made to resemble the Lynx version of ''[[Rygar]]''.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The team also ensured that the portrayal of Batman's [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] was accurate to the film as well.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Due to opting in having the game complete to coincide with the movie's release, members of the staff worked [[overtime]] over the course of several months during development.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Despite these setbacks, Skruch claimed that work on the project proved to be \"totally exhilarating\".<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/>\n\n''Batman Returns'' for the Atari Lynx was released on June 1992 to coincide with its eponymous film's [[premiere]].<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"EGM36\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|author=Bonehead|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_038_September_1992#page/n117/mode/2up|title=Special Feature: Lynx Year-End Extravaganza!|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=38|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=September 1992|pages=134\u2013136}}</ref> The game was also showcased during the 1992 [[Taste of Chicago]] [[food festival]] along with other Lynx titles such as ''[[Hydra (video game)|Hydra]]''.<ref name=\"AEOv1i8\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=Z*NET NEWSWIRE - Latest Atari News and Industry Update: ATARI VIDEO GAME CONTEST|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=8|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=July 18, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The title later became a pack-in game for the Lynx II in certain regions.<ref name=\"AGamer\"/><ref name=\"Z35\"/>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|Allgame    = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"AGLYNXbr\">{{cite web|last=Williamson|first=Colin|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=375&tab=review|title=Batman Returns (Atari Lynx) - Review|work=[[AllGame]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|date=1998|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114130612/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=375&tab=review|archive-date=2014-11-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|GamePro    = 17.5 / 25<ref name=\"GProLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Sinister|first=Sister|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_039_October_1992#page/n41/mode/1up|title=Special Feature: Bruce Wayne's World - Batman Returns (by Atari)|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=39|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=October 1992|page=40}}</ref>\n|IGN        = 8.0 / 10<ref name=\"IGNLYNXbr\">{{cite web|last=A. Jung|first=Robert|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/1999/07/01/batman-returns|title=Batman Returns - Guaranteed to sell more Lynxes. Atari's Batman Returns reviewed|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=July 1, 1999|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815202843/http://www.ign.com/articles/1999/07/01/batman-returns|archive-date=2018-08-15|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|rev1       = ''[[Aktueller Software Markt]]''\n|rev1Score  = 9 / 12<ref name=\"ASMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=H\u00f6fer|first1=Marcus|last2=Anton|first2=Michael|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=4537|title=Konsolen: Batman Returns (Lynx) - Enten & Flederma\u00fcse|magazine=[[Aktueller Software Markt]]|issue=67|publisher=Tronic Verlag|date=September 1992|page=128|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev2       = ''[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]''\n|rev2Score  = 46%<ref name=\"C+LYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|author1=Axel|author2=Robby|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8679&album=oui|title=Lynx Review - Batman II: Le Retour|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=12|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=September 1992|pages=108-109|lang=fr|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114055934/http://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8679&album=oui|archive-date=2017-11-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev3       = ''Game Zero Magazine''\n|rev3Score  = 74.5 / 100<ref name=\"GZMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=Man|first1=Ferrari|author2=????|author3=R.I.P.|author4=Salamander|url=http://www.gamezero.com/team-0/final_word/lynx/batman_returns.html|title=The Final Word game review - Batman Returns -- Atari|magazine=Game Zero Magazine|volume=1|issue=3|publisher=Game Zero|date=August-September 1992|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808024439/http://www.gamezero.com/team-0/final_word/lynx/batman_returns.html|archive-date=2018-08-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4       = ''[[Hobby Consolas]]''\n|rev4Score  = 89 / 100<ref name=\"HCLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Garc\u00eda|first=Juan Carlos|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:HobbyConsolas_ES_011.pdf&page=66|title=Lo M\u00e1s Nuevo - Lynx: Batman Returns \u2013 Vuelve el murci\u00e9lago|magazine=[[Hobby Consolas]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=August 1992|pages=74\u201375|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev5       = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev5Score  = 93%<ref name=\"JPadLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=Huyghues-Lacour|first1=Alain|last2=Nini|first2=Nourdine|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1780&album=oui|title=Lynx: Chauve-Souris Qui Peut, Batman Est De Retour! - Batman Returns|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]|issue=11|publisher=[[:fr:Yellow Media|Yellow Media]]|date=August-September 1992|pages=124-125|lang=fr|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916145810/http://abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1780&album=oui|archive-date=2017-09-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6       = ''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]''\n|rev6Score  = 93%<ref name=\"JStickLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Nini|first=Nourdine|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Joystick/joystick_numero029/page%20203.jpg|title=Consoles News - Lynx: Batman Returns|magazine=[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]|issue=29|publisher=[[:fr:Anuman Interactive|Anuman Interactive]]|date=July-August 1992|page=203|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev7       = ''[[Microman\u00eda]]''\n|rev7Score  = 49 / 60<ref name=\"MMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|author=F.D.L.|url=https://archive.org/stream/micromania-segunda-epoca-55#page/n46/mode/1up|title=Video Consolas: La Sombra Del Murci\u00e9lago Es Alargada - Batman Returns (LYNX, Arcade)|magazine=[[Microman\u00eda]]|volume=2|issue=55|publisher=HobbyPress|date=December 1992|page=47|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev8       = ''[[:de:Play Time|Play Time]]''\n|rev8Score  = 55%<ref name=\"PTLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Szameitat|first=Thorsten|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3APlayTime_DE_1992-10.pdf&page=113|title=Super Sonic - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Play Time|Play Time]]|issue=16|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=October 1992|page=113|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev9       = ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n|rev9Score  = 55%<ref name=\"POLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Drevet|first=Cyril|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Player%20One/playerone_numero023/Player%20One%20023%20-%20Page%20118%20%281992-09%29.jpg|title=Tests De Jeux - Lynx: Batman Returns - Ou comment massacrer une leg\u00e9nde sur une console portable couleur!|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=23|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=September-October 1992|page=118|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev10      = ''[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]''\n|rev10Score = 52%<ref name=\"PPLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Gollert|first=Knut|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=9377|title=Videospiele / Tests - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]|issue=53|publisher=Future Verlag|date=August 1992|page=141|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev11      = ''[[ST Format]]''\n|rev11Score = 77%<ref name=\"STFLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Hutchinson|first=Andy|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/hi_res/atari-st-format-issue-040_127.jpg|title=Screenplay - Lynx Games: Lynx Roundup - Batman Returns|magazine=[[ST Format]]|issue=40|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=November 1992|page=127|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927011048/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/hi_res/atari-st-format-issue-040_127.jpg|archive-date=2018-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev12      = ''[[:es:Superjuegos|Superjuegos]]''\n|rev12Score = 77,2 / 100<ref name=\"SJLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Iturrioz|first=Javier|url=https://archive.org/stream/Superjuegos_006#page/n41/mode/1up|title=Consola - En pantalla: Batman Returns - Un c\u00f3mic en acci\u00f3n (Lynx: arcade)|magazine=[[:es:Superjuegos|Superjuegos]]|issue=6|publisher=[[:es:Grupo Zeta|Grupo Zeta]]|date=September 1992|page=42|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev13      = ''[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]''\n|rev13Score = 38%<ref name=\"VGLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Barysch|first=Jan|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8446|title=Test: Lahme Flatter - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=9|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=August 1992|page=124|lang=de}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was received with mixed reception.<ref name=\"NAULYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Sweeney|first=John|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/page-6-issue-58.pdf|title=Lynx Games: Grab The Lynx Robin! - Hockey|magazine=[[New Atari User]]|issue=58|publisher=Page 6 Publishing|format=PDF|date=October-November 1992|page=46|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926114552/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/page-6-issue-58.pdf|archive-date=2018-09-26|url-status=live}}</ref> Sister Sinister of ''[[GamePro]]'' praised the Lynx version's graphics as \"exceptionally good considering the small venue\" and felt that the game's high difficulty compensated for its short length, although noted that while the audio \"ranks high on the rockability scale\", it became monotonous after a few hours.<ref name=\"GProLYNXbr\"/> Robert A. Jung of ''[[IGN]]'' described the Lynx version as \"respectable\" and commended the game's visuals, animations and difficulty.<ref name=\"IGNLYNXbr\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://atariage.com/software_page.php?SoftwareLabelID=1877 ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[AtariAge]]\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/lynx/586926-batman-returns ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/lynx/batman-returns__ ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Portal bar|1990s|USA|Video games}}\n{{Batman video games}}\n{{Batman in film}}\n{{Catwoman}}\n{{Atari Lynx games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batman Returns (Atari Lynx game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Action video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade and video games based on Batman films]]\n[[Category:Atari games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx-only games]]\n[[Category:Batman (1989 film series)]]\n[[Category:Christmas video games]]\n[[Category:Pack-in video games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Video games based on films]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Alex Rudis]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1992 Atari Lynx video game|the other video games based on the eponymous film|Batman Returns (video game)|the 1992 film|Batman Returns}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title      = Batman Returns\n|image      = Atari Lynx Batman Returns cover art.jpg\n|developer  = [[Atari Corporation]]\n|publisher  = Atari Corporation\n|producer   = John Skruch\n|programmer = Eric Ginner<br />Jerome Strach\n|artist     = Eric Blumrich<br />Eric Elliot<br />Melody Rondeau\n|composer   = Alex Rudis <small>(Uncredited)</small><ref name=\"AEOv1i1\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=AE Online NewsRoom - Batman Returns!|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=1|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=May 1, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />Robert Vieira\n|series     = ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]''\n|platforms  = [[Atari Lynx]]\n|released   = {{vgrelease|NA|June [[1992 in video gaming|1992]]|EU|1992}}\n|genre      = [[Action game|Action]]-[[beat 'em up]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Batman Returns''''' is a [[1992 in video gaming|1992]] [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[Action game|action]]-[[beat 'em up]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Atari Corporation]] in North America and Europe exclusively for the [[Atari Lynx]].<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/Atari_Explorer_May_June_1992.pdf|title=Entertainment: Batman Returns - Atari Welcomes The Caped Crusader To The Silver LCD!|magazine=Atari Explorer|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|format=PDF|date=May-June 1992|pages=29\u201331|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926091538/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/Atari_Explorer_May_June_1992.pdf|archive-date=2018-09-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EGM36\">{{cite magazine|first=|last=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_036#page/n69/mode/2up|title=Next Wave - Batman Returns|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=36|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=July 1992|pages=70-73}}</ref> Based on the popular [[DC Comics]] [[superhero]] [[Batman]], it is inspired by the [[Warner Bros.]]'s [[1992 in film|1992]] [[Batman Returns|film of the same name]]. In the main storyline, Batman must confront both [[Catwoman (Batman Returns)|Catwoman]] and the [[Penguin (character)|Penguin]].\n\nHeaded by ''[[Checkered Flag (1991 video game)|Checkered Flag]]'' [[Video game producer|producer]] John Skruch, ''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Atari Corp. for their [[Video game#Platforms|platform]]. The team undertook the Lynx version in [[1991 in video gaming|1991]] but a tight development cycle and multiple issues were faced during the creation process before its eventual launch to the market, which were attributed to the film's production schedule.\n\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was met with mixed reception from critics and reviewers alike since its release; common complaints were towards the high level of difficulty, steep learning curve and repetitive gameplay, although it was praised for its presentation, detailed graphics and sound design. The title later became a [[pack-in game]] for the [[Atari Lynx#Lynx II|Lynx II]] in certain regions.<ref name=\"AGamer\">{{cite web|last=Kromin|first=Igor|url=https://atarigamer.com/pages/atari-lynx-ii-console-box---batman-returns---p-n-pa4401|title=Atari Lynx II Console Box - Batman Returns - P/N PA4401|website=atarigamer.com|date=September 2, 2019|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222044849/https://atarigamer.com/pages/atari-lynx-ii-console-box---batman-returns---p-n-pa4401|archive-date=2020-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Z35\">{{cite magazine|last=Lopez|first=Amaya|url=https://archive.org/stream/Zero_Issue_35_1992-09_Dennis_Publishing_GB#page/n6/mode/1up|title=Smaaart! - News: Batman's Silica Job|magazine=[[Zero (video game magazine)|Zero]]|issue=35|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=September 1992|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:LYNX Batman Returns.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx is a side-scrolling action-beat 'em up game where players take control of Batman through four increasingly difficult stages fighting against multiple adversaries such as the Red Triangle Gang in order to stop both Catwoman and the Penguin from spreading terror across [[Gotham City]] as the main objective.<ref name=\"EGM36\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\">''Batman Returns'' game manual (Atari Lynx, US)</ref><ref name=\"BRLYNX\">{{cite web|last=Pac|first=Classic|url=http://atariage.com/forums/topic/71230-1992-lynx-catalog/#entry874742|title=1992 Lynx Catalog|website=[[AtariAge]]|date=June 15, 2005|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In the first stage, Batman must face off the Red Triangle Gang with Penguin as the end level [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]]. The second stage pits Batman against the police on the rooftops with Catwoman as the end level boss. The third stage is about defeating Penguin's forces in the sewers, while the Penguin is fought for the last time in the fourth stage.<ref name=\"BRLYNX\"/> Along the way, Batman can grab a variety of [[Item (gaming)|item]]s to aid him on his journey against enemies such as [[batarang]]s and [[bat]]-shaped [[Health (gaming)|health]] pickups.<ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNX\"/>\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was created by most of the same staff that worked on previous projects at Atari Corp. for their platform such as ''Checkered Flag'', ''[[Klax (video game)|Klax]]'' and ''[[Warbirds (video game)|Warbirds]]'', among others.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=BATMAN RETURNS - ATARI WELCOMES THE CAPED CRUSADER: An Interview with John Skruch|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=4|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=June 14, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its development was supervised by producer John Skruch, with both Eric Ginner and Jerome Strach acting as co-[[Video game programmer|programmer]]s.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The [[visual art]] team was led by Susan G. McBride, who also worked as [[animator]] alongside [[Video game artist|artist]]s Eric Blumrich, Eric \"Coyote\" Elliott, Melody Rondeau, Philip Temple and Robb Mariani.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Mariani came from Atari's [[Chicago]] division, while both Blumrich and Temple were brought as contractors.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The audio was handled by [[Video game composer|composer]]s Robert \"Bob\" Vieira and Alex \"LX\" Rudis, although the latter is not named as such in the credits of the game.<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"BRLYNXmanual\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/>\n\n[[File:Atari-Lynx-II-Handheld-Angled.jpg|right|thumb|''Batman Returns'' for the Atari Lynx went through a turbulent development cycle before launch to coincide with the film's premiere. It later became a pack-in game for the Lynx II.]]\nJohn Skruch recounted the game's creation process and history through publications like ''Atari Explorer''.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Skruch stated that Atari undertook the project in September 1991 but due to the movie's tight production schedule, the team did not received a preliminary synopsis of the plot until November of the same year.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Conceptualization began at that point until other original production materials such as stills and a [[shooting script]] arrived on January 1992, when the development team was prepared to start programming work, although members of the staff worked on the Lynx [[Video game conversion|conversion]] of ''[[Rampart (video game)|Rampart]]'' during their [[leisure]] early in the development cycle.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> \n\nSkruch also stated that several issues were faced during development like approval from actors of [[publicity still]]s with appearance of their likeness before their distribution, as well as redesigning certain aspects in the game to be more in line with the final movie version due to constant changes during the filming process.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> When designing the game, Skruch and the team wanted to convey major scenes of the film in an action game format, while gameplay was made to resemble the Lynx version of ''[[Rygar]]''.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> The team also ensured that the portrayal of Batman's [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] was accurate to the film as well.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Due to opting in having the game complete to coincide with the movie's release, members of the staff worked [[overtime]] over the course of several months during development.<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/> Despite these setbacks, Skruch claimed that work on the project proved to be \"totally exhilarating\".<ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/>\n\n''Batman Returns'' for the Atari Lynx was released on June 1992 to coincide with its eponymous film's [[premiere]].<ref name=\"AEOv1i1\"/><ref name=\"AEX\"/><ref name=\"EGM36\"/><ref name=\"AEOv1i4\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|author=Bonehead|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_038_September_1992#page/n117/mode/2up|title=Special Feature: Lynx Year-End Extravaganza!|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=38|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=September 1992|pages=134\u2013136}}</ref> The game was also showcased during the 1992 [[Taste of Chicago]] [[food festival]] along with other Lynx titles such as ''[[Hydra (video game)|Hydra]]''.<ref name=\"AEOv1i8\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|title=Z*NET NEWSWIRE - Latest Atari News and Industry Update: ATARI VIDEO GAME CONTEST|magazine=Atari Explorer Online|volume=1|issue=8|publisher=[[Atari Corporation]]|date=July 18, 1992|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202933/http://www.atarihq.com/jeo/archive.htm|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The title later became a pack-in game for the Lynx II in certain regions.<ref name=\"AGamer\"/><ref name=\"Z35\"/>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|Allgame    = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"AGLYNXbr\">{{cite web|last=Williamson|first=Colin|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=375&tab=review|title=Batman Returns (Atari Lynx) - Review|work=[[AllGame]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|date=1998|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114130612/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=375&tab=review|archive-date=2014-11-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|GamePro    = 17.5 / 25<ref name=\"GProLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Sinister|first=Sister|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_Issue_039_October_1992#page/n41/mode/1up|title=Special Feature: Bruce Wayne's World - Batman Returns (by Atari)|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=39|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=October 1992|page=40}}</ref>\n|IGN        = 8.0 / 10<ref name=\"IGNLYNXbr\">{{cite web|last=A. Jung|first=Robert|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/1999/07/01/batman-returns|title=Batman Returns - Guaranteed to sell more Lynxes. Atari's Batman Returns reviewed|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=July 1, 1999|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815202843/http://www.ign.com/articles/1999/07/01/batman-returns|archive-date=2018-08-15|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|rev1       = ''[[Aktueller Software Markt]]''\n|rev1Score  = 9 / 12<ref name=\"ASMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=H\u00f6fer|first1=Marcus|last2=Anton|first2=Michael|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=4537|title=Konsolen: Batman Returns (Lynx) - Enten & Flederma\u00fcse|magazine=[[Aktueller Software Markt]]|issue=67|publisher=Tronic Verlag|date=September 1992|page=128|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev2       = ''[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]''\n|rev2Score  = 46%<ref name=\"C+LYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|author1=Axel|author2=Robby|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8679&album=oui|title=Lynx Review - Batman II: Le Retour|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=12|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=September 1992|pages=108-109|lang=fr|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114055934/http://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8679&album=oui|archive-date=2017-11-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev3       = ''Game Zero Magazine''\n|rev3Score  = 74.5 / 100<ref name=\"GZMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=Man|first1=Ferrari|author2=????|author3=R.I.P.|author4=Salamander|url=http://www.gamezero.com/team-0/final_word/lynx/batman_returns.html|title=The Final Word game review - Batman Returns -- Atari|magazine=Game Zero Magazine|volume=1|issue=3|publisher=Game Zero|date=August-September 1992|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808024439/http://www.gamezero.com/team-0/final_word/lynx/batman_returns.html|archive-date=2018-08-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4       = ''[[Hobby Consolas]]''\n|rev4Score  = 89 / 100<ref name=\"HCLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Garc\u00eda|first=Juan Carlos|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:HobbyConsolas_ES_011.pdf&page=66|title=Lo M\u00e1s Nuevo - Lynx: Batman Returns \u2013 Vuelve el murci\u00e9lago|magazine=[[Hobby Consolas]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=August 1992|pages=74\u201375|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev5       = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev5Score  = 93%<ref name=\"JPadLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last1=Huyghues-Lacour|first1=Alain|last2=Nini|first2=Nourdine|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1780&album=oui|title=Lynx: Chauve-Souris Qui Peut, Batman Est De Retour! - Batman Returns|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]|issue=11|publisher=[[:fr:Yellow Media|Yellow Media]]|date=August-September 1992|pages=124-125|lang=fr|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916145810/http://abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1780&album=oui|archive-date=2017-09-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6       = ''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]''\n|rev6Score  = 93%<ref name=\"JStickLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Nini|first=Nourdine|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Joystick/joystick_numero029/page%20203.jpg|title=Consoles News - Lynx: Batman Returns|magazine=[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]|issue=29|publisher=[[:fr:Anuman Interactive|Anuman Interactive]]|date=July-August 1992|page=203|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev7       = ''[[Microman\u00eda]]''\n|rev7Score  = 49 / 60<ref name=\"MMLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|author=F.D.L.|url=https://archive.org/stream/micromania-segunda-epoca-55#page/n46/mode/1up|title=Video Consolas: La Sombra Del Murci\u00e9lago Es Alargada - Batman Returns (LYNX, Arcade)|magazine=[[Microman\u00eda]]|volume=2|issue=55|publisher=HobbyPress|date=December 1992|page=47|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev8       = ''[[:de:Play Time|Play Time]]''\n|rev8Score  = 55%<ref name=\"PTLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Szameitat|first=Thorsten|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3APlayTime_DE_1992-10.pdf&page=113|title=Super Sonic - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Play Time|Play Time]]|issue=16|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=October 1992|page=113|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev9       = ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n|rev9Score  = 55%<ref name=\"POLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Drevet|first=Cyril|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Player%20One/playerone_numero023/Player%20One%20023%20-%20Page%20118%20%281992-09%29.jpg|title=Tests De Jeux - Lynx: Batman Returns - Ou comment massacrer une leg\u00e9nde sur une console portable couleur!|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=23|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=September-October 1992|page=118|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev10      = ''[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]''\n|rev10Score = 52%<ref name=\"PPLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Gollert|first=Knut|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=9377|title=Videospiele / Tests - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]|issue=53|publisher=Future Verlag|date=August 1992|page=141|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev11      = ''[[ST Format]]''\n|rev11Score = 77%<ref name=\"STFLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Hutchinson|first=Andy|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/hi_res/atari-st-format-issue-040_127.jpg|title=Screenplay - Lynx Games: Lynx Roundup - Batman Returns|magazine=[[ST Format]]|issue=40|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=November 1992|page=127|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927011048/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/hi_res/atari-st-format-issue-040_127.jpg|archive-date=2018-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev12      = ''[[:es:Superjuegos|Superjuegos]]''\n|rev12Score = 77,2 / 100<ref name=\"SJLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Iturrioz|first=Javier|url=https://archive.org/stream/Superjuegos_006#page/n41/mode/1up|title=Consola - En pantalla: Batman Returns - Un c\u00f3mic en acci\u00f3n (Lynx: arcade)|magazine=[[:es:Superjuegos|Superjuegos]]|issue=6|publisher=[[:es:Grupo Zeta|Grupo Zeta]]|date=September 1992|page=42|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev13      = ''[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]''\n|rev13Score = 38%<ref name=\"VGLYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Barysch|first=Jan|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8446|title=Test: Lahme Flatter - Batman Returns (Lynx)|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=9|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=August 1992|page=124|lang=de}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Batman Returns'' on the Atari Lynx was received with mixed reception.<ref name=\"NAULYNXbr\">{{cite magazine|last=Sweeney|first=John|url=http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/page-6-issue-58.pdf|title=Lynx Games: Grab The Lynx Robin! - Hockey|magazine=[[New Atari User]]|issue=58|publisher=Page 6 Publishing|format=PDF|date=October-November 1992|page=46|access-date=2020-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926114552/http://www.atarimania.com/mags/pdf/page-6-issue-58.pdf|archive-date=2018-09-26|url-status=live}}</ref> Sister Sinister of ''[[GamePro]]'' praised the Lynx version's graphics as \"exceptionally good considering the small venue\" and felt that the game's high difficulty compensated for its short length, although noted that while the audio \"ranks high on the rockability scale\", it became monotonous after a few hours.<ref name=\"GProLYNXbr\"/> Robert A. Jung of ''[[IGN]]'' described the Lynx version as \"respectable\" and commended the game's visuals, animations and difficulty.<ref name=\"IGNLYNXbr\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://atariage.com/software_page.php?SoftwareLabelID=1877 ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[AtariAge]]\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/lynx/586926-batman-returns ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/lynx/batman-returns__ ''Batman Returns (Atari Lynx)''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Portal bar|1990s|USA|Video games}}\n{{Batman video games}}\n{{Batman in film}}\n{{Catwoman}}\n{{Atari Lynx games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batman Returns (Atari Lynx game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Action video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade and video games based on Batman films]]\n[[Category:Atari games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx-only games]]\n[[Category:Batman (1989 film series)]]\n[[Category:Christmas video games]]\n[[Category:Pack-in video games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Video games based on films]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Alex Rudis]]\n", "name_user": "KGRAMR", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batman_Returns_(Atari_Lynx_game)"}
{"title_page": "Socialism in New Zealand", "text_new": "{{Socialism sidebar |History by country}} \n{{Politics of New Zealand|expanded=Ideology}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2019}}\nThe extent to which [[socialism]] plays a part in modern [[Politics of New Zealand|New Zealand politics]] depends on which definitions of socialist are used, but few mainstream politicians would describe themselves using the word \"socialist\". The term \"[[social democracy|social-democrat]]\" is more common, but the more general \"[[left-wing politics|left-wing]]\" or \"[[centre-left politics|centre-left]]\" are used far more frequently. New Zealand has a complicated assortment of socialist causes and organisations. Some of these play a considerable role in public [[activism]]\u2014some commentators claim that New Zealand socialists are more prominent in causes such as the [[anti-war movement]] than in promoting socialism itself.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Other groups are strongly committed to radical socialist revolution.\n\nSeveral prominent [[List of political parties in New Zealand|political parties in New Zealand]], such as the [[New Zealand Labour Party]], have historical links to socialism but are not generally considered socialist today due to their acceptance of a [[market economy]]. More likely to receive this label are the small [[Marxism|Marxist]] organisations that exist outside the mainstream political world, such as [[Organise Aotearoa]], the [[International Socialist Organisation (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organisation]] and [[Socialist Aotearoa]].{{sfn|Wayne and Hope|2015|pp=548-551}}\n\n==History of New Zealand socialism==\nAcademic [[Josephine F. Milburn]] argues that socialist theories were introduced by immigrant workers with experience in the British labour movement. Their ideas were not widely accepted, however. The Liberal government that was dominant 1891-1912 rejected socialism but it supported unions and the [[Liberal Government of New Zealand]] set up the country's welfare state in the 1890s and fought the large land holders. She argues that governmental activism cannot be attributed to the influence of the small socialist movement.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Milburn |first1=Josephine |title=Socialism and Social Reform in Nineteenth-Century New Zealand |journal=Political Science |date=1960 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=62\u201370}}</ref>\n\n===Non-ideological socialism===\n{{Weasel|date=March 2009}}\nThe growth of socialism as an ideology in New Zealand only began to occur around the beginning of the 20th century. Some historians, however, claim that a sort of \"non-ideological\" socialism was born shortly after the establishment of self-government, and flourished in the late 19th century. This, they say, was mostly in the form of a \"[[paternalism|paternalistic]]\" government which believed in the need to speed the country's economic growth, rather than in the form of an ideologically leftist government. These historians argue that because of New Zealand's small size and its focus on agriculture, the newly established government was forced to assume responsibility for many things that would otherwise be undertaken by private enterprise - railways, banking, insurance, and many other things that New Zealand's small business sector could not yet afford. Premier [[Julius Vogel]] was a notable advocate of government projects of this nature. Later, the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] was accused by its opponents of being \"socialist\", although most within the party rejected this. One commentator has claimed that until the [[Russian Revolution of 1917]], New Zealand was the most socialist country in the world, although many believe that this is overstating the case.\n\n===Unions and workers' parties===\n[[File:Harry Holland (1925).jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Harry Holland]], a socialist who was a founder and leader of the modern [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]]]]\nIdeological socialism, when it arrived, mostly stemmed from Britain or other British colonies. Much of socialism's early growth was found in the labour movement, and often coincided with the growth of [[labor union|trade unions]]. During the 1870s, James McPherson and his Canterbury Working Men's Mutual Protection Society had written to [[Karl Marx]], requesting affiliation with the [[International Workingmen's Association|First International]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}} The [[New Zealand Federation of Labor]] (also known as the \"Red Federation\") was influenced by socialist theories, as were many other labour organizations. The Red Federation was formed in 1909 when a federation of the mining unions invited other unions to join a New Zealand Federation of Labour. The Red Federation's official organ was the ''[[Maoriland Worker]]'', which advocated militant unionism and socialism. Key Red Federation leaders included the [[Australia]]n&ndash;born Hickey and [[Paddy Webb]], and fellow Australian [[Bob Semple]]. In opposition to the Red Federation, mainstream trade and labour councils formed a rival [[New Zealand Federation of Labour (1909)|Federation of Labour]].{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=55-56}}\n\nThe arrival of 200 British socialists called the \"Clarion Settlers\" led to the formation of the [[New Zealand Socialist Party]] in 1901, which promoted the works of Marx and [[Friedrich Engels]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}} Strongly influenced by the British [[Independent Labour Party]], the Socialist Party advocated promoting socialism through education and agitation rather than elections. The group met with little tangible success, but it nevertheless had considerable impact on the development of New Zealand socialism, forging close ties with the \"Red Federation.\"{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=48-49, 55-56}} In particular, [[Edward Hunter (Billy Banjo)|Edward Hunter]] (sometimes known under the pen name \"[[Billy Banjo]]\", and a member of both the Socialist Party and the Red Federation), was a major figure in the spread of socialist ideas to the unions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Richadrson |first1=Lee |title=Hunter, Edward |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/3h45/hunter-edward |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1996}}</ref>{{sfn|Len Richardson|2002|pp=73-86}}\n\nIn the years leading up to the [[First World War]], several New Zealand and Australian socialists including [[Harry Holland]], [[Michael Joseph Savage]], [[Peter Fraser]], [[Harry Scott Bennett]], [[Tom Barker (trade unionist)|Tom Barker]], [[Tom Bloodworth]], and [[Bob Semple]] advocated the creation of a \"Cooperative Commonwealth\" in which all land and means of wealth production, distribution, and management would be owned and managed collectively by the people. Besides Marx and Engels, these antipodean socialists were influenced by various radical European and American writers including [[Henry George]], [[Edward Bellamy]], [[Georges Sorel]], [[August Bebel]], [[Eugene Debs]], [[Bill Haywood]], and [[Irving Fisher]]. In 1912, a Petone Marxian Club was formed and met every Monday. This was one of the forerunners to the [[New Zealand Marxian Association]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n\nThe growth of unionism eventually led to the establishment of a number of socialist-influenced parties. Originally, the working class vote was concentrated mainly with the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]], where a number of prominent left-wing politicians (such as [[Frederick Pirani]]) emerged. Later, however, there were increasing calls for an independent workers' party, particularly as the Liberals began to lose their reformist drive.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=47-49}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steven |first1=Oliver |title=Pirani, Frederick |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2p19/pirani-frederick |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe second organised party to gain a seat in Parliament (after the Liberal Party) was the small [[Independent Political Labour League]], which won an urban electorate in [[Wellington]] in the [[1908 New Zealand general election|1908 election]]. Later, in 1910, the IPLL was reformed as the [[New Zealand Labour Party (original)|Labour Party]] (not to be confused with the modern party).{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=51-57}}\n\n===Emergence of the Labour Party===\n[[File:Michael Joseph Savage Portrait.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Michael Joseph Savage]] was the first Labour [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]].]]\n{{Formation of New Zealand Labour Party}}\nThe growing drive for unity among left-wing groups resulted in a \"Unity Conference\" being called in 1912. This conference aimed to merge the various left-wing parties in New Zealand, including both the moderate Labour Party and the hardline Socialist Party. The Socialist Party, however, refused to attend the conference, and the new [[United Labour Party (New Zealand)|United Labour Party]] consisted only of the Labour Party and a number of independent campaigners.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=62-64}}\n\nPremier [[William Massey]]'s \"heavy-handed\" suppression of the [[Waihi miners' strike]] prompted another attempt at unity in 1913. This time, the Socialists were willing to attend. A new group, the [[Social Democratic Party (New Zealand)|Social Democratic Party]], was formed, merging the United Labour Party and the Socialist Party. A faction of the United Labour Party refused to accept the decision, however, and continued on under the same name. Later, a decision by the Social Democrats to support a strike of dockworkers and coal miners resulted in a number of Social Democratic leaders being arrested, leaving the party in disarray in the [[1914 New Zealand general election|1914 election]], the remnants of the United Labour Party actually won more seats than the \"united\" Social Democrats.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=61-68}}\n\nFinally, in 1916, it was agreed that the Social Democrats and the United Labour Party remnants would all be amalgamated into a single group, the [[New Zealand Labour Party]]. The new Labour Party was explicitly socialist, and was based around goals of redistribution of wealth, nationalization of industry, and elimination of conscription.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=69-71}}<ref name=\"Te Ara Origins\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 1. Origins of the Labour Party |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-1 |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref> Eventual Labour Party leader, [[Harry Holland]], was strongly socialist in his beliefs, having been associated with the Socialist Party and with the striking miners in Waihi. Holland believed that the militancy at Waihi was a sign of further impending class conflict. While the Labour Party gained some electoral success, it continued to trail the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] and the [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform Party]] until the replacement of Holland with [[Michael Joseph Savage]]. Savage, although also involved in the earlier Socialist Party, was more moderate than Holland, and Labour gained considerable support. Assisted by the [[Great Depression]], Labour won a decisive victory in the [[1935 New Zealand general election|1935 election]].{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=78-81, 87-95}}<ref name=\"First Labour government\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 2. First Labour government, 1935 to 1949 |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-2 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Labour's social democracy===\n[[File:John Alexander Lee.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[John A. Lee]] was a prominent socialist figure in the Labour Party from the 1920s until his expulsion in 1940]]\nDespite its socialist roots, the Labour Party shifted towards a more [[social democracy|social democratic]] orientation once in power. The [[First Labour Government of New Zealand|First Labour Government]] led by Savage and Peter Fraser implemented a range of socialist policies such as nationalising industry, broadcasting, transportation, and a [[Keynesianism|Keynesian]] welfare state. However, the party did not seek to abolish capitalism, instead opting for a [[mixed economy]]. Labour's welfare state and mixed economy were not challenged until the 1980s.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=87-105}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 2. First Labour government, 1935 to 1949 |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-2 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTwo years after the Labour Party lost the [[1949 New Zealand general election|1949 election]], the goal of implementing \"the socialisation of the means of production, distribution, and exchange\" was removed from the party's policy platform. This is sometimes seen as the end of any real claim to full socialism by the Labour Party. However, the shift away from socialism had not come about without dispute. Labour Party politician [[John A. Lee]] was harshly critical of the changes, and had eventually left to establish the [[Democratic Labour Party (New Zealand)|Democratic Labour Party]] in 1940. The party was considerably more socialist than Labour, but performed poorly. Many members eventually left the party, mostly due to Lee's perceived autocratic style.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=106-114}}<ref name=\"Ideology and unions\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 5. Ideology and the role of unions |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-5 |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fourth Labour Government]] under Prime Minister [[David Lange]] and [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Finance Minister]] [[Roger Douglas]] implemented several [[neoliberalism|neoliberal]] economic reforms known as [[Rogernomics]] which transitioned New Zealand's Keynesian economy towards a more free market model. Labour's abandonment of its traditional values fractured the party, leading disaffected members to join [[Jim Anderton]]'s [[NewLabour Party (New Zealand)|NewLabour Party]], [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Greens]], [[New Zealand Democratic Party for Social Credit]], and the [[Mana Motuhake]] parties under the [[Alliance (New Zealand political party)|Alliance]]. Successive Labour governments have promoted centre-left social and economic policies while preserving a free market economy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 4. Fourth, fifth and sixth Labour governments |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-4 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Hope and Scott|2015|p=547}} The current Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] identifies as a social democrat and formerly served as President of the [[International Union of Socialist Youth]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Tim|title=What Jacinda Ardern wants|url=https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2017/07/31/40717/what-jacinda-wants|accessdate=15 August 2017|work=Newsroom|date=1 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816062218/https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2017/07/31/40717/what-jacinda-wants|archivedate=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news|last1=Kirk|first1=Stacey|title=Jacinda Ardern says she can handle it and her path to the top would suggest she's right|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/politics/95327574/Jacinda-Ardern-says-shes-can-handle-it-and-her-path-to-the-top-would-suggest-shes-right|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=15 August 2017|date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rise of the Communist Party===\n[[File:CPNZ logo.jpg|right|thumb|The Communist Party of New Zealand existed between 1921 and 1994.]]\nEven before Holland's replacement, and especially after Labour's 1949 policy change, many people had come to the conclusion that the Labour Party had moved too far away from its socialist roots. Only two years after Labour's foundation, the [[New Zealand Marxian Association]] was established. The Marxian Association was inspired by the [[Socialist Party of Great Britain]] (SPGB) and focused on political action. It would later clash acrimoniously with Holland. The Marxian Association itself would fall prey to internal division in 1921. That year, a number of members who supported the [[Russian Revolution of 1917|Russian Revolution]] departed to form the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] (CPNZ). They were joined by two other revolutionary strands within the New Zealand Socialist Party: the [[De Leonism|De Lonites]] who espoused revolutionary politics and industrial unionism; and the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW)-[[syndicalism|syndicalist]] tradition who advocated direct action and spurned political activity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Kerry |title='Our Motto, No Compromise': The Ideological Origins and Foundation of the Communist Party of New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1994 |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=160\u2013177 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=712&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bennett|2004|pp=74-75}}\n\nIn 1930, however, former members of the Marxian Association (backed by members of the [[Socialist Party of Australia (WSM)]]) established the [[Socialist Party of New Zealand]] (distinct from the earlier [[New Zealand Socialist Party]]). This group denied that the Labour Party (or even any of the parties before it, except for the Marxian Association) represented genuine socialism. The new Socialist Party still exists today, although has slightly modified its name (becoming the [[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]]).<ref name=\"Standard2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2000s/2004/no-1203-november-2004/marxian-socialism-new-zealand|title=Marxian Socialism in New Zealand|author=Peter E. Newell|newspaper=[[Socialist Standard]]|date=November 2004|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the CPNZ built its support from miners in the [[South Island]]'s [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] in the [[North Island]]'s [[Waikato]] district, and from seamen and waterside workers. The party faithfully followed the official position of the Soviet Union, modelling its aims, beliefs, manifesto and organisational structure and processes on those of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] (CPSU). The Soviets also sought to guide international Communist parties through the [[Communist International|Third International]] or Comintern.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=20-21}} In addition, the CPNZ also maintained close ties with the [[Communist Party of Australia]] (CPA) and supported [[M\u0101ori people|Maori right]]s and the [[Mau movement]] in [[Samoa|Western Samoa]].{{sfn|Bennett|2004|pp=75-77}}{{sfn|Taloy|2002|pp=103-115}}\n\nDuring the 1920s, the CPNZ and the Communist front organisation NZ-USSR Society attempted to influence the New Zealand trade union movement, workers, intellectuals and the New Zealand Labour Party to promote support for the Soviet Union and socialist policies. These attempts were largely unsuccessful and the Labour Party adopted a policy excluding all members of the CPNZ and Communist front organisations. This set the stage for enmity and rivalry between communists and [[social democracy|social democratic]] parties over control of the trade unions and unemployed workers' movements during the [[Great Depression]]. Both communists and social democrats however did work together during the 1930s to combat [[fascism]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=20-21}}\n\n===Communist offshoots===\n[[File:Vic Wilcox.jpg|left|175px|thumb|[[Vic Wilcox]], pro-[[Maoism|Maoist]] leader of the Communist Party.]]\n[[File:Ken Douglas (cropped).jpg|left|175px|thumb|[[Ken Douglas]], leader of the rival Socialist Unity Party.]]\nWhen the [[Sino-Soviet split]] occurred in the 1960s, the CPNZ was sharply divided between supporters of the Soviet Union (led by the \"revisionist\" [[Nikita Khrushchev]]) and supporters of China (led by the radical [[Mao Zedong]]). Eventually, the [[Maoists]]  led by [[Vic Wilcox]] triumphed, and supporters of Khrushchev were expelled. Under Wilcox's leadership, the CPNZ was the only Western Communist party to side with China against the Soviets. The CPNZ's official mouthpiece was the ''People's Voice''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}\n\nThe expelled members led by [[Ken Douglas]] and [[Bill Andersen|George Harold (Bill) Andersen]] eventually established the [[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]] (SUP). The SUP supported the CPSU and Soviet Union until the collapse of the USSR in 1991, defending the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]] in 1968, the suppression of the [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|1982 Solidarity demonstrations]] in Poland, and the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]. In return, Moscow funded frequent trips by SUP members to Russia, and Soviet ideologues and advisers regularly visited their SUP counterparts in New Zealand. The SUP's newspaper was called ''NZ Tribune''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}} The Socialist Unity party eventually suffered its own split, with some members departing to found the modern [[Socialist Party of Aotearoa]].<ref>Pacey, quoted in Locke, C. (2012, p. 239). ''Workers in the Margins: Union Radicals in Post-war New Zealand.'' Wellington: Bridget Williams Books.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pickmere |first1=Arnold |title=Obituary: Bill Andersen |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10007504 |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=[[New Zealand Herald]] |date=21 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, a group called the Socialist Action League (now the [[Communist League (New Zealand)|Communist League]]) was established. The League emerged from student protests against the [[Vietnam War]] and was influenced by the theories of [[Leon Trotsky]], [[Fidel Castro]], and [[Che Guevera]]. The League took an interest in Communist movements in [[Cuba]], [[Nicaragua]], and the [[Philippines]]. Its newspaper was called ''Socialist Action''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}  The League has proven to be one of the more durable parties and contested the [[2017 Mount Albert by-election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Mt Albert by-election - Official Result |url=https://www.electionresults.govt.nz/2017_mt_albert_byelection/ |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Communist League candidate in Mt Albert by-election |url=http://business.scoop.co.nz/2017/02/14/communist-league-candidate-in-mt-albert-by-election/ |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |publisher=Communist League |date=14 February 2017}}</ref> [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green]] Member of Parliament [[Keith Locke]] was once involved in the Socialist Action League.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=123}}\n\nAfter Mao's death, the CPNZ under the leadership if Richard Wolf and Harold Crook rejected the reforms introduced by [[Deng Xiaoping]]. Instead, they followed [[Albania]], which was led by [[Enver Hoxha]]'s [[Party of Labour of Albania]]. The leadership of the party believed that Hoxha was the only communist leader to keep \"real\" communism, but the group's determination to follow the narrowest path available alienated many of its supporters. The party gradually declined. Those CPNZ members who remained loyal to Beijing formed the [[Workers' Communist League (New Zealand)|Workers' Communist League]], whose newspaper was called ''Unity''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}\n\nDuring the [[Cold War]], the CPNZ, SUP, Workers Commnist League and the Socialist Action League tried to influence the Labour Party, trade unions, and a range of popular issues like the [[1981 South Africa rugby union tour of New Zealand|anti-Springbok tour protests]], the [[M\u0101ori protest movement|M\u0101ori biculturalism]], and the [[New Zealand's nuclear-free zone|anti-nuclear movement]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=29-30}} During the [[ANZUS]] diplomatic crisis 1984-85 which resulted from NZ's nuclear ship ban, the SUP tried to infiltrate anti-nuclear organisations as part of a strategy of steering New Zealand's foreign policy away from its traditional ally the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loudon |first1=Trevor |last2=Moran |first2=Bernard |date=March 22, 2007 |title=The untold story behind New Zealand's ANZUS breakdown |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+untold+story+behind+New+Zealand's+ANZUS+breakdown.-a0173717046 |url-status=dead|publisher=[[National Observer (Australia)|National Observer]] |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204091431/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+untold+story+behind+New+Zealand's+ANZUS+breakdown.-a0173717046|archivedate=2013-02-04|accessdate=26 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the collapse of Albanian communism, the CPNZ adopted the [[Trotskyism]] it had once harshly condemned, and merged with a newer group known as the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]]. The resultant party was called the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]].{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=63}} Later, however, many supporters of the International Socialist Organization withdrew from the new party, reestablishing their old group. As such, some see the Socialist Workers Organization (SWO) as a continuation of the old Communist Party. The SWO, known then as Socialist Worker, voted to dissolve itself in January 2012.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nOther groups continue to promote socialism as well. In the [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002 election]], four candidates were put forward an umbrella group (known as the [[Anti-Capitalist Alliance (New Zealand)|Anti-Capitalist Alliance]]) consisting of the [[Workers Party of New Zealand]], the [[Revolution (New Zealand political party)|Revolution]] group, and other left-wing activists. The International Socialist Organization is also active at some universities.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===New Left variations===\n[[File:Sue Bradford.jpg|right|thumb|Former Green Member of Parliament [[Sue Bradford]], was also involved in the Auckland PYM and the Auckland Resistance bookshop during her youth.]]\nThe [[New Left]] in New Zealand emerged during the 1950s and 1960s in response to the perceived \"authoritarian, bureaucratic, and repressive norms\" of New Zealand society and the so-called conservatism of the Communist Party, Labour, and [[New Zealand National Party|National]] parties. Eschewing the hierarchical structures of the \"[[Old Left]]\" political parties, the New Left developed informal groups that were non-sectarian, anti-bureaucratic, and decentralised. While the \"Old Left\" viewed the working class as the agent of revolutionary change, the New Left also saw revolutionary potential in [[Third World]] peasants, students, ethnic minorities and other marginalised groups. As with their New Left counterparts in Europe and North America, the New Left in New Zealand was largely young, white, male, middle-class, student-dominated, and incorporated a wide range of beliefs including [[radical liberalism]]{{disambiguation needed|date=November 2019}}, the [[counter-culture]] movement, [[Christian pacifism]], [[anarchism]], neo-[[Leninism]], and libertarian forms of [[Marxism]]. According to Boraman, the New Zealand New Left combined both the socialist orientation of the European New Left and the liberal orientation of its American counterpart.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=118-119}}\n\nNew Left groups championed several causes included opposition to [[racism]], the [[nuclear arms race]], and the [[Vietnam War]]. Key New Left organisations in New Zealand were the anti-[[Apartheid]] [[Halt All Racist Tours]] (HART), the Progressive Youth Movement (PYM), Socialist Forum, and the Resistance bookshops; which were organised locally. Unlike the Australian and American New Left groups, the Socialist Forum, PYM groups, and the Resistance bookshops were not university-based organisations but largely drew their support from working-class youth. The Wellington PYM consisted of a mixture of working-class youth and university students. Like the American New Left, the various PYM groups opposed the Vietnam War, racism, and Apartheid. While the New Zealand [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament (NZ)|Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]] (CND) was not a New Left organisation, several New Leftists including Graham Butterworth, Jim Delahunty, and Helmut Eionhorn of Wellington Socialist Forum also participated in the CND.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=120-122}}\n\nDuring the 1960s and 1970s, the New Left reached its heyday. HART, the PYM, and Resistance bookshops were joined by other groups including the [[University of Auckland|Auckland University]] Society for the Active Prevention of Cruelty to Politically Apathetic Humans (AUSAPOCHPAH), the Auckland-based Friends of Brutus, the New Left Club at [[Massey University]], the [[Victoria University of Wellington|Victoria University]] Socialist Club, the Anarchist Congress in Wellington, the Radical Student's Alliance at the [[University of Canterbury]], the [[Christchurch]]-based Anarchist Commune, the [[University of Otago]]'s Progressive Left Club, and the [[Dunedin]] Anarchist Army.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=123}} The activist, scholar, and [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green Party]] Member of Parliament [[Sue Bradford]] was involved in the Auckland PYM and the Auckland Resistance bookshop.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=125}}{{sfn|Hope and Scott|205|p=552}}\n\nFollowing the election of the [[Third Labour Government of New Zealand|Third Labour Government]] in 1972, the new government delivered many of the New Left's demands including withdrawing New Zealand troops from Vietnam in 1972; ending [[Compulsory military training in New Zealand|compulsory military training]] that same year; and terminating sporting contact with South Africa. As a result, the New Left lost much of its prominence due to the winding down of the protest movement. While New Leftists were still active in radical politics such as the Resistance bookshops, the more liberal wing of the protest movement had largely been appeased by the Third Labour Government's policies.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=129}}\n\nDuring the early to mid 1970s, some New Left elements like the Christchurch PYM became influenced by the [[Maoism|Maoist]] Communist Party. One New Left group that emerged in 1974 was Murray Horton and [[Owen Wilkes]]' [[Campaign Against Foreign Control of Aotearoa]], which campaigned against foreign military bases and economic activity in New Zealand. According to Boraman, several New Leftists including former PYM members were also instrumental in founding several \"new social movements\" during the 1960s and 1970s including [[Tama Poata]]'s M\u0101ori Organisation on Human Rights (MOOHR), the [[Black Panthers]]&ndash;inspired [[Polynesian Panthers]], Therese O'Connell's Wellington Women's Liberation Front, the Auckland Women's Liberation Front, and the Auckland&ndash;based Women for Equality. Boraman has characterized opposition to [[American imperialism]] and uncritical praise for Communist states and figures like [[Mao Zedong]], [[Ho Chi Minh]], and [[Che Guevara]] as two key defining features of the later New Left activists and groups.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n\n===Left-wing alternative media===\n[[File:Trotter, Chris (Alliance).jpg|left|175px|thumb|Chris Trotter, editor of the ''New Zealand Political Review''.]]\nDuring the early 20th century, the emergence of working-class consciousness led to the formation of several left-wing newspapers including ''The Maoriland  Worker'' (1910&ndash;1924), ''The Weekly Herald'', ''The Transport Worker'', and ''The New Zealand Watersider''. During the 1930s, they were joined by activist theatre companies, politically-engaged literary magazines, the Left Book Club, the Co-Operative Book Movement, and the Progressive Publishing Company. During the Great Depression, liberal-left perspectives penetrated mainstream New Zealand society through churches, women's groups, populist radio programmes, and the Labour Party.{{sfn|Hope and Scott|2015|p=546}}{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=41}}\n\nThe ''Maoriland Worker'' later revamped itself as the ''New Zealand Worker'' (1924&ndash;1935) and as the Labour Party's affiliated newspaper ''The Standard'' (1935&ndash;1959). While it was sympathetic to the Labour Party, the ''Maoriland Worker'' was a largely radical socialist publication that was independent of the Labour Party.{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=41}}  The various Communist parties also published their own newspapers. The CPNZ's official organ was the ''People's Voice'' (1939&ndash;1991), which reached a peak of 14,000 copies in 1945. The Socialist Unity Party's newspapers were the ''Tribune'' (1966&ndash;1995), ''Socialist Worker'' (1994&ndash;2005), ''The Spark'' (1991&ndash;2013), and ''Socialist Review'' (1997&ndash;present), and ''The Spark''{{'s}} successor ''Fightback'' (2013&ndash;present). The Socialist Action League's newspaper was ''Socialist Action'' (1969&ndash;1998), which reached a peak of 8,400 copies during the [[New Zealand general election, 1978|1978 general election]]. The Workers' Communist League's newspaper was called ''Unity'' (1978&ndash;1990).{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=37, 45}}\n\nSeveral notable independent socialist magazines and newspapers in New Zealand have included the ''New Zealand Monthly Review'' (''NZMR'', 1960&ndash;1996), ''The Republican'' (1974&ndash;1996), ''Race Gender Class'' (1985&ndash;1992), left-wing journalist [[Chris Trotter]]'s social democratic ''New Zealand Political Review'' (''NZPR'', 1992&ndash;2005),{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=64-65}} the feminist ''Broadsheet'' (1972&ndash;1997), the Peace Movement Aotearoa's ''Peacelink'', the queer feminist ''Bitches, Witches and Dykes'', the anti-apartheid ''HART News'', ''CARP Newsletter'', ''Foreign Control Watchdog'', and ''Peace Researcher''. Other independent left-wing publications have included the Marxist Publishing Group's ''Red Papers'' (1976&ndash;1979) ,''The Paper'' (1973&ndash;1975), and the Victoria University Socialist Club's ''Red Spark'' (1969&ndash;1970).{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=36-37, 44-45}}\n\n==Contemporary socialist parties, groups, and media in New Zealand==\nThere are around twenty political parties or organizations in New Zealand which follow socialist or communist policies. It is often difficult to gain a clear picture of socialist parties in New Zealand - mergers, splits, and re-namings leave the situation confused. In 2019 only Organise Aotearoa, the International Socialist Organisation, Socialist Aotearoa, the Canterbury Socialist Society, and the New Communist Party of Aotearoa hold regular public meetings and maintain regularly updated websites.\n\n===Modern parties and organizations===\n* '''[[Communist League (New Zealand)|Communist League]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established in 1969 as the \"Socialist Action League\". It has links to the [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|Socialist Workers Party]] of the USA. The Communist League had two candidates in the [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002 election]], but neither won their respective races. The League also stood candidates in the 2010 Auckland council election.\n*'''[[Communist Workers' Group (New Zealand)|Communist Workers' Group]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group. It was established in 1995 as a splinter group from the [[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]] organization. It is associated with the global [[Liaison Committee of Militants for a Revolutionary Communist International]] alliance, which itself was a split from the global alliance that Workers' Power belonged to. Their website is redrave.blogspot.co.nz.\n* Fightback - formerly the Workers Party, which was previously the Anti-Capitalist Alliance. Branches in Wellington and Auckland and a monthly publication. Some members have worked as organisers for Unite Union. Fightback publishes a monthly magazine by the same name.\n*'''[[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]]''' - a revolutionary [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group that is particularly active in universities. It briefly attempted to merge with the remnants of the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]], forming the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]. However, the majority of the group eventually rejected this decision and reestablished their own party but were now outside of the [[International Socialist Tendency]]. The ISO has fraternal relations with Socialist Alternative, in Australia, and the International Socialist Organisation, USA. Branches in Auckland, Wellington and Dunedin. Bi-monthly magazine called Socialist Review. \n*'''[[Organise Aotearoa]]''' \u2013 a revolutionary socialist group formed in 2016 and widely publicised in October 2018. Shortly after its public announcement, the organisation engaged in a series of [[direct action]] campaigns, including joining the blockade of New Zealand Defence Industry Association forums,<ref name=\"Organise Aotearoa\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1810/S00422/organise-aotearoa-to-join-opposition-to-the-weapons-expo.htm |title=Organise Aotearoa to join opposition to the Weapons Expo |date=2018-10-31 |publisher=Scoop News |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> occupying the [[Brazil]]ian embassy after the inauguration of [[Jair Bolsonaro]],<ref name=\"Protest of Brazilian embassy\">{{Cite web |url=https://thedailyblog.co.nz/2019/01/07/protest-of-brazilian-embassy-in-new-zealand-goes-viral-in-brazil-organise-aotearoa/ |title=Protest of Brazilian embassy in New Zealand goes viral in Brazil |date=2019-01-07 |publisher=The Daily BLog |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> occupying the [[United States]] consulate in Auckland during the [[2019 Venezuelan uprising|2019 Venezuelan coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], and joining the occupation of [[\u014ctuataua and Ihum\u0101tao|Ihum\u0101tao]]. The group has also organised broader mobilisations such as the 2018 protests agitating for [[Abortion in New Zealand|abortion reform]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://95bfm.com/bcast/i-v-w-organise-aotearoa-december-5-2018 |title=Interview with Organise Aotearoa |date=2018-12-05 |publisher=95.bFM |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> As of June 2019, the organisation claims a membership of 272 active members. Branches in Auckland, Hamilton, Wellington, and Dunedin.\n*'''[[Permanent Revolution Group (New Zealand)|Permanent Revolution Group]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established as a breakaway from the [[Spartacist League (New Zealand)|Spartacist League]] (which later became the [[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]] organization). It is associated with the International Bolshevik Tendency.\n*'''[[Socialist Aotearoa]]''' - an [[Auckland]]-based group formed in May 2008 which split from [[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]] over disagreement with the organization's participation in the [[Residents Action Movement]] electoral coalition. The group has an eclectic mix of Trotskyists, anarchists, ecosocialists and various other ideologies in its ranks. Members are active in Unite Union, with one member, Joe Carolan, a senior organiser in that union.\n* '''[[Socialist Voice (New Zealand)|Socialist Voice]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established in 2002. It is associated with the [[Committee for a Workers' International (1974)|Committee for a Workers' International]], and is therefore linked to the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party of England and Wales]].\n*'''[[Socialist Party of Aotearoa]]''' - a Marxist-Leninist group. It was founded in 1990 as a split from the [[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]], which was itself a split from the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]].\n\n===Defunct parties and organizations===\n\n*'''[[New Zealand Socialist Party]]''' (1901-1913) - an organization established in 1901. It should not be confused with the Socialist Party of New Zealand, a completely separate organization which is now known as the [[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]].\n* '''[[Communist Party of New Zealand]]''' (1921-1994) - an old communist group that initially gained a modest measure of success, but which later declined. The party became attached to [[Stalinism]], and when the [[Sino-Soviet split]] occurred, the party adopted [[Maoism]]. Later, after [[Mao Zedong|Mao]]'s death, it followed [[Enver Hoxha]], leader of [[Albania]] (which they considered to be the last bastion of true communism). After the fall of Albania, the party renounced all these ideologies and adopted [[Trotskyism]]. The party then attempted a merger with the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]], creating the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]. Most of the International Socialists eventually withdrew from this coalition, leaving the new Socialist Workers Organization dominated by the former Communist Party.\n* '''[[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]]''' (1930-??) - a group based primarily around opposition to [[Leninism]]. It was originally established in 1930 simply as the \"Socialist Party of New Zealand\", but later added \"world\" to its name. It is affiliated with the [[World Socialist Movement]].\n*'''[[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]]''' (1966-1990) - a pro-Soviet party established by expelled members of the Communist Party. The Communist Party had been split between supporters of the Soviet Union and supporters of [[Mao Zedong]]'s China, and the pro-Soviet faction eventually lost. The Socialist Unity party survived until relatively recently, and maintained a relatively high level of influence in the trade union movement.\n* '''[[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]]''' (?-2012). A revolutionary socialist group aligned with the International Socialist Tendency. Formerly known as the Socialist Workers Organisation, the final conference of SW voted to dissolve itself at its conference in January 2012.\n* '''[[Workers Party of New Zealand]]''' (2002-2013) - The party was founded in 2002. It was originally formed by an electoral alliance of the original Workers' Party (pro-Mao, Marxist-Leninist) and the pro-Trotsky Revolution group. it is the first, and so far only, registered [[hard left]] political party under [[Mixed-member proportional representation|mixed-member proportional]] (MMP) representation.\n* Black Cat '''[[Anarchism in New Zealand#cite note-2|BlackCat Anarchist Collective]]''' - an [[anarcho-communism|anarcho-communist]] group based in the city of [[Auckland]].\n* '''[[Communist Party of Aotearoa]]''' - a [[Maoism|Maoist]] group that split from the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] in 1993, condemning that organization's abandonment of Maoism and adoption of [[Trotskyism]].\n* '''Revolutionary Communist League of New Zealand''' founded in 1984 by students and lecturers at the University of Canterbury in Christchurch. It was a revolutionary Marxist group affiliated with the [[United Secretariat of the Fourth International]]. After a few conferences, intending to rally opposition to [[Rogernomics]], RCLNZ organized a larger nationwide grouping called '''Socialist Alliance''' which stood a candidate in the 1987 general election. The RCLNZ was transformed into the '''Socialist Workers' Project''' in 1990, based in the ChCh Centre for Socialist Education.\n*'''[[New Zealand Marxian Association]]''' - a group established in 1918. It was founded to give endorsement and support to \"Marxian Revolutionist\" candidates in general elections.{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n* '''[[Organisation for Marxist Unity - New Zealand|Organisation for Marxist Unity]]''' - a [[Maoism|Maoist]] group.\n* '''[[Revolutionary Workers League (New Zealand)|Revolutionary Workers League]]''' - a merger of the pro-[[Mao Zedong|Mao]], [[Marxist-Leninist]] [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Workers' Party of New Zealand]] and the [[Revolution (NZ political group)|Revolution]] group. A tendency within the modern [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Workers' Party of New Zealand]].\n*'''[[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]''' - a revolutionary [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] party. It was established by the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] and the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]], although the majority of the latter group eventually withdrew from the merger. It was linked to the [[International Socialist Tendency]]. It evolved into the present day [[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]] group.\n*'''[[Workers' Party of New Zealand (pro-Mao, Marxist-Leninist)]]''' - A pro-[[Mao Zedong|Mao]], [[Marxist-Leninist]] party founded by Ray Nunes, formerly a prominent member of the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]]. The party joined the [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Anti-Capitalist Alliance]] (ACA), a radical-left electoral alliance, in 2002. The Workers' Party merged with [[Revolution (NZ political group)|Revolution]] to become the [[Revolutionary Workers League (New Zealand)|Revolutionary Workers' League]] in 2004.\n* '''[[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group formed in 1981 with links to the global Workers' Power entity. It later absorbed a group called the \"[[Communist Left (New Zealand)|Communist Left]]\". It is linked to the [[League for a Fifth International]].\n\n===Contemporary left-wing media===\nWith the advent of the Internet during the 1990s and early 21st century, left-wing print media gave way to online alternative media, which were cheaper to produce. Notable left-wing New Zealand blogs have included the independent Marxist collective \"Redline\", \"Against the Current\", [[Martyn \"Bomber\" Bradbury]]'s current affairs&ndash;oriented ''The Daily Blog'' (2012&ndash;present), and ''The Standard''. Besides blogs, left wing alternative media have also utilised email newsletters, publishing software, and major social media platforms like [[YouTube]], [[Facebook]], and [[Twitter]].{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=67}}{{sfn|Hope and Scott|20175pp=551-553}}<ref>{{cite web |title=About |url=https://thestandard.org.nz/about/ |website=The Standard |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent figures in New Zealand socialism==\n*[[Martyn \"Bomber\" Bradbury]]{{sfn|Hope and Scott|20175pp=551-553}}\n*[[Sue Bradford]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=125}}\n*[[Peter Fraser]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Harry Holland]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Edward Hunter (Billy Banjo)|Edward Hunter]] (aka \"Billy Banjo\"){{sfn|Len Richardson|2002|pp=73-86}}\n*[[John A. Lee]]{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=106-114}}\n*[[Tama Poata]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n*[[Michael Joseph Savage]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Bob Semple]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Chris Trotter]]{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=64-65}}\n*[[Owen Wilkes]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n\n==Prominent figures in New Zealand communism==\n*[[Bill Andersen|George Harold (Bill) Andersen]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n*[[Ken Douglas]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n*[[Vic Wilcox]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Boraman |first=Tom |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=[[University of Otago]] Press|date=2002 |pages=117\u2013132 |chapter=Chapter 7: The New Left in New Zealand |isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Boraman |first1=Toby |title=The Independent Left Press and the Rise and Fall of Mass Dissent in Aotearoa since the 1970s |journal=Counterfutures |date=2016 |issue=1 |pages=31\u201370 |url=https://counterfutures.nz/1/boraman.pdf |accessdate=18 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Franks |first1=Peter |last2=McAloon |first2=Jim |title=Labour: The New Zealand Labour Party, 1916-2016 |date=2016 |publisher=[[Victoria University of Wellington|Victoria University]] Press |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]] |isbn=9781776560745 |url=https://vup.victoria.ac.nz/labour-the-new-zealand-labour-party-1916-2016/ |accessdate=16 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Gustafson|first=Barry |editor-last1=Trapeznik |editor-first1=Alexander |editor-last2=Fox |editor-first2=Aaron |title=Lenin's Legacy Down Under: New Zealand's Cold War |publisher=University of Otago Press |date=2004|pages=17\u201333 |chapter=Chapter 2: New Zealand in the Cold War World |isbn=1-877276-90-1}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hope |first1=Wayne |last2=Scott |first2=Jane |editor-last=Hayward |editor-first=Janine |title=New Zealand Government and Politics, Sixth Edition |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=28 May 2015 |pages=545\u2013555 |chapter=Chapter 8.5: Left political activism|isbn=9780195585254 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/new-zealand-government-and-politics-9780195585254?cc=nz&lang=en& |accessdate=25 September 2019}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Milburn |first1=Josephine F. |title=Socialism and Social Reform in Nineteenth-Century New Zealand |journal=Political Science |date=1960 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=62\u201370}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Newell |first1=Peter E. |url=http://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2000s/2004/no-1203-november-2004/marxian-socialism-new-zealand|title=Marxian Socialism in New Zealand|newspaper=[[Socialist Standard]]|date=November 2004|accessdate=26 March 2018}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Olssen |first1=Erik |title=W.T. Mills, E.J.B. Allen, J.A. Lee, and Socialism in New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1976 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013119 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=1408&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Len |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=University of Otago Press |date=2002|pages=73\u201386 |chapter=Chapter 4: 'Billy Banjo: Coalminer, Socialist, Poet and Novelist |isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Kerry |title='Our Motto, No Compromise': The Ideological Origins and Foundation of the Communist Party of New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1994 |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=160\u2013177 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=712&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Taylor|first=Kerry |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=University of Otago Press|date=2002 |pages=103\u2013115 |chapter=Chapter 6: 'Potential Allies of the Working Class': The Communist Party of New Zealand and Maori, 1921-1952|isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.broadleft.org/nz.htm Leftist Parties of New Zealand] - contains links and statistics for left-wing (not necessarily socialist/communist) parties in New Zealand. Includes links to most parties mentioned above.\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Socialist states}}\n{{Oceania in topic|Socialism in}}\n\n[[Category:Socialism in New Zealand| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Socialism sidebar |History by country}} \n{{Politics of New Zealand|expanded=Ideology}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2019}}\nThe extent to which [[socialism]] plays a part in modern [[Politics of New Zealand|New Zealand politics]] depends on which definitions of socialist are used, but few mainstream politicians would describe themselves using the word \"socialist\". The term \"[[social democracy|social-democrat]]\" is more common, but the more general \"[[left-wing politics|left-wing]]\" or \"[[centre-left politics|centre-left]]\" are used far more frequently. New Zealand has a complicated assortment of socialist causes and organisations. Some of these play a considerable role in public [[activism]]\u2014some commentators claim that New Zealand socialists are more prominent in causes such as the [[anti-war movement]] than in promoting socialism itself.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Other groups are strongly committed to radical socialist revolution.\n\nSeveral prominent [[List of political parties in New Zealand|political parties in New Zealand]], such as the [[New Zealand Labour Party]], have historical links to socialism but are not generally considered socialist today due to their acceptance of a [[market economy]]. More likely to receive this label are the small [[Marxism|Marxist]] organisations that exist outside the mainstream political world, such as [[Organise Aotearoa]], the [[International Socialist Organisation (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organisation]] and [[Socialist Aotearoa]].{{sfn|Wayne and Hope|2015|pp=548-551}}\n\n==History of New Zealand socialism==\nAcademic [[Josephine F. Milburn]] argues that socialist theories were introduced by immigrant workers with experience in the British labour movement. Their ideas were not widely accepted, however. The Liberal government that was dominant 1891-1912 rejected socialism but it supported unions and the [[Liberal Government of New Zealand]] set up the country's welfare state in the 1890s and fought the large land holders. She argues that governmental activism cannot be attributed to the influence of the small socialist movement.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Milburn |first1=Josephine |title=Socialism and Social Reform in Nineteenth-Century New Zealand |journal=Political Science |date=1960 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=62\u201370}}</ref>\n\n===Non-ideological socialism===\n{{Weasel|date=March 2009}}\nThe growth of socialism as an ideology in New Zealand only began to occur around the beginning of the 20th century. Some historians, however, claim that a sort of \"non-ideological\" socialism was born shortly after the establishment of self-government, and flourished in the late 19th century. This, they say, was mostly in the form of a \"[[paternalism|paternalistic]]\" government which believed in the need to speed the country's economic growth, rather than in the form of an ideologically leftist government. These historians argue that because of New Zealand's small size and its focus on agriculture, the newly established government was forced to assume responsibility for many things that would otherwise be undertaken by private enterprise - railways, banking, insurance, and many other things that New Zealand's small business sector could not yet afford. Premier [[Julius Vogel]] was a notable advocate of government projects of this nature. Later, the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] was accused by its opponents of being \"socialist\", although most within the party rejected this. One commentator has claimed that until the [[Russian Revolution of 1917]], New Zealand was the most socialist country in the world, although many believe that this is overstating the case.\n\n===Unions and workers' parties===\n[[File:Harry Holland (1925).jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Harry Holland]], a socialist who was a founder and leader of the modern [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]]]]\nIdeological socialism, when it arrived, mostly stemmed from Britain or other British colonies. Much of socialism's early growth was found in the labour movement, and often coincided with the growth of [[labor union|trade unions]]. During the 1870s, James McPherson and his Canterbury Working Men's Mutual Protection Society had written to [[Karl Marx]], requesting affiliation with the [[International Workingmen's Association|First International]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}} The [[New Zealand Federation of Labor]] (also known as the \"Red Federation\") was influenced by socialist theories, as were many other labour organizations. The Red Federation was formed in 1909 when a federation of the mining unions invited other unions to join a New Zealand Federation of Labour. The Red Federation's official organ was the ''[[Maoriland Worker]]'', which advocated militant unionism and socialism. Key Red Federation leaders included the [[Australia]]n&ndash;born Hickey and [[Paddy Webb]], and fellow Australian [[Bob Semple]]. In opposition to the Red Federation, mainstream trade and labour councils formed a rival [[New Zealand Federation of Labour (1909)|Federation of Labour]].{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=55-56}}\n\nThe arrival of 200 British socialists called the \"Clarion Settlers\" led to the formation of the [[New Zealand Socialist Party]] in 1901, which promoted the works of Marx and [[Friedrich Engels]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}} Strongly influenced by the British [[Independent Labour Party]], the Socialist Party advocated promoting socialism through education and agitation rather than elections. The group met with little tangible success, but it nevertheless had considerable impact on the development of New Zealand socialism, forging close ties with the \"Red Federation.\"{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=48-49, 55-56}} In particular, [[Edward Hunter (Billy Banjo)|Edward Hunter]] (sometimes known under the pen name \"[[Billy Banjo]]\", and a member of both the Socialist Party and the Red Federation), was a major figure in the spread of socialist ideas to the unions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Richadrson |first1=Lee |title=Hunter, Edward |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/3h45/hunter-edward |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1996}}</ref>{{sfn|Len Richardson|2002|pp=73-86}}\n\nIn the years leading up to the [[First World War]], several New Zealand and Australian socialists including [[Harry Holland]], [[Michael Joseph Savage]], [[Peter Fraser]], [[Harry Scott Bennett]], [[Tom Barker (trade unionist)|Tom Barker]], [[Tom Bloodworth]], and [[Bob Semple]] advocated the creation of a \"Cooperative Commonwealth\" in which all land and means of wealth production, distribution, and management would be owned and managed collectively by the people. Besides Marx and Engels, these antipodean socialists were influenced by various radical European and American writers including [[Henry George]], [[Edward Bellamy]], [[Georges Sorel]], [[August Bebel]], [[Eugene Debs]], [[Bill Haywood]], and [[Irving Fisher]]. In 1912, a Petone Marxian Club was formed and met every Monday. This was one of the forerunners to the [[New Zealand Marxian Association]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n\nThe growth of unionism eventually led to the establishment of a number of socialist-influenced parties. Originally, the working class vote was concentrated mainly with the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]], where a number of prominent left-wing politicians (such as [[Frederick Pirani]]) emerged. Later, however, there were increasing calls for an independent workers' party, particularly as the Liberals began to lose their reformist drive.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=47-49}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steven |first1=Oliver |title=Pirani, Frederick |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2p19/pirani-frederick |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe second organised party to gain a seat in Parliament (after the Liberal Party) was the small [[Independent Political Labour League]], which won an urban electorate in [[Wellington]] in the [[1908 New Zealand general election|1908 election]]. Later, in 1910, the IPLL was reformed as the [[New Zealand Labour Party (original)|Labour Party]] (not to be confused with the modern party).{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=51-57}}\n\n===Emergence of the Labour Party===\n[[File:Michael Joseph Savage Portrait.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Michael Joseph Savage]] was the first Labour [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]].]]\n{{Formation of New Zealand Labour Party}}\nThe growing drive for unity among left-wing groups resulted in a \"Unity Conference\" being called in 1912. This conference aimed to merge the various left-wing parties in New Zealand, including both the moderate Labour Party and the hardline Socialist Party. The Socialist Party, however, refused to attend the conference, and the new [[United Labour Party (New Zealand)|United Labour Party]] consisted only of the Labour Party and a number of independent campaigners.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=62-64}}\n\nPremier [[William Massey]]'s \"heavy-handed\" suppression of the [[Waihi miners' strike]] prompted another attempt at unity in 1913. This time, the Socialists were willing to attend. A new group, the [[Social Democratic Party (New Zealand)|Social Democratic Party]], was formed, merging the United Labour Party and the Socialist Party. A faction of the United Labour Party refused to accept the decision, however, and continued on under the same name. Later, a decision by the Social Democrats to support a strike of dockworkers and coal miners resulted in a number of Social Democratic leaders being arrested, leaving the party in disarray in the [[1914 New Zealand general election|1914 election]], the remnants of the United Labour Party actually won more seats than the \"united\" Social Democrats.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=61-68}}\n\nFinally, in 1916, it was agreed that the Social Democrats and the United Labour Party remnants would all be amalgamated into a single group, the [[New Zealand Labour Party]]. The new Labour Party was explicitly socialist, and was based around goals of redistribution of wealth, nationalization of industry, and elimination of conscription.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=69-71}}<ref name=\"Te Ara Origins\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 1. Origins of the Labour Party |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-1 |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref> Eventual Labour Party leader, [[Harry Holland]], was strongly socialist in his beliefs, having been associated with the Socialist Party and with the striking miners in Waihi. Holland believed that the militancy at Waihi was a sign of further impending class conflict. While the Labour Party gained some electoral success, it continued to trail the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] and the [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform Party]] until the replacement of Holland with [[Michael Joseph Savage]]. Savage, although also involved in the earlier Socialist Party, was more moderate than Holland, and Labour gained considerable support. Assisted by the [[Great Depression]], Labour won a decisive victory in the [[1935 New Zealand general election|1935 election]].{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=78-81, 87-95}}<ref name=\"First Labour government\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 2. First Labour government, 1935 to 1949 |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-2 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Labour's social democracy===\n[[File:John Alexander Lee.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[John A. Lee]] was a prominent socialist figure in the Labour Party from the 1920s until his expulsion in 1940]]\nDespite its socialist roots, the Labour Party shifted towards a more [[social democracy|social democratic]] orientation once in power. The [[First Labour Government of New Zealand|First Labour Government]] led by Savage and Peter Fraser implemented a range of socialist policies such as nationalising industry, broadcasting, transportation, and a [[Keynesianism|Keynesian]] welfare state. However, the party did not seek to abolish capitalism, instead opting for a [[mixed economy]]. Labour's welfare state and mixed economy were not challenged until the 1980s.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=87-105}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 2. First Labour government, 1935 to 1949 |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-2 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTwo years after the Labour Party lost the [[1949 New Zealand general election|1949 election]], the goal of implementing \"the socialisation of the means of production, distribution, and exchange\" was removed from the party's policy platform. This is sometimes seen as the end of any real claim to full socialism by the Labour Party. However, the shift away from socialism had not come about without dispute. Labour Party politician [[John A. Lee]] was harshly critical of the changes, and had eventually left to establish the [[Democratic Labour Party (New Zealand)|Democratic Labour Party]] in 1940. The party was considerably more socialist than Labour, but performed poorly. Many members eventually left the party, mostly due to Lee's perceived autocratic style.{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=106-114}}<ref name=\"Ideology and unions\">{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 5. Ideology and the role of unions |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-5 |website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fourth Labour Government]] under Prime Minister [[David Lange]] and [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Finance Minister]] [[Roger Douglas]] implemented several [[neoliberalism|neoliberal]] economic reforms known as [[Rogernomics]] which transitioned New Zealand's Keynesian economy towards a more free market model. Labour's abandonment of its traditional values fractured the party, leading disaffected members to join [[Jim Anderton]]'s [[NewLabour Party (New Zealand)|NewLabour Party]], [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Greens]], [[New Zealand Democratic Party for Social Credit]], and the [[Mana Motuhake]] parties under the [[Alliance (New Zealand political party)|Alliance]]. Successive Labour governments have promoted centre-left social and economic policies while preserving a free market economy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aimer |first1=Peter |title=Page 4. Fourth, fifth and sixth Labour governments |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/labour-party/page-4 |website=Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |date=1 June 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Hope and Scott|2015|p=547}} The current Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] identifies as a social democrat and formerly served as President of the [[International Union of Socialist Youth]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Tim|title=What Jacinda Ardern wants|url=https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2017/07/31/40717/what-jacinda-wants|accessdate=15 August 2017|work=Newsroom|date=1 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816062218/https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2017/07/31/40717/what-jacinda-wants|archivedate=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news|last1=Kirk|first1=Stacey|title=Jacinda Ardern says she can handle it and her path to the top would suggest she's right|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/politics/95327574/Jacinda-Ardern-says-shes-can-handle-it-and-her-path-to-the-top-would-suggest-shes-right|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=15 August 2017|date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rise of the Communist Party===\n[[File:CPNZ logo.jpg|right|thumb|The Communist Party of New Zealand existed between 1921 and 1994.]]\nEven before Holland's replacement, and especially after Labour's 1949 policy change, many people had come to the conclusion that the Labour Party had moved too far away from its socialist roots. Only two years after Labour's foundation, the [[New Zealand Marxian Association]] was established. The Marxian Association was inspired by the [[Socialist Party of Great Britain]] (SPGB) and focused on political action. It would later clash acrimoniously with Holland. The Marxian Association itself would fall prey to internal division in 1921. That year, a number of members who supported the [[Russian Revolution of 1917|Russian Revolution]] departed to form the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] (CPNZ). They were joined by two other revolutionary strands within the New Zealand Socialist Party: the [[De Leonism|De Lonites]] who espoused revolutionary politics and industrial unionism; and the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW)-[[syndicalism|syndicalist]] tradition who advocated direct action and spurned political activity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Kerry |title='Our Motto, No Compromise': The Ideological Origins and Foundation of the Communist Party of New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1994 |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=160\u2013177 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=712&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>{{sfn|Bennett|2004|pp=74-75}}\n\nIn 1930, however, former members of the Marxian Association (backed by members of the [[Socialist Party of Australia (WSM)]]) established the [[Socialist Party of New Zealand]] (distinct from the earlier [[New Zealand Socialist Party]]). This group denied that the Labour Party (or even any of the parties before it, except for the Marxian Association) represented genuine socialism. The new Socialist Party still exists today, although has slightly modified its name (becoming the [[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]]).<ref name=\"Standard2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2000s/2004/no-1203-november-2004/marxian-socialism-new-zealand|title=Marxian Socialism in New Zealand|author=Peter E. Newell|newspaper=[[Socialist Standard]]|date=November 2004|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the CPNZ built its support from miners in the [[South Island]]'s [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] in the [[North Island]]'s [[Waikato]] district, and from seamen and waterside workers. The party faithfully followed the official position of the Soviet Union, modelling its aims, beliefs, manifesto and organisational structure and processes on those of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] (CPSU). The Soviets also sought to guide international Communist parties through the [[Communist International|Third International]] or Comintern.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=20-21}} In addition, the CPNZ also maintained close ties with the [[Communist Party of Australia]] (CPA) and supported [[M\u0101ori people|Maori right]]s and the [[Mau movement]] in [[Samoa|Western Samoa]].{{sfn|Bennett|2004|pp=75-77}}{{sfn|Taloy|2002|pp=103-115}}\n\nDuring the 1920s, the CPNZ and the Communist front organisation NZ-USSR Society attempted to influence the New Zealand trade union movement, workers, intellectuals and the New Zealand Labour Party to promote support for the Soviet Union and socialist policies. These attempts were largely unsuccessful and the Labour Party adopted a policy excluding all members of the CPNZ and Communist front organisations. This set the stage for enmity and rivalry between communists and [[social democracy|social democratic]] parties over control of the trade unions and unemployed workers' movements during the [[Great Depression]]. Both communists and social democrats however did work together during the 1930s to combat [[fascism]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=20-21}}\n\n===Communist offshoots===\n[[File:Vic Wilcox.jpg|left|175px|thumb|[[Vic Wilcox]], pro-[[Maoism|Maoist]] leader of the Communist Party.]]\n[[File:Ken Douglas (cropped).jpg|left|175px|thumb|[[Ken Douglas]], leader of the rival Socialist Unity Party.]]\nWhen the [[Sino-Soviet split]] occurred in the 1960s, the CPNZ was sharply divided between supporters of the Soviet Union (led by the \"revisionist\" [[Nikita Khrushchev]]) and supporters of China (led by the radical [[Mao Zedong]]). Eventually, the [[Maoists]]  led by [[Vic Wilcox]] triumphed, and supporters of Khrushchev were expelled. Under Wilcox's leadership, the CPNZ was the only Western Communist party to side with China against the Soviets. The CPNZ's official mouthpiece was the ''People's Voice''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}\n\nThe expelled members led by [[Ken Douglas]] and [[Bill Andersen|George Harold (Bill) Andersen]] eventually established the [[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]] (SUP). The SUP supported the CPSU and Soviet Union until the collapse of the USSR in 1991, defending the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]] in 1968, the suppression of the [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|1982 Solidarity demonstrations]] in Poland, and the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]. In return, Moscow funded frequent trips by SUP members to Russia, and Soviet ideologues and advisers regularly visited their SUP counterparts in New Zealand. The SUP's newspaper was called ''NZ Tribune''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}} The Socialist Unity party eventually suffered its own split, with some members departing to found the modern [[Socialist Party of Aotearoa]].<ref>Pacey, quoted in Locke, C. (2012, p. 239). ''Workers in the Margins: Union Radicals in Post-war New Zealand.'' Wellington: Bridget Williams Books.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pickmere |first1=Arnold |title=Obituary: Bill Andersen |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10007504 |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=[[New Zealand Herald]] |date=21 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, a group called the Socialist Action League (now the [[Communist League (New Zealand)|Communist League]]) was established. The League emerged from student protests against the [[Vietnam War]] and was influenced by the theories of [[Leon Trotsky]], [[Fidel Castro]], and [[Che Guevera]]. The League took an interest in Communist movements in [[Cuba]], [[Nicaragua]], and the [[Philippines]]. Its newspaper was called ''Socialist Action''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}  The League has proven to be one of the more durable parties and contested the [[2017 Mount Albert by-election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Mt Albert by-election - Official Result |url=https://www.electionresults.govt.nz/2017_mt_albert_byelection/ |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Communist League candidate in Mt Albert by-election |url=http://business.scoop.co.nz/2017/02/14/communist-league-candidate-in-mt-albert-by-election/ |accessdate=17 September 2019 |work=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |publisher=Communist League |date=14 February 2017}}</ref> [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green]] Member of Parliament [[Keith Locke]] was once involved in the Socialist Action League.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=123}}\n\nAfter Mao's death, the CPNZ under the leadership if Richard Wolf and Harold Crook rejected the reforms introduced by [[Deng Xiaoping]]. Instead, they followed [[Albania]], which was led by [[Enver Hoxha]]'s [[Party of Labour of Albania]]. The leadership of the party believed that Hoxha was the only communist leader to keep \"real\" communism, but the group's determination to follow the narrowest path available alienated many of its supporters. The party gradually declined. Those CPNZ members who remained loyal to Beijing formed the [[Workers' Communist League (New Zealand)|Workers' Communist League]], whose newspaper was called ''Unity''.{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}\n\nDuring the [[Cold War]], the CPNZ, SUP, Workers Commnist League and the Socialist Action League tried to influence the Labour Party, trade unions, and a range of popular issues like the [[1981 South Africa rugby union tour of New Zealand|anti-Springbok tour protests]], the [[M\u0101ori protest movement|M\u0101ori biculturalism]], and the [[New Zealand's nuclear-free zone|anti-nuclear movement]].{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|pp=29-30}} During the [[ANZUS]] diplomatic crisis 1984-85 which resulted from NZ's nuclear ship ban, the SUP tried to infiltrate anti-nuclear organisations as part of a strategy of steering New Zealand's foreign policy away from its traditional ally the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loudon |first1=Trevor |last2=Moran |first2=Bernard |date=March 22, 2007 |title=The untold story behind New Zealand's ANZUS breakdown |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+untold+story+behind+New+Zealand's+ANZUS+breakdown.-a0173717046 |url-status=dead|publisher=[[National Observer (Australia)|National Observer]] |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204091431/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+untold+story+behind+New+Zealand's+ANZUS+breakdown.-a0173717046|archivedate=2013-02-04|accessdate=26 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the collapse of Albanian communism, the CPNZ adopted the [[Trotskyism]] it had once harshly condemned, and merged with a newer group known as the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]]. The resultant party was called the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]].{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=63}} Later, however, many supporters of the International Socialist Organization withdrew from the new party, reestablishing their old group. As such, some see the Socialist Workers Organization (SWO) as a continuation of the old Communist Party. The SWO, known then as Socialist Worker, voted to dissolve itself in January 2012.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nOther groups continue to promote socialism as well. In the [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002 election]], four candidates were put forward an umbrella group (known as the [[Anti-Capitalist Alliance (New Zealand)|Anti-Capitalist Alliance]]) consisting of the [[Workers Party of New Zealand]], the [[Revolution (New Zealand political party)|Revolution]] group, and other left-wing activists. The International Socialist Organization is also active at some universities.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===New Left variations===\n[[File:Sue Bradford.jpg|right|thumb|Former Green Member of Parliament [[Sue Bradford]], was also involved in the Auckland PYM and the Auckland Resistance bookshop during her youth.]]\nThe [[New Left]] in New Zealand emerged during the 1950s and 1960s in response to the perceived \"authoritarian, bureaucratic, and repressive norms\" of New Zealand society and the so-called conservatism of the Communist Party, Labour, and [[New Zealand National Party|National]] parties. Eschewing the hierarchical structures of the \"[[Old Left]]\" political parties, the New Left developed informal groups that were non-sectarian, anti-bureaucratic, and decentralised. While the \"Old Left\" viewed the working class as the agent of revolutionary change, the New Left also saw revolutionary potential in [[Third World]] peasants, students, ethnic minorities and other marginalised groups. As with their New Left counterparts in Europe and North America, the New Left in New Zealand was largely young, white, male, middle-class, student-dominated, and incorporated a wide range of beliefs including [[radical liberalism]]{{disambiguation needed|date=November 2019}}, the [[counter-culture]] movement, [[Christian pacifism]], [[anarchism]], neo-[[Leninism]], and libertarian forms of [[Marxism]]. According to Boraman, the New Zealand New Left combined both the socialist orientation of the European New Left and the liberal orientation of its American counterpart.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=118-119}}\n\nNew Left groups championed several causes included opposition to [[racism]], the [[nuclear arms race]], and the [[Vietnam War]]. Key New Left organisations in New Zealand were the anti-[[Apartheid]] [[Halt All Racist Tours]] (HART), the Progressive Youth Movement (PYM), Socialist Forum, and the Resistance bookshops; which were organised locally. Unlike the Australian and American New Left groups, the Socialist Forum, PYM groups, and the Resistance bookshops were not university-based organisations but largely drew their support from working-class youth. The Wellington PYM consisted of a mixture of working-class youth and university students. Like the American New Left, the various PYM groups opposed the Vietnam War, racism, and Apartheid. While the New Zealand [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament (NZ)|Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]] (CND) was not a New Left organisation, several New Leftists including Graham Butterworth, Jim Delahunty, and Helmut Eionhorn of Wellington Socialist Forum also participated in the CND.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=120-122}}\n\nDuring the 1960s and 1970s, the New Left reached its heyday. HART, the PYM, and Resistance bookshops were joined by other groups including the [[University of Auckland|Auckland University]] Society for the Active Prevention of Cruelty to Politically Apathetic Humans (AUSAPOCHPAH), the Auckland-based Friends of Brutus, the New Left Club at [[Massey University]], the [[Victoria University of Wellington|Victoria University]] Socialist Club, the Anarchist Congress in Wellington, the Radical Student's Alliance at the [[University of Canterbury]], the [[Christchurch]]-based Anarchist Commune, the [[University of Otago]]'s Progressive Left Club, and the [[Dunedin]] Anarchist Army.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=123}} The activist, scholar, and [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand|Green Party]] Member of Parliament [[Sue Bradford]] was involved in the Auckland PYM and the Auckland Resistance bookshop.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=125}}{{sfn|Hope and Scott|205|p=552}}\n\nFollowing the election of the [[Third Labour Government of New Zealand|Third Labour Government]] in 1972, the new government delivered many of the New Left's demands including withdrawing New Zealand troops from Vietnam in 1972; ending [[Compulsory military training in New Zealand|compulsory military training]] that same year; and terminating sporting contact with South Africa. As a result, the New Left lost much of its prominence due to the winding down of the protest movement. While New Leftists were still active in radical politics such as the Resistance bookshops, the more liberal wing of the protest movement had largely been appeased by the Third Labour Government's policies.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=129}}\n\nDuring the early to mid 1970s, some New Left elements like the Christchurch PYM became influenced by the [[Maoism|Maoist]] Communist Party. One New Left group that emerged in 1974 was Murray Horton and [[Owen Wilkes]]' [[Campaign Against Foreign Control of Aotearoa]], which campaigned against foreign military bases and economic activity in New Zealand. According to Boraman, several New Leftists including former PYM members were also instrumental in founding several \"new social movements\" during the 1960s and 1970s including [[Tama Poata]]'s M\u0101ori Organisation on Human Rights (MOOHR), the [[Black Panthers]]&ndash;inspired [[Polynesian Panthers]], Therese O'Connell's Wellington Women's Liberation Front, the Auckland Women's Liberation Front, and the Auckland&ndash;based Women for Equality. Boraman has characterized opposition to [[American imperialism]] and uncritical praise for Communist states and figures like [[Mao Zedong]], [[Ho Chi Minh]], and [[Che Guevara]] as two key defining features of the later New Left activists and groups.{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n\n===Left-wing alternative media===\n[[File:Trotter, Chris (Alliance).jpg|left|175px|thumb|Chris Trotter, editor of the ''New Zealand Political Review''.]]\nDuring the early 20th century, the emergence of working-class consciousness led to the formation of several left-wing newspapers including ''The Maoriland  Worker'' (1910&ndash;1924), ''The Weekly Herald'', ''The Transport Worker'', and ''The New Zealand Watersider''. During the 1930s, they were joined by activist theatre companies, politically-engaged literary magazines, the Left Book Club, the Co-Operative Book Movement, and the Progressive Publishing Company. During the Great Depression, liberal-left perspectives penetrated mainstream New Zealand society through churches, women's groups, populist radio programmes, and the Labour Party.{{sfn|Hope and Scott|2015|p=546}}{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=41}}\n\nThe ''Maoriland Worker'' later revamped itself as the ''New Zealand Worker'' (1924&ndash;1935) and as the Labour Party's affiliated newspaper ''The Standard'' (1935&ndash;1959). While it was sympathetic to the Labour Party, the ''Maoriland Worker'' was a largely radical socialist publication that was independent of the Labour Party.{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=41}}  The various Communist parties also published their own newspapers. The CPNZ's official organ was the ''People's Voice'' (1939&ndash;1991), which reached a peak of 14,000 copies in 1945. The Socialist Unity Party's newspapers were the ''Tribune'' (1966&ndash;1995), ''Socialist Worker'' (1994&ndash;2005), ''The Spark'' (1991&ndash;2013), and ''Socialist Review'' (1997&ndash;present), and ''The Spark''{{'s}} successor ''Fightback'' (2013&ndash;present). The Socialist Action League's newspaper was ''Socialist Action'' (1969&ndash;1998), which reached a peak of 8,400 copies during the [[New Zealand general election, 1978|1978 general election]]. The Workers' Communist League's newspaper was called ''Unity'' (1978&ndash;1990).{{sfn|Gustafson|2004|p=29}}{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=37, 45}}\n\nSeveral notable independent socialist magazines and newspapers in New Zealand have included the ''New Zealand Monthly Review'' (''NZMR'', 1960&ndash;1996), ''The Republican'' (1974&ndash;1996), ''Race Gender Class'' (1985&ndash;1992), left-wing journalist [[Chris Trotter]]'s social democratic ''New Zealand Political Review'' (''NZPR'', 1992&ndash;2005),{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=64-65}} the feminist ''Broadsheet'' (1972&ndash;1997), the Peace Movement Aotearoa's ''Peacelink'', the queer feminist ''Bitches, Witches and Dykes'', the anti-apartheid ''HART News'', ''CARP Newsletter'', ''Foreign Control Watchdog'', and ''Peace Researcher''. Other independent left-wing publications have included the Marxist Publishing Group's ''Red Papers'' (1976&ndash;1979) ,''The Paper'' (1973&ndash;1975), and the Victoria University Socialist Club's ''Red Spark'' (1969&ndash;1970).{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=36-37, 44-45}}\n\n==Contemporary socialist parties, groups, and media in New Zealand==\nThere are around twenty political parties or organizations in New Zealand which follow socialist or communist policies. It is often difficult to gain a clear picture of socialist parties in New Zealand - mergers, splits, and re-namings leave the situation confused. In 2019 only Organise Aotearoa, the International Socialist Organisation, Socialist Aotearoa, the Canterbury Socialist Society, and the New Communist Party of Aotearoa hold regular public meetings and maintain regularly updated websites.\n\n===Modern parties and organizations===\n* '''[[Communist League (New Zealand)|Communist League]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established in 1969 as the \"Socialist Action League\". It has links to the [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|Socialist Workers Party]] of the USA. The Communist League had two candidates in the [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002 election]], but neither won their respective races. The League also stood candidates in the 2010 Auckland council election.\n*'''[[Communist Workers' Group (New Zealand)|Communist Workers' Group]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group. It was established in 1995 as a splinter group from the [[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]] organization. It is associated with the global [[Liaison Committee of Militants for a Revolutionary Communist International]] alliance, which itself was a split from the gobal alliance that Workers' Power belonged to. Their website is redrave.blogspot.co.nz.\n* Fightback - formerly the Workers Party, which was previously the Anti-Capitalist Alliance. Branches in Wellington and Auckland and a monthly publication. Some members have worked as organisers for Unite Union. Fightback publishes a monthly magazine by the same name.\n*'''[[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]]''' - a revolutionary [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group that is particularly active in universities. It briefly attempted to merge with the remnants of the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]], forming the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]. However, the majority of the group eventually rejected this decision and reestablished their own party but were now outside of the [[International Socialist Tendency]]. The ISO has fraternal relations with Socialist Alternative, in Australia, and the International Socialist Organisation, USA. Branches in Auckland, Wellington and Dunedin. Bi-monthly magazine called Socialist Review. \n*'''[[Organise Aotearoa]]''' \u2013 a revolutionary socialist group formed in 2016 and widely publicised in October 2018. Shortly after its public announcement, the organisation engaged in a series of [[direct action]] campaigns, including joining the blockade of New Zealand Defence Industry Association forums,<ref name=\"Organise Aotearoa\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1810/S00422/organise-aotearoa-to-join-opposition-to-the-weapons-expo.htm |title=Organise Aotearoa to join opposition to the Weapons Expo |date=2018-10-31 |publisher=Scoop News |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> occupying the [[Brazil]]ian embassy after the inauguration of [[Jair Bolsonaro]],<ref name=\"Protest of Brazilian embassy\">{{Cite web |url=https://thedailyblog.co.nz/2019/01/07/protest-of-brazilian-embassy-in-new-zealand-goes-viral-in-brazil-organise-aotearoa/ |title=Protest of Brazilian embassy in New Zealand goes viral in Brazil |date=2019-01-07 |publisher=The Daily BLog |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> occupying the [[United States]] consulate in Auckland during the [[2019 Venezuelan uprising|2019 Venezuelan coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], and joining the occupation of [[\u014ctuataua and Ihum\u0101tao|Ihum\u0101tao]]. The group has also organised broader mobilisations such as the 2018 protests agitating for [[Abortion in New Zealand|abortion reform]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://95bfm.com/bcast/i-v-w-organise-aotearoa-december-5-2018 |title=Interview with Organise Aotearoa |date=2018-12-05 |publisher=95.bFM |accessdate=2019-06-24}}</ref> As of June 2019, the organisation claims a membership of 272 active members. Branches in Auckland, Hamilton, Wellington, and Dunedin.\n*'''[[Permanent Revolution Group (New Zealand)|Permanent Revolution Group]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established as a breakaway from the [[Spartacist League (New Zealand)|Spartacist League]] (which later became the [[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]] organization). It is associated with the International Bolshevik Tendency.\n*'''[[Socialist Aotearoa]]''' - an [[Auckland]]-based group formed in May 2008 which split from [[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]] over disagreement with the organization's participation in the [[Residents Action Movement]] electoral coalition. The group has an eclectic mix of Trotskyists, anarchists, ecosocialists and various other ideologies in its ranks. Members are active in Unite Union, with one member, Joe Carolan, a senior organiser in that union.\n* '''[[Socialist Voice (New Zealand)|Socialist Voice]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group established in 2002. It is associated with the [[Committee for a Workers' International (1974)|Committee for a Workers' International]], and is therefore linked to the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party of England and Wales]].\n*'''[[Socialist Party of Aotearoa]]''' - a Marxist-Leninist group. It was founded in 1990 as a split from the [[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]], which was itself a split from the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]].\n\n===Defunct parties and organizations===\n\n*'''[[New Zealand Socialist Party]]''' (1901-1913) - an organization established in 1901. It should not be confused with the Socialist Party of New Zealand, a completely separate organization which is now known as the [[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]].\n* '''[[Communist Party of New Zealand]]''' (1921-1994) - an old communist group that initially gained a modest measure of success, but which later declined. The party became attached to [[Stalinism]], and when the [[Sino-Soviet split]] occurred, the party adopted [[Maoism]]. Later, after [[Mao Zedong|Mao]]'s death, it followed [[Enver Hoxha]], leader of [[Albania]] (which they considered to be the last bastion of true communism). After the fall of Albania, the party renounced all these ideologies and adopted [[Trotskyism]]. The party then attempted a merger with the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]], creating the [[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]. Most of the International Socialists eventually withdrew from this coalition, leaving the new Socialist Workers Organization dominated by the former Communist Party.\n* '''[[World Socialist Party of New Zealand]]''' (1930-??) - a group based primarily around opposition to [[Leninism]]. It was originally established in 1930 simply as the \"Socialist Party of New Zealand\", but later added \"world\" to its name. It is affiliated with the [[World Socialist Movement]].\n*'''[[Socialist Unity Party (New Zealand)|Socialist Unity Party]]''' (1966-1990) - a pro-Soviet party established by expelled members of the Communist Party. The Communist Party had been split between supporters of the Soviet Union and supporters of [[Mao Zedong]]'s China, and the pro-Soviet faction eventually lost. The Socialist Unity party survived until relatively recently, and maintained a relatively high level of influence in the trade union movement.\n* '''[[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]]''' (?-2012). A revolutionary socialist group aligned with the International Socialist Tendency. Formerly known as the Socialist Workers Organisation, the final conference of SW voted to dissolve itself at its conference in January 2012.\n* '''[[Workers Party of New Zealand]]''' (2002-2013) - The party was founded in 2002. It was originally formed by an electoral alliance of the original Workers' Party (pro-Mao, Marxist-Leninist) and the pro-Trotsky Revolution group. it is the first, and so far only, registered [[hard left]] political party under [[Mixed-member proportional representation|mixed-member proportional]] (MMP) representation.\n* Black Cat '''[[Anarchism in New Zealand#cite note-2|BlackCat Anarchist Collective]]''' - an [[anarcho-communism|anarcho-communist]] group based in the city of [[Auckland]].\n* '''[[Communist Party of Aotearoa]]''' - a [[Maoism|Maoist]] group that split from the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] in 1993, condemning that organization's abandonment of Maoism and adoption of [[Trotskyism]].\n* '''Revolutionary Communist League of New Zealand''' founded in 1984 by students and lecturers at the University of Canterbury in Christchurch. It was a revolutionary Marxist group affiliated with the [[United Secretariat of the Fourth International]]. After a few conferences, intending to rally opposition to [[Rogernomics]], RCLNZ organized a larger nationwide grouping called '''Socialist Alliance''' which stood a candidate in the 1987 general election. The RCLNZ was transformed into the '''Socialist Workers' Project''' in 1990, based in the ChCh Centre for Socialist Education.\n*'''[[New Zealand Marxian Association]]''' - a group established in 1918. It was founded to give endorsement and support to \"Marxian Revolutionist\" candidates in general elections.{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n* '''[[Organisation for Marxist Unity - New Zealand|Organisation for Marxist Unity]]''' - a [[Maoism|Maoist]] group.\n* '''[[Revolutionary Workers League (New Zealand)|Revolutionary Workers League]]''' - a merger of the pro-[[Mao Zedong|Mao]], [[Marxist-Leninist]] [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Workers' Party of New Zealand]] and the [[Revolution (NZ political group)|Revolution]] group. A tendency within the modern [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Workers' Party of New Zealand]].\n*'''[[Socialist Workers Organization (New Zealand)|Socialist Workers Organization]]''' - a revolutionary [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] party. It was established by the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]] and the [[International Socialist Organization (New Zealand)|International Socialist Organization]], although the majority of the latter group eventually withdrew from the merger. It was linked to the [[International Socialist Tendency]]. It evolved into the present day [[Socialist Worker (Aotearoa)]] group.\n*'''[[Workers' Party of New Zealand (pro-Mao, Marxist-Leninist)]]''' - A pro-[[Mao Zedong|Mao]], [[Marxist-Leninist]] party founded by Ray Nunes, formerly a prominent member of the [[Communist Party of New Zealand]]. The party joined the [[Workers Party of New Zealand|Anti-Capitalist Alliance]] (ACA), a radical-left electoral alliance, in 2002. The Workers' Party merged with [[Revolution (NZ political group)|Revolution]] to become the [[Revolutionary Workers League (New Zealand)|Revolutionary Workers' League]] in 2004.\n* '''[[Workers' Power (New Zealand)|Workers' Power]]''' - a [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] group formed in 1981 with links to the global Workers' Power entity. It later absorbed a group called the \"[[Communist Left (New Zealand)|Communist Left]]\". It is linked to the [[League for a Fifth International]].\n\n===Contemporary left-wing media===\nWith the advent of the Internet during the 1990s and early 21st century, left-wing print media gave way to online alternative media, which were cheaper to produce. Notable left-wing New Zealand blogs have included the independent Marxist collective \"Redline\", \"Against the Current\", [[Martyn \"Bomber\" Bradbury]]'s current affairs&ndash;oriented ''The Daily Blog'' (2012&ndash;present), and ''The Standard''. Besides blogs, left wing alternative media have also utilised email newsletters, publishing software, and major social media platforms like [[YouTube]], [[Facebook]], and [[Twitter]].{{sfn|Boraman|2016|p=67}}{{sfn|Hope and Scott|20175pp=551-553}}<ref>{{cite web |title=About |url=https://thestandard.org.nz/about/ |website=The Standard |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent figures in New Zealand socialism==\n*[[Martyn \"Bomber\" Bradbury]]{{sfn|Hope and Scott|20175pp=551-553}}\n*[[Sue Bradford]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|p=125}}\n*[[Peter Fraser]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Harry Holland]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Edward Hunter (Billy Banjo)|Edward Hunter]] (aka \"Billy Banjo\"){{sfn|Len Richardson|2002|pp=73-86}}\n*[[John A. Lee]]{{sfn|Franks and McAloon|2016|pp=106-114}}\n*[[Tama Poata]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n*[[Michael Joseph Savage]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Bob Semple]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=20}}\n*[[Chris Trotter]]{{sfn|Boraman|2016|pp=64-65}}\n*[[Owen Wilkes]]{{sfn|Boraman|2002|pp=129-131}}\n\n==Prominent figures in New Zealand communism==\n*[[Bill Andersen|George Harold (Bill) Andersen]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n*[[Ken Douglas]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n*[[Vic Wilcox]]{{sfn|Gustafson|2003|p=29}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Boraman |first=Tom |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=[[University of Otago]] Press|date=2002 |pages=117\u2013132 |chapter=Chapter 7: The New Left in New Zealand |isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Boraman |first1=Toby |title=The Independent Left Press and the Rise and Fall of Mass Dissent in Aotearoa since the 1970s |journal=Counterfutures |date=2016 |issue=1 |pages=31\u201370 |url=https://counterfutures.nz/1/boraman.pdf |accessdate=18 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Franks |first1=Peter |last2=McAloon |first2=Jim |title=Labour: The New Zealand Labour Party, 1916-2016 |date=2016 |publisher=[[Victoria University of Wellington|Victoria University]] Press |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]] |isbn=9781776560745 |url=https://vup.victoria.ac.nz/labour-the-new-zealand-labour-party-1916-2016/ |accessdate=16 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Gustafson|first=Barry |editor-last1=Trapeznik |editor-first1=Alexander |editor-last2=Fox |editor-first2=Aaron |title=Lenin's Legacy Down Under: New Zealand's Cold War |publisher=University of Otago Press |date=2004|pages=17\u201333 |chapter=Chapter 2: New Zealand in the Cold War World |isbn=1-877276-90-1}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hope |first1=Wayne |last2=Scott |first2=Jane |editor-last=Hayward |editor-first=Janine |title=New Zealand Government and Politics, Sixth Edition |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=28 May 2015 |pages=545\u2013555 |chapter=Chapter 8.5: Left political activism|isbn=9780195585254 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/new-zealand-government-and-politics-9780195585254?cc=nz&lang=en& |accessdate=25 September 2019}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Milburn |first1=Josephine F. |title=Socialism and Social Reform in Nineteenth-Century New Zealand |journal=Political Science |date=1960 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=62\u201370}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Newell |first1=Peter E. |url=http://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2000s/2004/no-1203-november-2004/marxian-socialism-new-zealand|title=Marxian Socialism in New Zealand|newspaper=[[Socialist Standard]]|date=November 2004|accessdate=26 March 2018}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Olssen |first1=Erik |title=W.T. Mills, E.J.B. Allen, J.A. Lee, and Socialism in New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1976 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013119 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=1408&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Len |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=University of Otago Press |date=2002|pages=73\u201386 |chapter=Chapter 4: 'Billy Banjo: Coalminer, Socialist, Poet and Novelist |isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Kerry |title='Our Motto, No Compromise': The Ideological Origins and Foundation of the Communist Party of New Zealand |journal=New Zealand Journal of History |date=1994 |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=160\u2013177 |url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/document.php?wid=712&action=null |accessdate=17 September 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last=Taylor|first=Kerry |editor-last1=Moloney |editor-first1=Pat |editor-last2=Taylor |editor-first2=Kerry |title=On the Left: Essays on Socialism in New Zealand |publisher=University of Otago Press|date=2002 |pages=103\u2013115 |chapter=Chapter 6: 'Potential Allies of the Working Class': The Communist Party of New Zealand and Maori, 1921-1952|isbn=1-877276-19-7}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.broadleft.org/nz.htm Leftist Parties of New Zealand] - contains links and statistics for left-wing (not necessarily socialist/communist) parties in New Zealand. Includes links to most parties mentioned above.\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Socialist states}}\n{{Oceania in topic|Socialism in}}\n\n[[Category:Socialism in New Zealand| ]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socialism_in_New_Zealand"}
