 society]]\n", "name_user": "Myasuda", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternment and redress:paragraph break; c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_Americans"}
{"title_page": "Randy Baumgardner", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Randy Baumgardner\n| image              = Randy Baumgardner.JPG\n| image_size         = 225px\n| image_upright      =\n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Baumgardner in 2018.\n|state_senate = Colorado\n|district     = [[Colorado's 8th Senate district|8th]]\n|term_start   = January 15, 2013\n|term_end     = January 21, 2019\n|predecessor  = [[Jean White (Colorado legislator)|Jean White]]\n|successor    = [[Bob Rankin]]\n|state_house1 = Colorado\n|district1    = 57th\n|term_start1  = January 7, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 9, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Al White (politician)|Al White]]\n|successor1   = [[Bob Rankin]] \n|birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bedford, Indiana|Bedford]], [[Indiana]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lori Baumgardner\n}}\n\n'''Randy Baumgardner''' is a former legislator in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. Elected to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] in 2008, he won election to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2012. He represented [[Colorado's 8th Senate district|Senate District 8]], which encompasses Garfield, Grand, Jackson, Moffat, Rio Blanco, Routt, and Summit Counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ashby |first=Charles |date=2019-01-23 |title=Rankin becomes a state senator |url=https://www.gjsentinel.com/news/western_colorado/rankin-becomes-a-state-senator/article_5359d4e2-1ed8-11e9-a37f-10604b9f7e7c.html |work=The Daily Sentinel |location= |access-date=2019-01-23 }}</ref>  In the 2015 legislative session he served as the Majority Whip for the Senate Republican caucus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradosenaterepublicans.com/senator_randy_baumgardner|title=Senator Randy Baumgardner|first=Uselabs|last=(http://uselabs.com)|publisher=}}</ref> He resigned on January 19, 2019.\n\nBaumgardner was an unsuccessful candidate for U. S. Senate;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/07/07/randy-baumgardner-kicks-off-u-s-senate-campaign-friday-against-mark-udall/98072/|title=Randy Baumgardner to kick off U.S. Senate campaign Friday against Mark Udall|date=7 July 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> the  [[United States Senate election in Colorado, 2014|Republican primary]] was held on June 24, 2014.\n\n==Biography and early career==\n\nBaumgardner was born in Bedford, Indiana in 1956. He worked for the Colorado Department of Transportation for a decade before running for public office. He continues to own and operate a ranch with his wife, near Granby.\n\n==Colorado House of Representatives==\n\n===2008 election===\n\nBaumgardner defeated Daniel L. Korkowski in the contested Republican primary in August, taking 67 percent of votes cast.<ref name=\"prim08\">{{cite web |url=http://rs.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=syj1hm55hso5ty55pcuhyprg&ControlID=a61fb386-685c-4a0c-a691-71334ad539d8&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=ClientControllerdnn_ctr370_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&EnableFindNext=False&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 Primary Election |accessdate=2008-11-08 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBaumgardner faced Democrat Todd Hagenbuch in the November 2008 general election. Baumgardner's candidacy was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]'',<ref name=\"dphouse\">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}\n</ref> and he won election with 57 percent of the popular vote.<ref name=\"gen08\">{{cite web |url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\n\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Baumgardner was named to the House Education Committee and the House Transportation and Energy Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/Clics/CLICS2009A/csljournals.nsf/(jouhse)/0475167CD03000CB8725752E0056A5B3/$FILE/Jn07.pdf |title=House Journal - January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-09 |format=pdf |work=Colorado General Assembly }}</ref><ref name=\"cmte09\">\n{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 |access-date=May 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231125753/http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node%2F92 |archive-date=December 31, 2014 |url-status=dead|df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> Citing concerns over water rights filings on the Western Slope, Baumgarder also sought a seat on the House Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resources Committee.<ref name=\"shale\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=Oil shale a hot topic at Capitol |url=http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2009/jan/17/oil_shale_hot_topic_capitol/ |work=[[Steamboat Pilot & Today]]|date=17 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nBaumgardner proposed legislation to redirect a portion of federal mineral lease revenues from local governments to state road and bridge projects for a period of ten years,<ref name=\"newlegbill\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=1st-year legislator introduces bill |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/12/1styear_legislator_introduces_bill/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"dola\">{{cite news |first=Collin |last=Smith |title=City Council: DOLA, festival present financial issues |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/15/city_council_dola_festival_present_financial_issue/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"billboost\">{{cite news |first=Brandon |last=Gee |title=Rep. Baumgardner\u2019s bill could boost county mineral lease funds |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/29/rep_baumgardner_bill_could_boost_county_mineral_le/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-04-20 }}</ref> The measure was criticized for altering recently negotiated revenue formulas, and was watered down in the House Agriculture Committee.<ref name=\"baumwaterbill\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason  |title=Baumgardner bill gains agriculture committee support |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/31/baumgardner_bill_gains_agriculture_committee_suppo/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 }}</ref> Baumgardner also offered legislation to modify the permitting process for [[coal pollution mitigation]] operations, a measure which died in a House committee.<ref name=\"cleancoal\">{{cite news |first=Brandon |last=Gee |title=State budget deficit could cause slash in tourism spending |url=http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2009/feb/01/state_budget_deficit_could_cause_slash_tourism_spe/ |work=[[Steamboat Pilot & Today]]|date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n===2010 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name= Baumgardner\n|Year=2010\n|Bill Number 1=HB10-1223\n|Bill Number 2=HB10-1232\n|Bill Number 3=HB10-1275\n|Bill Number 4=SB10-033\n|Bill Number 5=SB10-075\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/41B0D382751EB7AC872576B00069C8FD?Open&file=1223_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/31AA863FDE1DEF9F872576B100784036?Open&file=1232_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A1501B3195D0CA66872576A80026BA53?Open&file=1275_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/31FA79951C3288B0872576A80027B4CC?Open&file=033_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/282CDEBD976657CD872576AA006979FA?Open&file=075_enr.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 5= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the continuation of the Forestry Advisory Board. \n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the definition of school vehicles.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning a requirement that the location of a private burial be recorded.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning the verification of the work eligibility status of new employees through the federal electronic verification program.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning the requirement that military vehicles valued for historical purposes bear a license plate.\n}}\nIn 2010, Baumgardner co-sponsored SB10-033. This measure concerned a verification program of a worker\u2019s eligibility in Colorado. SB10-033 was co-sponsored by Senator Schultheis. It was assigned to the State Senate, Veterans, and Military Affairs committee, where it was ultimately defeated.\n\n===2010 election===\nIn the 2010 election, Baumgardner ran for re-election. He faced no opposition in the primary election, but faced Steve Ivanice of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and Mike Kien of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] during the general election, before defeating both with 64% of the vote.<ref name=\"2010electionresults\">{{cite news |url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-house/2010/|title = Colorado State House 2010 Election Results | accessdate=2012-11-13 | work=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\n===2011 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name= Baumgardner\n|Year=2011\n|Bill Number 1=HB11-1107\n|Bill Number 2=HB11-1170\n|Bill Number 3=HB11-1308\n|Bill Number 4=HB11-1309\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/04129893206CB6DF8725781800719F17?Open&file=1107_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/972C4F68BF6FEFDE872578160059B558?Open&file=1170_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9C6DCC1E81C092D587257878007AEFE0?Open&file=1308_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/8583D0A1A3A14641872578780077DC85?Open&file=1309_ren.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee. \n|Bill Title 1=Concerning enforcement of illegal immigration violations. \n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the extension of the availability of the income tax credit related to alternative fuel refueling facilities.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the distribution of federal mineral leasing revenues related to naval oil shale reserves to affected counties in Colorado.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning enactment of the \"Unauthorized Employment Act\". \n}}\n\nDuring the 2011 legislative session, Baumgardner focused on several important bills regarding illegal immigration and mining. A major piece of legislation he worked on was his efforts in trying to extend an income tax credit for alternative fuel refueling facilities. The bill was initially sent to the House committee on Agriculture, Livestock, and Natural Resources, before being passed on to the House Finance committee, where it was laid over until the end of session.\n\n===2012 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Baumgardner\n|Year=2012\n|Bill Number 1=HB12-1014\n|Bill Number 2=HB12-1160\n|Bill Number 3=SB12-025\n|Bill Number 4=SB12-031\n|Bill Number 5=SB12-050\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/EEC8D607786A111D87257981007DC70D?Open&file=1014_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D049AE35980E1D9287257981007DB584?Open&file=1160_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/192D8885E8DFA02187257981007F190E?Open&file=025_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/37EBC4BD9B890E6587257981007DD3C5?Open&file=031_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9739E830170EB37287257981007F0F98?Open&file=050_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 2=Laid over indefinitely on Senate calendar\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Governor [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1= Concerning a modification of the fee for late registration of a vehicle.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning methane gas captured from active and inactive coal mines.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the authority of a law-abiding person to carry a concealed handgun without a permit.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning federal mineral lease districts.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning the elimination of the use of automated vehicle identification systems for traffic law enforcement.\n}}\n\nIn 2012, one of the major bills that Baumgardner sponsored was HB12-1160. This bill, co-sponsored by Senator Schwartz, focused on adding coal mine methane gas as an eligible energy resource under Colorado\u2019s renewable energy portfolio. This bill was introduced into the House where it passed before being sent to the Senate. HB12-1160 also passed through its Senate committee, before being laid over daily through the end of session, therefore failing to pass.\n\n==Colorado State Senate==\n\n===2012 election===\nBaumgardner decided to run for higher office by putting in his bid for the State Senate District 8 seat in 2012. He faced [[incumbent]] Republican [[Jean White (Colorado legislator)|Jean White]] in the primary race, which the [[Denver Post]] described as \"nasty\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/07/07/randy-baumgardner-kicks-off-u-s-senate-campaign-friday-against-mark-udall/98072/|title=Randy Baumgardner to kick off U.S. Senate campaign Friday against Mark Udall|date=7 July 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> White was attacked by outside interest groups for her support for civil unions. Baumgardner was criticised for falling asleep during a House session and also faced revelations that an unregistered sex offender lived at his house and worked on his farm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_20794256/ugly-campaign-fliers-hit-northwestern-colorado-state-senate|title=Ugly campaign fliers hit in northwestern Colorado state Senate race|date=16 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_20870155/unregistered-sex-offender-lives-at-home-colorado-lawmaker|title=Unregistered sex offender lives at home of Colorado lawmaker|date=16 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> Nevertheless, Baumgardner won the Republican nomination, taking 58% of the vote.<ref name=\"2012primary\">{{cite news |title=Baumgardner tops White in GOP state Senate primary |url= http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20120626/NEWS/120629847\n|work=Summit Daily |date=June 26, 2012 |accessdate=2012-11-09 }}</ref> \n\nWhite refused to endorse him, saying \"I'll have a hard time supporting a dishonest man. The lies prevailed. His lies beat my truth. It shows that running an upright and honest campaign doesn't necessarily win the day. This is a man who lied to me. He lied about me. He lied about where he lives, what he does and how he votes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2012/06/26/sen-jean-white-lies-beat-truth/75045/|title=Sen. Jean White: \"His lies beat my truth\"|date=26 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> During the general election, Baumgardner defeated his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent Emily Tracy with 51.1% of the vote.<ref name=\"2012general\">{{cite news |url=http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2012/| title = Colorado State Senate 2012 Election Results | work = Denver Post |accessdate = 2014-02-26 }}</ref>\n\n===2013 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=Baumgardner\n|Year=2013\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Number 6=\n|Bill Link 1=\n|Bill Link 2= \n|Bill Link 3= \n|Bill Link 4= \n|Bill Link 5= \n|Bill Link 6= \n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2= \n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Status 6=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5=\n|Bill Title 6= \n}}\n\nSenator Baumgardner was elected to be the Majority Whip and appointed to serve on the Senate Business, Labor, and Technology Committee, Vice Chair of the Capital Development Committee, and Chair of the Transportation Committee. He also serves on the Colorado Tourism Board, Water Resources Review Committee, The Economic Vitality Caucus and Sportsmens' Caucus.\n\n===2017 Legislative Session===\n\n'''Senator Baumgardner''' is the chairman of the Senate Transportation Committee, and the vice-chairman of the Senate Agriculture, Natural Resources and Energy Committee, as well as the Capitol Development Committee.\n\nHe sponsored the following bills. He ran '''Senate Bill 243'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb17-243|title=Continue Motorcycle Operator Safety Training Program - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> to continue the Motorcycle Operators Safety Training (MOST) program and '''House Bill 1105,'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb17-1105|title=Vehicle Titling And Registration Inspection Requirements - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> which simplifies the vehicle registration system. '''Senate Bill 30'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb17-030|title=Exempt Injectable Anabolic Steroids For Cattle - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> was an agricultural bill designed to make it easier for ranchers to administer anabolic steroid shots to their cattle.\n\n===2018 Legislative Session===\n\nDuring the 2018 Legislative Session, Senator Baumgardner focused on broader, statewide issues. He was the prime sponsor of Senate Bill 41,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-041|title=Authorize Water Use Incidental Sand And Gravel Mines - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> concerning water used in gravel production. He sponsored Senate Bill 1,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-001|title=Transportation Infrastructure Funding - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> which would increase funding for road and bridge repair. This bill would allocate $250 billion to fix roads over the next 20 years. SB 1 also requires a percentage of the money to be spent on repairing roads in smaller counties with fewer than 50,000 people.<ref>https://leg.colorado.gov/sites/default/files/documents/2018A/bills/fn/2018a_sb001_r7.pdf</ref>\n\n===Resignation===\nBaumgardner was investigated twice for grabbing a staffers buttocks, making inappropriate comments and creating a hostile work environment for five others.  Each time he was recommended for expulsion, but the motions failed on a 17 to 17 vote.<ref>{{cite news | publisher = thehill.com | date = April 3, 2018 | title = Colorado state Senate votes against expelling GOP lawmaker accused of groping aide | author = LUIS SANCHEZ | url = https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/381381-colorado-state-senate-votes-against-expelling-gop-lawmaker-accused-of}}</ref> Baumgardner was investigated a third time by an independent investigator who found the charges were credible. When we was denied committee positions by the Republican majority, he resigned before a third expulsion vote could be held.<ref>{{cite news | publisher = cpr.org | date = December 18, 2018 | title =  Sen. Randy Baumgardner, Center Of Several Sexual Harassment Allegations, Resigns | author =  Bente Birkeland | url = https://www.cpr.org/2018/12/18/sen-randy-baumgardner-center-of-several-sexual-harassment-allegations-resigns/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | publisher = denverpost.com | date = December 17, 2018 | title =  Colorado Sen. Randy Baumgardner stepping down after beating expulsion vote, Republican was accused of slapping and grabbing a legislative aide | author = NIC GARCIA, The Denver Post | url =https://www.denverpost.com/2018/12/17/randy-baumgardner-retiring/ }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.randybaumgardner.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/randy-l-baumgardner Colorado General Assembly Website]\n* [http://coloradosenatenews.com/ Colorado Senate News]\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart= | fec=C00546838 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Randy_Baumgardner Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Randy_Baumgardner.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* -->\n*{{C-SPAN|RandyBaumgardner}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baumgardner, Randy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Randy Baumgardner\n| image              = Randy Baumgardner.JPG\n| image_size         = 225px\n| image_upright      =\n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Baumgardner in 2018.\n|state_senate = Colorado\n|district     = [[Colorado's 8th Senate district|8th]]\n|term_start   = January 15, 2013\n|term_end     = January 21, 2019\n|predecessor  = [[Jean White (Colorado legislator)|Jean White]]\n|successor    = [[Bob Rankin]]\n|state_house1 = Colorado\n|district1    = 57th\n|term_start1  = January 7, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 9, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Al White (politician)|Al White]]\n|successor1   = [[Bob Rankin]] \n|birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bedford, Indiana|Bedford]], [[Indiana]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lori Baumgardner\n}}\n\n'''Randy Baumgardner''' is a former legislator in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. Elected to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] in 2008, he won election to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2012. He represented [[Colorado's 8th Senate district|Senate District 8]], which encompasses Garfield, Grand, Jackson, Moffat, Rio Blanco, Routt, and Summit Counties, until his resignation on January 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ashby |first=Charles |date=2019-01-23 |title=Rankin becomes a state senator |url=https://www.gjsentinel.com/news/western_colorado/rankin-becomes-a-state-senator/article_5359d4e2-1ed8-11e9-a37f-10604b9f7e7c.html |work=The Daily Sentinel |location= |access-date=2019-01-23 }}</ref>  In the 2015 legislative session he served as the Majority Whip for the Senate Republican caucus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradosenaterepublicans.com/senator_randy_baumgardner|title=Senator Randy Baumgardner|first=Uselabs|last=(http://uselabs.com)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBaumgardner was an unsuccessful candidate for U. S. Senate;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/07/07/randy-baumgardner-kicks-off-u-s-senate-campaign-friday-against-mark-udall/98072/|title=Randy Baumgardner to kick off U.S. Senate campaign Friday against Mark Udall|date=7 July 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> the  [[United States Senate election in Colorado, 2014|Republican primary]] was held on June 24, 2014.\n\n==Biography and early career==\n\nBaumgardner was born in Bedford, Indiana in 1956. He worked for the Colorado Department of Transportation for a decade before running for public office. He continues to own and operate a ranch with his wife, near Granby.\n\n==Colorado House of Representatives==\n\n===2008 election===\n\nBaumgardner defeated Daniel L. Korkowski in the contested Republican primary in August, taking 67 percent of votes cast.<ref name=\"prim08\">{{cite web |url=http://rs.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=syj1hm55hso5ty55pcuhyprg&ControlID=a61fb386-685c-4a0c-a691-71334ad539d8&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=ClientControllerdnn_ctr370_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&EnableFindNext=False&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 Primary Election |accessdate=2008-11-08 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBaumgardner faced Democrat Todd Hagenbuch in the November 2008 general election. Baumgardner's candidacy was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]'',<ref name=\"dphouse\">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}\n</ref> and he won election with 57 percent of the popular vote.<ref name=\"gen08\">{{cite web |url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\n\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Baumgardner was named to the House Education Committee and the House Transportation and Energy Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/Clics/CLICS2009A/csljournals.nsf/(jouhse)/0475167CD03000CB8725752E0056A5B3/$FILE/Jn07.pdf |title=House Journal - January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-09 |format=pdf |work=Colorado General Assembly }}</ref><ref name=\"cmte09\">\n{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 |access-date=May 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231125753/http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node%2F92 |archive-date=December 31, 2014 |url-status=dead|df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> Citing concerns over water rights filings on the Western Slope, Baumgarder also sought a seat on the House Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resources Committee.<ref name=\"shale\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=Oil shale a hot topic at Capitol |url=http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2009/jan/17/oil_shale_hot_topic_capitol/ |work=[[Steamboat Pilot & Today]]|date=17 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nBaumgardner proposed legislation to redirect a portion of federal mineral lease revenues from local governments to state road and bridge projects for a period of ten years,<ref name=\"newlegbill\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=1st-year legislator introduces bill |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/12/1styear_legislator_introduces_bill/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"dola\">{{cite news |first=Collin |last=Smith |title=City Council: DOLA, festival present financial issues |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/15/city_council_dola_festival_present_financial_issue/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"billboost\">{{cite news |first=Brandon |last=Gee |title=Rep. Baumgardner\u2019s bill could boost county mineral lease funds |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/29/rep_baumgardner_bill_could_boost_county_mineral_le/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-04-20 }}</ref> The measure was criticized for altering recently negotiated revenue formulas, and was watered down in the House Agriculture Committee.<ref name=\"baumwaterbill\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason  |title=Baumgardner bill gains agriculture committee support |url=http://www.craigdailypress.com/news/2009/jan/31/baumgardner_bill_gains_agriculture_committee_suppo/ |work=Craig Daily Press |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 }}</ref> Baumgardner also offered legislation to modify the permitting process for [[coal pollution mitigation]] operations, a measure which died in a House committee.<ref name=\"cleancoal\">{{cite news |first=Brandon |last=Gee |title=State budget deficit could cause slash in tourism spending |url=http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2009/feb/01/state_budget_deficit_could_cause_slash_tourism_spe/ |work=[[Steamboat Pilot & Today]]|date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n===2010 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name= Baumgardner\n|Year=2010\n|Bill Number 1=HB10-1223\n|Bill Number 2=HB10-1232\n|Bill Number 3=HB10-1275\n|Bill Number 4=SB10-033\n|Bill Number 5=SB10-075\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/41B0D382751EB7AC872576B00069C8FD?Open&file=1223_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/31AA863FDE1DEF9F872576B100784036?Open&file=1232_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A1501B3195D0CA66872576A80026BA53?Open&file=1275_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/31FA79951C3288B0872576A80027B4CC?Open&file=033_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/282CDEBD976657CD872576AA006979FA?Open&file=075_enr.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 5= Signed by Governor [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the continuation of the Forestry Advisory Board. \n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the definition of school vehicles.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning a requirement that the location of a private burial be recorded.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning the verification of the work eligibility status of new employees through the federal electronic verification program.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning the requirement that military vehicles valued for historical purposes bear a license plate.\n}}\nIn 2010, Baumgardner co-sponsored SB10-033. This measure concerned a verification program of a worker\u2019s eligibility in Colorado. SB10-033 was co-sponsored by Senator Schultheis. It was assigned to the State Senate, Veterans, and Military Affairs committee, where it was ultimately defeated.\n\n===2010 election===\nIn the 2010 election, Baumgardner ran for re-election. He faced no opposition in the primary election, but faced Steve Ivanice of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and Mike Kien of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] during the general election, before defeating both with 64% of the vote.<ref name=\"2010electionresults\">{{cite news |url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-house/2010/|title = Colorado State House 2010 Election Results | accessdate=2012-11-13 | work=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\n===2011 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name= Baumgardner\n|Year=2011\n|Bill Number 1=HB11-1107\n|Bill Number 2=HB11-1170\n|Bill Number 3=HB11-1308\n|Bill Number 4=HB11-1309\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/04129893206CB6DF8725781800719F17?Open&file=1107_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/972C4F68BF6FEFDE872578160059B558?Open&file=1170_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9C6DCC1E81C092D587257878007AEFE0?Open&file=1308_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/8583D0A1A3A14641872578780077DC85?Open&file=1309_ren.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee.\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee. \n|Bill Title 1=Concerning enforcement of illegal immigration violations. \n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the extension of the availability of the income tax credit related to alternative fuel refueling facilities.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the distribution of federal mineral leasing revenues related to naval oil shale reserves to affected counties in Colorado.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning enactment of the \"Unauthorized Employment Act\". \n}}\n\nDuring the 2011 legislative session, Baumgardner focused on several important bills regarding illegal immigration and mining. A major piece of legislation he worked on was his efforts in trying to extend an income tax credit for alternative fuel refueling facilities. The bill was initially sent to the House committee on Agriculture, Livestock, and Natural Resources, before being passed on to the House Finance committee, where it was laid over until the end of session.\n\n===2012 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Baumgardner\n|Year=2012\n|Bill Number 1=HB12-1014\n|Bill Number 2=HB12-1160\n|Bill Number 3=SB12-025\n|Bill Number 4=SB12-031\n|Bill Number 5=SB12-050\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/EEC8D607786A111D87257981007DC70D?Open&file=1014_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D049AE35980E1D9287257981007DB584?Open&file=1160_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/192D8885E8DFA02187257981007F190E?Open&file=025_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/37EBC4BD9B890E6587257981007DD3C5?Open&file=031_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9739E830170EB37287257981007F0F98?Open&file=050_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 2=Laid over indefinitely on Senate calendar\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Governor [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1= Concerning a modification of the fee for late registration of a vehicle.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning methane gas captured from active and inactive coal mines.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the authority of a law-abiding person to carry a concealed handgun without a permit.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning federal mineral lease districts.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning the elimination of the use of automated vehicle identification systems for traffic law enforcement.\n}}\n\nIn 2012, one of the major bills that Baumgardner sponsored was HB12-1160. This bill, co-sponsored by Senator Schwartz, focused on adding coal mine methane gas as an eligible energy resource under Colorado\u2019s renewable energy portfolio. This bill was introduced into the House where it passed before being sent to the Senate. HB12-1160 also passed through its Senate committee, before being laid over daily through the end of session, therefore failing to pass.\n\n==Colorado State Senate==\n\n===2012 election===\nBaumgardner decided to run for higher office by putting in his bid for the State Senate District 8 seat in 2012. He faced [[incumbent]] Republican [[Jean White (Colorado legislator)|Jean White]] in the primary race, which the [[Denver Post]] described as \"nasty\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/07/07/randy-baumgardner-kicks-off-u-s-senate-campaign-friday-against-mark-udall/98072/|title=Randy Baumgardner to kick off U.S. Senate campaign Friday against Mark Udall|date=7 July 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> White was attacked by outside interest groups for her support for civil unions. Baumgardner was criticised for falling asleep during a House session and also faced revelations that an unregistered sex offender lived at his house and worked on his farm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_20794256/ugly-campaign-fliers-hit-northwestern-colorado-state-senate|title=Ugly campaign fliers hit in northwestern Colorado state Senate race|date=16 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_20870155/unregistered-sex-offender-lives-at-home-colorado-lawmaker|title=Unregistered sex offender lives at home of Colorado lawmaker|date=16 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> Nevertheless, Baumgardner won the Republican nomination, taking 58% of the vote.<ref name=\"2012primary\">{{cite news |title=Baumgardner tops White in GOP state Senate primary |url= http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20120626/NEWS/120629847\n|work=Summit Daily |date=June 26, 2012 |accessdate=2012-11-09 }}</ref> \n\nWhite refused to endorse him, saying \"I'll have a hard time supporting a dishonest man. The lies prevailed. His lies beat my truth. It shows that running an upright and honest campaign doesn't necessarily win the day. This is a man who lied to me. He lied about me. He lied about where he lives, what he does and how he votes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2012/06/26/sen-jean-white-lies-beat-truth/75045/|title=Sen. Jean White: \"His lies beat my truth\"|date=26 June 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|work=Denver Post|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> During the general election, Baumgardner defeated his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent Emily Tracy with 51.1% of the vote.<ref name=\"2012general\">{{cite news |url=http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2012/| title = Colorado State Senate 2012 Election Results | work = Denver Post |accessdate = 2014-02-26 }}</ref>\n\n===2013 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=Baumgardner\n|Year=2013\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Number 6=\n|Bill Link 1=\n|Bill Link 2= \n|Bill Link 3= \n|Bill Link 4= \n|Bill Link 5= \n|Bill Link 6= \n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2= \n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Status 6=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5=\n|Bill Title 6= \n}}\n\nSenator Baumgardner was elected to be the Majority Whip and appointed to serve on the Senate Business, Labor, and Technology Committee, Vice Chair of the Capital Development Committee, and Chair of the Transportation Committee. He also serves on the Colorado Tourism Board, Water Resources Review Committee, The Economic Vitality Caucus and Sportsmens' Caucus.\n\n===2017 Legislative Session===\n\n'''Senator Baumgardner''' is the chairman of the Senate Transportation Committee, and the vice-chairman of the Senate Agriculture, Natural Resources and Energy Committee, as well as the Capitol Development Committee.\n\nHe sponsored the following bills. He ran '''Senate Bill 243'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb17-243|title=Continue Motorcycle Operator Safety Training Program - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> to continue the Motorcycle Operators Safety Training (MOST) program and '''House Bill 1105,'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb17-1105|title=Vehicle Titling And Registration Inspection Requirements - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> which simplifies the vehicle registration system. '''Senate Bill 30'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb17-030|title=Exempt Injectable Anabolic Steroids For Cattle - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> was an agricultural bill designed to make it easier for ranchers to administer anabolic steroid shots to their cattle.\n\n===2018 Legislative Session===\n\nDuring the 2018 Legislative Session, Senator Baumgardner focused on broader, statewide issues. He was the prime sponsor of Senate Bill 41,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-041|title=Authorize Water Use Incidental Sand And Gravel Mines - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> concerning water used in gravel production. He sponsored Senate Bill 1,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-001|title=Transportation Infrastructure Funding - Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov}}</ref> which would increase funding for road and bridge repair. This bill would allocate $250 billion to fix roads over the next 20 years. SB 1 also requires a percentage of the money to be spent on repairing roads in smaller counties with fewer than 50,000 people.<ref>https://leg.colorado.gov/sites/default/files/documents/2018A/bills/fn/2018a_sb001_r7.pdf</ref>\n\n===Resignation===\nBaumgardner was investigated twice for grabbing a staffers buttocks, making inappropriate comments and creating a hostile work environment for five others.  Each time he was recommended for expulsion, but the motions failed on a 17 to 17 vote.<ref>{{cite news | publisher = thehill.com | date = April 3, 2018 | title = Colorado state Senate votes against expelling GOP lawmaker accused of groping aide | author = LUIS SANCHEZ | url = https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/381381-colorado-state-senate-votes-against-expelling-gop-lawmaker-accused-of}}</ref> Baumgardner was investigated a third time by an independent investigator who found the charges were credible. When we was denied committee positions by the Republican majority, he resigned before a third expulsion vote could be held.<ref>{{cite news | publisher = cpr.org | date = December 18, 2018 | title =  Sen. Randy Baumgardner, Center Of Several Sexual Harassment Allegations, Resigns | author =  Bente Birkeland | url = https://www.cpr.org/2018/12/18/sen-randy-baumgardner-center-of-several-sexual-harassment-allegations-resigns/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | publisher = denverpost.com | date = December 17, 2018 | title =  Colorado Sen. Randy Baumgardner stepping down after beating expulsion vote, Republican was accused of slapping and grabbing a legislative aide | author = NIC GARCIA, The Denver Post | url =https://www.denverpost.com/2018/12/17/randy-baumgardner-retiring/ }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.randybaumgardner.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/randy-l-baumgardner Colorado General Assembly Website]\n* [http://coloradosenatenews.com/ Colorado Senate News]\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart= | fec=C00546838 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Randy_Baumgardner Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Randy_Baumgardner.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* -->\n*{{C-SPAN|RandyBaumgardner}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baumgardner, Randy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Johnsagent", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randy_Baumgardner"}
